<FIRST>r a AM-SmithDinner     10-19 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smith Dinner,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Addresses Annual Fund-Raiser</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush on Thursday night
contradicted a published report that she weighs 135 pounds.
   ``George said the press never gets anything right,'' Mrs. Bush
said. ``Just for starters, I was born weighing 135 pounds.''
   Mrs. Bush addressed the 44th annual Alfred E. Smith Memorial
Dinner, a fund-raiser that has been called the city's most famous
non-political political event.
   Approximately 1,350 guests gathered in the Waldorf-Astoria
hotel's Grand Ballroom, where they dined on filet mignon and
chocolate hazelnut torte at $500 a plate.
   After straightening out the weight question, Mrs. Bush paused,
then handed outgoing Mayor Edward I. Koch, who was also on the
dais, one of his own lines.
   ``How'm I doing, Ed?''
   Mrs. Bush, wearing a black and purple gown with her
characteristic pearl choker, said she welcomed the chance ``to
prove I'm more than just a pretty face.''
   The glittering and often controversial Al Smith dinner always
draws an array of politicians and other notables, often held
shortly before a major election, though political hatchets are
supposed to be buried for the night.
   The first lady said she loved Tom Wolfe's satirical look at New
York politics and race relations, ``The Bonfire of the Vanities.''
   ``But I never dreamed I'd get to address some of the characters
in person,'' she said to cheers.
   This year's event drew the top contenders for City Hall,
Democrat David Dinkins and Republican Rudolph Giuliani, who sat two
seats apart on the dais and who, according to Giuliani, shook hands.
   At last year's dinner, then-Vice President George Bush and his
presidential opponent, Democrat Michael S. Dukakis, traded
witticisms just weeks before Bush won the race for the White House.
   Also in attendance Thursday were Alfred E. Smith IV, the master
of ceremonies; Gov. Mario Cuomo; New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean; state
Attorney General Robert Abrams; Fire Commissioner Joseph Bruno;
outgoing Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward and Cardinal John J.
O'Connor.
   The Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York has sponsored the
annual event since its inception in 1945, a year after Smith died.
The proceeds always go to health care causes.
   Smith, governor of New York from 1923-1928, in 1928 became the
first Catholic to be nominated for president.
   Past speakers have included John F. Kennedy, the first Catholic
elected president. Other speakers have been Winston S. Churchill,
Dwight D. Eisenhower, Lyndon B. Johnson, Danny Thomas, Bob Hope and
Kurt Waldheim.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
