<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--TeacherBeating     10-19 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Teacher Beating,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Exonerates Teacher In Beating of Pupil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court dismissed charges against a
teacher who whipped a 12-year-old boy so badly he had to be
hospitalized for six weeks, saying she did it help him improve his
grades, a newspaper reported today.
   The Korea Times said a court in the southern city of Taegu
dismissed assault charges this week against Kim Mi-kyong, 24, who
had been arrested for injuring the pupil.
   The teacher beat Park Kyong-jin with a stick because he had not
done well on a science test, the report said. The boy's back was
dislocated by the beating and was in the hospital for six weeks, it
said.
   The court ruled that corporal punishment was a necessary form of
discipline in schools and Miss Kim could not be charged with a
crime, the report said. The court also ruled the teacher was trying
to help the boy improve his grades and her actions were reasonable,
it said.
</TEXT>
