<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0041EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Superstitions     10-19 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Superstitions,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dictionary Of Superstitions Published</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just in time for Halloween, the Oxford University
Press is publishing a ``Dictionary of Superstitions'' with 1,500
entries including stepping on cracks and knocking on wood.
   Moira Tatum said she and co-author Iona Opie found in seven
years of research that many of today's superstitions are universal
and harken back thousands of years beyond written history.
   ``Although we know it goes back 4,000 years to nature worship,
the earliest written reference to knocking on wood is a
19th-century children's game,'' Ms. Tatum said.
   ``But the actual knocking on wood, or `touch wood' as the
British say, to save oneself after saying a boastful thing,
originated in Germany where they always knocked the underside of a
table and said, `May I not be bewitched.'''
   Ms. Tatum said putting together 494 pages of superstitions cured
any fears she had of bad omens: ``After all that work, I am totally
converted from those pagan ways.''
   The superstition to avoid stepping on cracks dates back to the
ancient Greek mythological character Persephone who was taken to
the underworld by Hades, she said.
   Ms. Tatum said superstitions are especially common in tightly
knit communities.
   ``The small communities of seamen or miners in Ireland or
Scotland are full of superstitions,'' she said. ``That's where you
find the more obscure or arcane superstitions.''
</TEXT>
