<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0048EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Haiti-Drugs     10-19 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Haiti-Drugs,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Seize 2,000 Pounds Of Cocaine</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Tipped off by U.S. drug agents,
authorities raided a suburban home and seized more than 2,000
pounds of cocaine in Haiti's biggest drug haul of the year, a news
report said.
   Police carried out the raid in the northern suburb of Delmas on
Tuesday and discovered the drugs Wednesday. A Colombian and a
Venezuelan who rented the house were absent and not detained, Radio
Metropole said.
   Authorities seized 2,024 pounds of cocaine, the privately-owned
radio said. It gave no value for the drug.
   The station, quoting police, said Haitian authorities were
tipped off by the U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency.
   Haiti has been identified by the DEA as a major conduit for
U.S.-bound Colombian cocaine. There has been testimony in a Cuban
drug-smuggling case linking ousted Haitian military leader Lt. Gen.
Henri Namphy to drug-running.
   On Oct. 9, Defense and Interior Minister Brig. Gen. Acedius
Saint-Louis said drug seizures have increased by 200 percent this
year compared with 1988.
   He said the Haitian Narcotics Bureau had handed over 4,000
pounds of cocaine to the DEA for destruction.
   Namphy was ousted in September 1988 in a coup led by junior
officers who said they were disgusted by government corruption and
state-sponsored killings and put Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril in power.
</TEXT>
