<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     10-19 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT PAYNE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 100-year-old man sliced into the
world's biggest cake to mark this town's 100th anniversary.
   The 128,238-pound, 12-layer cake _ 32 feet wide, 80 feet long
and shaped like the state of Alabama _ was unveiled Wednesday at
the local fairgrounds before 6,000 people. The country band
Alabama, who hail from Fort Payne, sang ``Happy Birthday.''
   Ed Henderson cut the cake with a sword and helped serve pieces.
   Gary Gengozian, editor and publisher of the local newspaper, The
Times Journal, came up with the idea of baking the birthday cake
because the EarthGrains Inc. bakery is the town's largest employer,
with 750 workers.
   He set a goal of topping a 90,000-pound cake baked in Austin,
Texas, for the Texas Sesquicentennial in 1986. The Guinness Book of
World Records lists that cake as the heaviest ever made.
   Guinness approved construction plans for the Fort Payne cake but
still must verify it as a record.
   Gary Gilbert, who supervised the baking of cake by EarthGrains,
said it contained 33,238 pounds of cake flour, 21,980 pounds of
sugar, 11,799 pounds of corn syrup, 608 pounds of vegetable oil,
161 pounds of vanilla flavoring, 1,206 pounds of baking powder, 568
gallons of powdered milk, 19,250 pounds of water and 429 pounds of
salt.
   The icing added another 33,354 pounds of ingredients, mostly
sugar.
   A local metal company provided the steel supports to keep the
cake from collapsing under its own weight.
   The Chamber of Commerce in the town of 12,000 said the cake
required $25,000 in ingredients, paid for with donations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STOCKBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 35 years, Jesse McCormick still
gets teased about being replaced by a dog in Norman Rockwell's
famous picture ``Breaking Home Ties.''
   ``I've been razzed about this quite a bit,'' said Mrs.
McCormick, 84. ``I knew that he changed the faces of the people in
his portraits, but this was a little drastic.''
   According to a Rockwell exhibit at the Old Corner House, the
artist had initially envisioned both a grieving mother and a father
in his 1954 painting of a young boy leaving home for the first
time. But only the father and son made the final version.
   Mrs. McCormick said was delighted when her late husband, Joseph,
a groundskeeper at the Stockbridge Country Club, came home and told
her that the artist wanted both of them to sit for the painting.
   ``I was so excited,'' Mrs. McCormick recalled. ``I made a dress
for the picture. I told everybody we were going to be on the cover
of the magazine.''
   The couple sat for several photos in Rockwell's studio with the
artist himself playing the anxious son.
   But when Rockwell finally got around to painting, he replaced
Mrs. McCormick with a big collie.
   She said one of her friends attempted to console her with the
advice, ``Don't feel so badly, dear. It's a beautiful dog.''

</TEXT>
