<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French designer Claude Montana will be Lanvin's new
creator of haute couture, the fashion house announced.
   Montana is the latest ready-to-wear designer to join the world
of couture after several other shakeups in the heady high fashion
scene this past year.
   Montana _ the creator of hulking, linebacker shoulders and
strong, aggressive fashion _ will be expected to turn out the
refined clothes expected by customers of the venerable old house of
Lanvin, started by Jeanne Lanvin in the 1920s.
   ``I'll be showing my first collection for 1990 next January,''
Montana said at a news conference Wednesday.
   He ducked questions about his salary. The Paris-born Montana
went to London when he was 20, and nearly starved before he created
papier-mache jewelry that was noticed by Vogue magazine.
   He returned to Paris and designed for several leather companies
before turning out his own collections starting in 1977.
