<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     10-19 0883</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Agreement With Canada Will Help Vegetable Sales, Expert Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new long-range trade pact with Canada
should help boost consumer demand for fresh vegetables on both
sides of the border, perhaps by 25 percent overall, says
Agriculture Department economist Amy Sparks.
   The U.S.-Canada Free Trade Agreement, which took effect last
Jan. 1, removes many trade restrictions between the two countries.
A major benefit down the road will be the elimination of all
agricultural tariffs within 10 years.
   Sparks, who works for the department's Economic Research
Service, took a look at the trade agreement's impact on vegetables.
Her findings are reported in a forthcoming issue of Farmline
magazine.
   Why focus on vegetables, when there are other larger and more
glamorous export commodities such as grains and meat to study?
   ``Everybody asks that question,'' Sparks said Wednesday in a
telephone interview. ``Don't feel that I take it personally.''
   But something ``totally different'' had to be found for her
doctoral dissertation, and vegetables were it, she said.
   ``Also, international trade in vegetables is growing quite a
bit,'' Sparks said. ``While it's not one of our major crops like
soybeans or corn, it's growing in importance and is something that
needs to be looked at.''
   The United States and Canada are each other's largest export
markets, overall, the report said. More than 18 percent of last
year's total U.S. imports were from Canada, while almost 22 percent
of all U.S. exports went to Canada.
   But agriculture makes up only a small portion of U.S. trade with
Canada, the report said. And of the U.S. agricultural export total,
only about 5 percent went to Canada in the 1980s.
   According to the department's Foreign Agricultural Service,
Canada imports around $3 billion in U.S. agricultural products
annually, including an average of about $450 million worth of
vegetables and $650 million worth of fruit.
   The USDA forecasts 1989-90 agricultural exports to Canada at a
value of $2.2 billion but adds that in recent years these figures
``have been under-reported by an estimated $1 billion annually''
and is officially recognized by both governments.
   Agricultural imports from Canada in 1989-90 are forecast at
about $2.8 billion, according to current USDA figures.
   The department's official estimate of total U.S. agricultural
export value in the year that began Oct. 1 is $40 billion. Japan is
the biggest single-country market at $8.1 billion, followed by the
Soviet Union, $3.5 billion; South Korea, $2.5 billion; Mexico, $2.4
billion; and Canada, $2.2 billion.
   With the complete elimination of tariffs, U.S. demand for
Canadian vegetables would increase about 80 percent from today's
levels, and Canadian demand for U.S. vegetable would go up 30
percent, according to Sparks' study.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The share of commodity marketings by farm
cooperatives has declined from levels of the early 1980s, according
to an Agriculture Department report.
   In 1987, the most recent year examined, co-ops accounted for 25
percent of farm marketings, down from 27 percent in 1985 and 28
percent in 1982.
   Grain marketings by cooperatives were reported at 29 percent of
the total, down from 33 percent in 1985 and 36 percent in 1982.
That includes sales of oilseeds except for cottonseed.
   ``Much of the decline has been the result of less cooperative
involvement in grain and oilseeds marketing,'' the report by the
department's Agricultural Cooperative Service said Wednesday.
   The co-op share of milk marketed was 76 percent in 1987,
compared with 78 percent in 1985 and 77 percent in 1982. Cotton
marketings were 38 percent, 33 percent and 36 percent,
respectively, and livestock at 7 percent, 8 percent and 11 percent.
   Fruit and vegetable marketings by co-ops accounted for 23
percent of the total in 1987, up from 8 percent in 1985 and 11
percent in 1982.
   Cooperative shares of production supplies sold to farmers also
dropped by similar percentages, to 25 percent in 1987 from 27
percent in 1985 and 28 percent in 1982, the report said. However,
not all items declined accordingly.
   Supplies included: fertilizer, 43 percent of the total in 1987,
44 percent in 1985 and 42 percent in 1982; petroleum, 37 percent,
44 percent and 36 percent; farm chemicals, 28 percent; 29 percent
and 34 percent; seed, 19 percent, 15 percent and 17 percent; and
feed, 17 percent, 16 percent and 18 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department trade report says
U.S. exports of solid wood products were valued at $2.95 billion in
the first six months of this year, up 11 percent from the first
half of 1988.
   Softwood products rose 4 percent to $1.9 billion, the report by
the department's Foreign Agricultural Service said Wednesday. That
included about $1.09 billion in the value of logs, $648.1 million
for lumber, and $104.9 million for plywood.
   Hardwood products increased 29 percent to $661 million,
including a 62 percent jump in hardwood logs to $147.8 million.
   ``Exports to Japan, the leading purchaser of U.S. wood products,
increased by 25 percent in the first half to $1.4 billion,'' the
report said. ``The other growth markets include Canada, 11 percent;
Iraq, 140 percent; and Australia, 39 percent.''
   But exports to China and Belgium, two other top markets, were
down 38 percent and 50 percent, respectively, from a year earlier,
the report said.
</TEXT>
