<HEAD>Seven Journalists Chosen for Hall of Fame</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven journalists have been chosen for admission
into the Hall of Fame of the Deadline Club, the local chapter of
the Society of Professional Journalists.
   Two of the seven were named posthumously: DeWitt and Lila
Acheson Wallace, who founded Reader's Digest in 1922.
   The others chosen are:
   _Don Hewitt, executive producer of CBS-TV's ``60 Minutes'';
   _Walter Kerr, the Pulitzer Prize-winning drama critic for the
New York Herald Tribune and The New York Times;
   _Warren Phillips, chairman and chief executive officer of Dow
Jones & Co.;
   _Harrison Salisbury, Pulitzer Prize-winning foreign
correspondent for The New York Times and author;
   _William Shawn, who retired as editor of The New Yorker in 1987;
   The chapter will recognize the selections Nov. 14 at Sardi's
restaurant.
   They will join 66 others in the Hall of Fame, which was
established in 1975.
