<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0203EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NorthPension     10-19 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Pension,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Supporters Fighting to Restore His Pension</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some lawmakers are vowing to restore Oliver
North's $23,000 military retirement pay, saying Congress never
intended for its anti-shredding law to deprive the convicted
Iran-Contra figure his pension.
   ``Regardless of what happened in the Iran-Contra affair, people
have a difficult time understanding why he is being denied the
pension that he earned,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
   The Senate is scheduled to vote Nov. 3 on a bill that would
exempt North from the penalty which was imposed after he was
convicted July 5 on charges of shredding government documents and
two other felonies. North is appealing the convictions.
   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Joseph Biden, D-Del., said
he will draft a report for the full Senate that outlines the
arguments on both sides of the politically divisive issue.
   ``We've got to solve this thing. We've got to make this thing
square for everybody,'' Biden told reporters after a hearing on
Wednesday on the matter.
   Biden suggested lawmakers should deal not just with North's
case, but with the pension rights of any federal official _
including members of Congress _ convicted of a felony.
   North's retirement pay was $23,000 a year. He is reportedly
getting $25,000 for each speech he gets on the lecture circuit.
   The law under which the pay was revoked provides that anyone
convicted of shredding protected government documents ``shall
forfeit his office.''
   The General Accounting Office, which has jurisdiction over
federal pay matters, ruled North's status as a retired military
officer came under that provision of the law and that forfeiting
his office meant he no longer qualified for retirement pay.
   Some conservatives who view North as a hero who bore the brunt
of blame for the Iran-Contra scandal were outraged at the decision.
Hatch, Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, and Sen. Strom Thurmond,
R-S.C., have said the retirement pay should be restored.
   But Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said North's sentence was
too lenient and the GAO was right to deny him retirement pay. ``We
are sending the wrong message when people violate the public trust
and get off with only a slap on the wrist,'' he said.
   Legal scholars told the Judiciary panel Congress should answer
whether the law meant for ``office'' to include military positions.
Technically, military retirement pay is not a pension based on past
service but a reduced salary for an officer who continues to hold a
commission and remains subject to recall to active duty.
   North ``very well may be entitled to his pension,'' Biden said.
``Whatever we do, there should be a basic equity'' with other cases.
   But he acknowledged, ``It's not going to be divorced from
politics.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
