<FIRST>r w PM-US-Cambodia     10-19 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Cambodia,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Accused of Violating Law With Indirect Support of Khmer Rouge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Federation of American
Scientists says the Bush administration is violating the law by
providing military supplies and advisers to allies of the Khmer
Rouge.
   Jeremy Stone, at a news conference Wednesday, said the Khmer
Rouge is still run by Pol Pot, who killed 2 million Cambodians when
he controlled the country from 1975 until 1978. ``These people are
beyond the Nazis,'' he said.
   Stone, who met last month with Thai leaders, said Thailand may
be prepared to reduce its support to the Khmer Rouge and Indonesia
and Malaysia, two other members of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations, ``are not in favor of the old line'' against
Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen.
   ``We should support Hun Sen as the main bulwark against the
Khmer Rouge,'' Stone said.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, at a peace conference in
August in Paris, supported an interim role for the Khmer Rouge in
the transition to a new government in Cambodia. But the conference
collapsed, and Stone warned the fighting is likely to increase with
the onset of the dry season.
   ``We think that the Department of State has to confront the
Chinese government publicly over its support of the Khmer Rouge,''
Stone said. ``We fear President Bush is taking his interest in
maintaining good relations with the Chinese too seriously. The
Chinese are oppressing democracy in China.''
   Stone said Vietnamese troops that backed Hun Sen have left
Cambodia and the Soviets will cease their support of the government
if the United States and China stopped assisting a three-way
coalition of troops loyal to Prince Sihanouk, the Khmer Rouge and
Son Senn.
   Stone said ASEAN still formally supports a hard line against Hun
Sen because it prefers unanimity on foreign policy issues.
   ``But,'' he said, ``the front-line state of Thailand has invited
Hu Senn to Bangkok three times and met with him in friendly fashion
and exchanged friendly messages. The Indonesian and Malaysian
governments are not in favor of the old line of freezing out the
Hun Sen government. The unanimity of ASEAN on this issue is no
longer real and it is something the U.S. government has to
recognize.''
   Thai Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan is due to visit
Washington Nov. 14-16 for talks with Bush and Baker.
   Stone said the Bush administration violated the Foreign Aid
authorization bill by providing military advisers, uniforms and
other supplies to Sihanouk forces and by helping Son Senn in his
forays into Cambodia.
   ``The U.S. government is supporting the Khmer Rouge in violation
of the law,'' he said. ``We say we are not supporting the Khmer
Rouge. We say we are only supporting Sihanouk and Son Senn. But
they are in a coalition with the Khmer Rouge. To support part of a
coalition with the Khmer Rouge is to support the Khmer Rouge.''
</TEXT>
