<FIRST>r a PM-Quake-Briefs     10-19 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Briefs,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bay area quake smashed a rare jade
pagoda into hundreds of pieces and damaged early California
exhibits and other artifacts at the Oakland Museum, a spokesman
said.
   The early 20th Century pagoda, about 4 feet tall, fell over in
its case and splintered, spokesman Phil Mumma said.
   ``The piece has a large value because it's so rare and very
unusual,'' Mumma said, adding, ``a lot of the pieces even if they
have a dollar value cannot be replaced by money.''
   Still, he said, damage in Tuesday's quake was moderate
considering the museum's location _ about a mile east of the Nimitz
Freeway section that collapsed, crushing to death more than 250
people.
   ``We are very, very fortunate,'' he said. ``Some sculptures
turned over with minimal damage, some glass pieces and some ceramic
pieces were either damaged or completely destroyed.''
   The museum was closed Wednesday for damage assessment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Monkeys and peacocks at the San Francisco
Zoological Gardens screamed, and elephants trumpeted when the
earthquake hit.
   Mike Sulak, curator of mammals, said he didn't notice any
unusual behavior among the animals in the minutes before Tuesday
evening's earthquake.
   But when the ground shook, the entire zoo erupted into a
cacophony of animal alarms that only died down after an hour or so,
Sulak said Wednesday.
   Kubie, an elder male gorilla, became extremely agitated and
would not go inside his shelter to join his mate and baby as
normal. He grunted and called out all night.
   Keepers finally lured Kubie inside Wednesday morning to get
breakfast.
   Sulak said he didn't think the zoo suffered any major damage.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The devastating earthquake hit during
production of NBC-TV's ``Midnight Caller'' program.
   Executive producer Robert Singer and his crew was filming on
Army Street when the quake hit Tuesday evening, said Nan Sumski, a
Lorimar Television publicist.
   ``Everyone is luckily safe and well and we're digging ourselves
out just like the rest of the city,'' Singer said in statement
relayed through Sumski on Wednesday.
   ``Last night we lost power and telephone lines. Power and phone
have been restored. For right now the set has remained closed.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Users of computer bulletin boards sought
word on family members electronically or alerted friends that they
were OK following the big earthquake.
   ``My car was uncontrollable and had to stop,'' Robert Ryan said
in a message left for other users of the Prodigy home computer
service. ``All I could really think about was how my kids were
doing and if anything happened to my home. ... Some of the streets
in Los Gatos had buckled. And there have been several deaths.''
   A man who signed himself Edgar Yergeau (Conn.) left a message
saying, ``If anyone in the Sacramento and Davis areas has a chance
to reply, I have friends whose children live in those areas, but
they cannot get through on the phones. I'd appreciate a response as
to how things are in those two areas.''
</TEXT>
