<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0213EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Panama-Church     10-19 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Church,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panamanian Church Leaders Taking on Noriega</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's Roman Catholic leaders are
becoming increasingly vocal in challenging strongman Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, even at the risk of seeing some priests expelled
from the country.
   The latest sign of troubled relations between church and state
involved the deportation Tuesday of Sister Elsa Marie Schaus, the
Peruvian-born principal of a Catholic girls school.
   Sister Schaus, who had lived in Panama for 26 years, was told by
immigration officials she was being expelled for ``state security
reasons and for her own safety.''
   Some church officials also said officials mentioned problems in
her treatment of the daughters of government and military officials.
   ``Whatever the reason, there is no relationship between a matter
of school discipline and the expulsion from the country of the
school's director,'' said the Rev. Fernando Guardia, vicar of the
Panama City archdiocese.
   The church's relations with the government have been prickly
since the early 1970s.
   In 1971, the Rev. Hector Gallego, a Colombian priest,
disappeared while organizing peasants in western Santiago de
Veraguas province. Church officials say he was slain and blame the
Defense Forces, which Noriega now commands.
   Most church schools have traditionally served middle- and
upper-class civilian families, where opposition to Noriega is
concentrated.
   However, growing numbers of affluent military and government
officials have been sending their children to these schools in
recent years.
   Making matters more complex, 220 of Panama's 297 Catholic
priests and 424 of its 482 nuns are foreigners, mostly from Europe.
Government and military officials are in many cases especially wary
of the foreign clery.
   ``The government regards the church as an enemy,'' said Guardia.
``Because of the large number of foreign priests, it is a direct
threat to the church when the government threatens to expel the
foreign priests.''
   However, Guardia said the church will not be deterred in its
campaign against Noriega, even though Sister Schaus' expulsion
``would seem to indicate the beginning of another campaign against
the church.''
   ``But the church will continue its campaign to make people aware
of their diginity as human beings, of their human rights, because
the gospel is a message of liberation,'' he added.
   Noriega has been cracking down on his opponents since federal
grand juries in Florida indicted him on drug-trafficking and
money-laundering charges February 1988.
   He survived a second military coup attempt on Oct. 3 and has
renewed efforts to eliminate opposition and consolidate power.
   Noriega has been closing down opposition news media and canceled
May 7 national elections when the returns showed that opposition
presidential candidate Guillermo Endara was winning by a 3-1
landslide.
   Panorama Catolico, the Panama City diocese weekly newspaper, is
the only opposition medium left in the country. It is sold at
churches every Sunday.
   Last week, it printed in a black box on the front page a prayer
for ``the dead, the wounded and their families.'' It was a clear
reference to the rebels from the latest attempted coup, 10 of whom
were killed.
   And in a letter in Panorama on Sept. 17, the nation's bishops
``noted with sadness that the people's will expressed in the
presidential elections has been ignored and the problems of our
people ... get worse every day.''
   Archbishop Marcos McGrath then angered the government-controlled
news media with an article deploring ``institutionalized violence
... and the violation of human rights.'' He urged a dialogue
between the country's political forces.
   Government newspapers and radio have been calling McGrath a
servant of the rich and contrasting him to Noriega, who is extolled
as a religious man and friend of the poor.
</TEXT>
