<FIRST>r w PM-Mosbacher-Mexico     10-19 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mosbacher-Mexico,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commerce Secretary Says Mexico Improving Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher says
Mexico is leading the way among Latin American nations trying to
strengthen their economies and assume a greater role in world trade.
   He told a Senate Banking subcommittee on Wednesday the
administration has high hopes ``Mexico will be the first olive out
of the jar'' in a succession of Latin economic successes and said
the long-range goal _ perhaps in 20 years _ should be a Western
Hemisphere with no trade barriers.
   Mosbacher said informal talks have already been held with
Mexican officials about working toward a free trade arrangement
similar to what the United States has with Canada.
   ``They are cautious,'' he said. ``We should not push them too
hard, too fast. But they are interested, very interested.''
   Mosbacher told the Senate Banking international finance and
monetary policy subcommittee that Mexico's new political leadership
is highly energetic and has taken significant steps to set a new
economic course.
   He said the nation's inflation rate has fallen to an annualized
rate of about 13 percent in the past few months and debt relief
agreements worked out with world lenders have freed up money for
domestic investments that are spurring the economy.
   He called Mexico's economic progress the best evidence that the
plan Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady outlined for restructuring
Third World debt can work.
   ``I agree the Brady plan will not work by itself, but it's part
of the puzzle,'' he said in response to skepticism from several
Democratic committee members.
   Mosbacher said a willingness by American businesses to put
long-term investments into Latin America is a key part of
administration's strategy in the region.
   ``Despite the discouragement of the debt problem,'' he said,
``we are seeing our major competitors making large new investments
in Latin America, particularly South America, and putting together
very competitive packages to capture major projects in sectors
where we have traditionally been preeminent.''
   Mosbacher said Japan is being particularly aggressive in moving
into Chile's mining sector and Venezuela's aluminum industry.
France is pushing hard in telecommunications in Brazil and Italy is
moving aggressively in Argentina, he said.
   ``These moves suggest that other industrial countries are taking
the long view, looking ahead to a brighter economic situation in
South America,'' said Mosbacher.
</TEXT>
