<FIRST>r w PM-Savimbi-CeaseFire     10-19 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Savimbi-Cease Fire,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angolan Rebel Optimistic on Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan anti-communist rebel leader Jonas
Savimbi says he believes the truce with Angola's leftist government
can be revived within the next two weeks even though a cease-fire
attempt four months ago was unsuccessful.
   Savimbi also said in a telephone interview Wednesday from the
Ivory Coast that a mutual prisoner exchange with the Angolan
government is possible.
   After reaching a high point last June, the Angolan peace process
has been bogged down by a resumption of fighting between government
and rebel forces as well as disagreements between Savimbi and
Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko, the chief peace mediator.
   Savimbi also angered his principal foreign patron, the United
States, when he declined to attend talks last month designed to
reinstate the cease-fire which had been agreed to last June.
   On Wednesday, Savimbi sounded upbeat following his weekend talks
in France with Mobutu and his earlier discussions in Washington
with President Bush. At one point recently, Savimbi was concerned
that Mobutu had abandoned impartiality and was siding with the
Angolan government.
   Savimbi made no reference Wednesday to a resumption of direct
talks with the Angolan government but said he was optimistic a
cease-fire could be back on track ``during this month of October.''
He raised the possibility that some African nations might
contribute troops to monitor the cease-fire if it is revived.
   But even if a truce is agreed to, the MPLA government and UNITA
face the challenging task of reaching a political settlement. With
U.S. support, UNITA is calling for free and fair elections to be a
key ingredient of the peace process.
   The Angolan government has a much narrower view of national
reconciliation, insisting the existing constitution remain
unchanged.
   But Savimbi said recent statements by senior Angolan officials
suggest a more flexible attitude on reconciliation.
   They are ``not so intransigent'' as they were before, said
Savimbi, who stopped off in the Ivory Coast while en route to his
home base in rebel-held southeast Angola.
   Discussing the possibility of a prisoner exchange, Savimbi said
there are between 3,000 and 5,000 MPLA prisoners in UNITA hands. He
said the government has refused to disclose the number of rebel
prisoners it holds.
   While the government receives substantial backing from the
Soviet Union, UNITA has been getting about $40 million annually
from the United States. UNITA has been at war with the MPLA
government for 14 years.
</TEXT>
