<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--UnscheduledLanding     10-19 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Unscheduled Landing,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>United 747 Makes Precautionary Stop in Seattle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Airlines 747 with 145 passengers made an
unscheduled landing at Seattle-Tacoma International Airport after
the pilot shut down one of the jumbo jet's four engines,
authorities said.
   Flight 137 was bound for Tokyo from San Francisco when the pilot
shut down the No. 4 engine because of a problem with the engine
pressure ratio, United spokesman Joe Hopkins said.
   The plane landed Wednesday night without a problem, said Hugh
Wilson, airport supervisor. A precautionary crash crew was on hand.
   Hopkins said the stop was just a precaution, ``nothing that far
out of the ordinary.''
   A Boeing 747 can fly from San Francisco to Tokyo on three
engines, Hopkins said.
   The passengers were to be flown to Tokyo today on a Continental
flight after an overnight stay in Seattle, Hopkins said. The 747's
engine was being replaced, he added.
