<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-19 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Nikkei Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down against the Japanese yen
Thursday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose
moderately.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 266.66
points, or 0.76 percent, ending at 35,374.22. It gained 111.48
points Wednesday.
   The dollar ended at 141.55 yen, down 0.55 yen from Wednesday's
142.10 yen-close. It started lower at 140.97 yen and moved between
140.80 yen and 141.70 yen.
   The dollar opened sharply lower as investment trust companies
overseas sold dollars to reduce their holdings of the currency,
then rose marginally in Tokyo and ranged mainly around 140.50 yen,
said Yoshitsugu Hanada, a trader for Mitsui Bank in Tokyo.
   ``The dollar has been gradually falling as market players are
inclined to sell it following a series of recent economic figures
in America, which have indicated the slowdown in economy there,''
he said. He cited the $10.8 billion trade deficit reported Tuesday
and Friday's stock market plunge on Wall Street.
   ``Although the exchange rate doesn't move much in one day, the
dollar is getting weaker slowly but surely,'' he said.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei, the market's major barometer,
rose ``intermittently but steadily,'' despite selling by
speculative investors for their arbitrage deals, said a dealer with
New Japan Securities Co. Ltd.
   The Tokyo market has been getting stronger, the dealer added,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
