<SECOND>PM-Quake-Hugo,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storm Victims Send Relief To Earthquake Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal disaster officials said they
would not siphon off Hurricane Hugo relief to help the San
Francisco area, and Charleston showed its sympathy to earthquake
victims by sending a planeload of water.
   ``We are in the process of recovering from a disaster. So we
will feel what is occurring there more deeply than any community in
the country,'' Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. said Wednesday.
   He said the national response to the victims of last month's
hurricane was heartwarming, and reminded him of his pledge that
``if ever another community in the United States ... was hit with a
disaster, we would want to respond.'' He set up a California
Earthquake Disaster Relief Fund to raise money for earthquake
victims.
   The Air Force C-141 transport that left Wednesday carrying
potable water also carried Police Chief Reuben Greenberg and
several Charleston police officers to help with emergency
operations in California.
   Hugo smashed into Charleston with 135 mph winds on Sept. 21,
prompting a nationwide outpouring of supplies and food for disaster
victims.
   Riley just returned from the San Francisco Bay area, where he
attended the first two games of the World Series.
   Officials of the Federal Emergency Management Agency, meanwhile,
said the response to the earthquake will not mean any curtailment
of the agency's operations in South Carolina.
   Coordinating officer Paul Hall said the $1.1 billion earmarked
by Congress for the Hugo recovery will be replenished as needed to
address other disasters.
   ``They must have learned some lessons,'' said Sen. Ernest
Hollings, D-S.C., a critic of the FEMA response in South Carolina.
He said FEMA responded quickly to the earthquake.
   ``I just hope for one thing: They won't take two weeks to
declare it a 100 percent disaster area,'' he said.
   It wasn't until two weeks after Hugo hit that the federal
government said it would cover all the cleanup costs in South
Carolina.
