obscene'' and lacking in serious artistic, literary, political or
scientific value.
   The ban was prompted by conservative legislators' complaints
that NEA funds were used by modern art institutes in Philadelphia
and Winston-Salem, N.C., to support exhibitions of controversial
works by photographer Robert Mapplethorpe and artist Andres Serrano.
   Frohnmayer succeeded Frank Hodsoll as endowment chairman Oct. 3.
