<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0337EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AsbestosSabotage     10-19 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Asbestos Sabotage,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Insulation Laced With Asbestos Placed in Front of Air-Circulation
Fans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A saboteur ripped insulation laced with
cancer-causing asbestos from pipes at Nassau County government
offices and placed it in front of air-circulation fans, police said.
   The fans were shut off when the asbestos was found, and tests
found no dangerous levels in the air at the County Executive
Building, Health Department spokeswoman Shelly Domash said
Wednesday.
   Airborne asbestos fibers can be inhaled and cause debilitating
lung disease and even lung cancer.
   Inspector Donald White, of Nassau County Police Department, said
the asbestos insulation also was found in front of a fan at police
headquarters but officials didn't test the air because they
believed the material was found soon enough to prevent danger.
   ``This is not an act of vandalism,'' White said. ``Someone
intentionally ripped the asbestos off the pipes and strategically
put it in an area which they thought could hurt someone.''
   County engineers also found torn insulation in front of fans in
a third county building, but that insulation contained no asbestos,
authorities said.
   The three rooms involved are locked and located in secured areas
which are not easily accessible without identification cards, White
said. There was no evidence of a break-in.
   ``Someone didn't walk off the street and do this,'' he said.
``The individual or individuals had to know what they were doing
and had access to the areas.''
   Asbestos insulation was found in front of fans Monday and
Tuesday at the county police headquarters and an underground
emergency operations center behind police headquarters.
   No problems had been found in the ventilation rooms when they
were checked by the same engineer on routine rounds 24 hours
earlier, according to White.
   There are 300 to 400 county employees in the three buildings.
   ``It could have been anyone: a disgruntled employee, maybe
someone who is trying to make a statement,'' White said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
