<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0353EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Angola     10-19 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Leader Ready for New Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrilla leader Jonas Savimbi says
he is ready to resume negotiations with Angola's Marxist government
and hopes a new cease-fire can be signed within a month.
   ``We are ready to talk anywhere,'' he said Wednesday in a
telephone interview during a stop in Abidjan. ``I think the
cease-fire will be signed this month because the mood is good.''
   He said his side wants the new truce to include monitors
provided by other African countries and release of all prisoners
through the International Red Cross.
   The guerrilla chief, who has U.S. support, said he was in
Abidjan to brief President Felix Houphouet-Boigny on weekend talks
in France with President Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire. Savimbi leads
the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, known as
UNITA.
   Mobutu has mediated negotiations toward ending the 14-year-old
war in the former Portuguese colony and was host for four days of
talks on the French Riviera with Angolan, South African and U.S.
officials.
   He negotiated a cease-fire in the conflict between UNITA and the
ruling Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola, known as the
MPLA, during a meeting June 22 at his home village of Gbadolite,
but it broke down within days.
   Savimbi subsequently rejected Mobutu's mediation, accusing the
Zairean leader of siding with the Angolan government. He refused to
attend a meeting of African heads of state last month in Kinshasa,
capital of Zaire, aimed at reviving the negotiations.
   At issue were the claim of several African leaders that Savimbi
had agreed to go into exile and the integration of his guerrillas
into Angola's armed forces. Savimbi said no such an agreement,
which he described as a defeat, had been made at Gbadolite.
   The United States, which has supported Mobutu's government
despite criticizing his human rights record, was caught between two
allies.
   Some congressional supporters of Savimbi said Mobutu, the main
conduit of $40 million in annual U.S. aid to UNITA, had blocked the
flow of weapons.
   After the Kinshasa meeting, Mobutu, Savimbi and Angolan
officials went to the United States, where President Bush met
separately with Mobutu and the guerrilla leader, urging new
negotiations.
   The French Riviera meeting was held a few days later and Savimbi
declared Wednesday it was a success.
   ``President Mobutu has reassured us that the basis of our work
in negotiations will be and will remain the Gbadolite agreement,''
he said.
   ``So we are reconciled on that,'' Savimbi said. ``He has been
our friend in the past and I think we can consider our relations
with him very good, and we have renewed our confidence in him as a
mediator.''
   Mobutu has said recent interviews in which Foreign Minister
Pedro van Dunem Loy of Angola said Savimbi should discuss the
issues of exile and integration, were encouraging.
   Savimbi said Wednesday: ``When they (MPLA) say exile has to be
discussed, good. I think they are coming along. Mobutu has also
said once the cease-fire is signed, the rest of the political
problem will be discussed by UNITA and the MPLA, face to face,
because it is an Angolan problem. Others should be called in only
if we have problems.''
</TEXT>
