<SECOND>PM-BRF--Phone Strike,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Jobless Benefits Restored to Striking Telephone Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered the state to restore
unemployment benefits about 12,000 striking phone workers. New
England Telephone immediately appealed the ruling.
   Wednesday's decision by Suffolk Superior Court Judge Elbert
Tuttle reversed an Oct. 6 decision by state Employment and Training
Commissioner James French to deny benefits to the strikers, most of
whom belong to the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers.
   ``The Legislature never intended to have the unemployment
compensation law turned into a strike fund for unions and this
would be the result if today's decision is not overturned,''
company spokesman Peter Cronin said.
   Under Massachusetts' unemployment compensation law, strikers are
paid benefits unless a company shows the walkout has resulted in a
``substantial curtailment'' of its operations.
   The union sued, arguing the law's confidentiality provision
denied them the right to examine and rebut the company's evidence.
