<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0353EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-TyphoonElsie     10-19 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Typhoon Elsie,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Typhoon Heads for Luzon Island, Residents Told to Seek Higher Ground</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The strongest typhoon to strike the
Philippines this year lashed the east coast of Luzon Island today
with 127 mph winds after residents of areas in its path were told
to seek higher ground.
   Advance winds from Typhoon Elsie struck land at midday near
Casiguran, 130 miles north of Manila, and the center of the storm
was expected to come ashore a few hours later, according to the
Manila Weather Bureau.
   Storm warnings were issued for all of Luzon, the main
Philippines island, and at U.S. military installations.
   ``Any typhoon of this strength is capable of massive
destruction,'' said forecaster Vicente Manalo.
   Elsie's westward path would take it across the rugged mountains
of northeastern Luzon and across the north-central agricultural
heartland about 100 miles north of the capital.
   There were no immediate reports of casualties or damage, but
Manila radio stations said they received sketchy reports of
flooding and landslides in the north.
   Manila radio station DZXL said its affiliate in Bayombong,
capital of Nueva Vizcaya province 130 miles to the north, was
knocked off the air by a power failure.
   U.S. officials said all six American military installations on
Luzon had been placed on maximum typhoon alert.
   U.S. Air Force forecasters predicted the storm would pass about
50 miles north of Clark Air Base but near the U.S. John Hay Air
Station in Baguio, 130 miles north of Manila.
   The storm was reported moving about 12 mph and was expected to
weaken as it crossed the Sierra Madre mountains of northeastern
Luzon.
   Philippine Airlines canceled flights from Manila to northern
Luzon, and the coast guard ordered ships to stay in port in the
affected area.
   U.S. Air Force officials said some jets had been moved to air
bases in Japan and South Korea until the storm passed.
   The Far East Network, which broadcasts to the 40,000-member U.S.
military community, advised residents at Clark, John Hay and the
U.S.-run Wallace Air Station to stock up on fresh water,
flashlights, candles and other emergency equipment.
   Residents at the U.S.-run Subic Bay naval base, 50 miles
northwest of Manila, were also advised to take precautions.
   Base spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Kevin Mukri said there were relatively
few warships in port ``so we're not going to have a very big exodus
if the conditions worsen.''
   The Navy routinely sends warships into the South China Sea when
storms threaten Subic.
   Elsie was the third major storm to strike the Philippines in two
weeks.
   Typhoon Dan hit Manila and southern Luzon on Oct. 10, killing at
least 59 people. On Oct. 6, Typhoon Angela killed at least 119
people in northern Luzon.
   An average of 20 typhoons and tropical storms strike the
Philippines annually. Elsie was the 17th of 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891019-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0357EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Quake-Family     10-19 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Family,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Reunited After Quake Horror and Marina Blaze</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Near the crest of California Street, Jane
and Richard Springwater watched the Marina district burn, fearing
their young children might be wandering in the stricken area.
   The emotional trial of the Springwaters was just one of many in
the Bay area quake catastrophe. But their story shares a common
thread with all families who struggled to find each other across a
disrupted urban landscape.
   ``You could see large plumes of smoke coming from the Marina,''
Richard said Wednesday. ``I tend to look on the bright side but it
didn't look good. We knew something catastrophic had happened
there.''
   Said Jane: ``For our children's babysitter, Tuesday is usually
the day they go down to the Marina. And my mom had said earlier in
the day they were going ... but I had no idea if my kids were in a
car, if they were walking. ...
   ``Not until we reached Nob Hill could we see the smoke,'' she
said. ``And it looked bad _ it looked like a huge fire.''
   Like many working couples, the Springwaters were at their
offices, away from their children, when the quake struck Tuesday
evening.
   Jane, a 33-year-old attorney, sat at her 39th-floor desk as the
shock wave rumbled through.
   For a moment or two, she said, she thought only of moving away
from her window, into the hall.
   ``And then, all I could think of was, `Oh my God! my kids. I
have no idea where my kids are.'''
   But she had a clue. On Tuesdays, Benjamin, 4, and Hannah, 1{,
usually went to the Marina with their babysitter. And their
grandmother, visiting from New York, said that that was where they
were going to go Tuesday.
   ``I called my husband as soon as the quake hit. His receptionist
picked up the line. I asked for him, and the lines went dead.''
   With no link to her family, Jane turned to the trickle of news
reports on radio and television. They were sketchy. But one thing
seemed pretty clear: the Marina was taking a beating. The area was
devastated by fire.
   Richard, 37, worked in his office five blocks from Jane's in the
financial district.
   ``Since I'm an architect, I went into the elevator core,'' he
said.
   The area between elevators is a building's most solid component,
he said. ``I don't really trust buildings.
   ``I wasn't worried about the Marina though,'' he said, recalling
his feelings when hearing on the radio that the district was
flattened. ``I didn't know the kids were in the Marina.''
   The Springwaters had talked a lot about putting together an
earthquake contingency plan but they never quite worked out the
details.
   So Richard started walking, moving past dazed, disoriented
financial district regulars shuffling along on the sidewalk. Jane
didn't show up at the front of her building. The elevators weren't
operating. So he opened the door and started up 39 floors.
   His wife already was well on her way down the same escape route.
   ``Had I left 10 minutes earlier, he would have climbed 39 floors
to find I wasn't there,'' she said.
   Jane shared her fears about their children.
   Benjamin, Hannah and Gramma had left the Marina just minutes
before the quake, though, to go shopping.
   In fact, they scarcely knew they were in the middle of the
second-deadliest quake in U.S. history.
   When the Springwaters arrived at their Pacific Heights
neighborhood, two hours after the initial jolt, everything looked
perfect.
   Their century-old house, a survivor of the 1906 catastrophe,
stood in place, brick for brick.
   ``When I got home and opened the door,'' Jane said, ``everyone
was there. They had eaten dinner. And my son was excited that there
were no lights.''
</TEXT>
