<FIRST>r a PM-Quake-Neighborhood     10-19 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Neighborhood,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tough Neighborhood Pulls Together</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE CARPENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Oakland, a drug-plagued neighborhood
of broken glass, shaken buildings and people, marshaled its
resources to help the people they knew were trapped under the
Nimitz Freeway.
   After the double-decked Cypress portion of Interstate 880 caved
in during Tuesday's earthquake, residents came quickly to the
rescue, mobilizing to provide tools, rescue squads and support
services.
   ``I haven't seen that much love in Oakland in a long time,''
said Greg Roberts, a street vendor. ``It was something to see.''
   Police Lt. Larry Eade praised the community that tried to help
the victims of the freeway disaster.
   ``They climbed up on the bridge to take people off. They lined
up to volunteer. They established medical help as soon as
possible,'' Eade said. ``I didn't see one instance of a citizen
that didn't cooperate.''
   ``West Oakland has a bad image as a dope haven, but there was a
lot of community effort,'' said Richard Reynolds, a car repair shop
owner who directed traffic for four hours with flares provided by
grateful police. ``This community came through.''
   William McElroy, a boilermaker, saw the community leap into
action as soon as the earthquake struck.
   ``The neighborhood people all came out to help, so we said, `Go
back into your houses and get ladders, wire cutters, tools,
flashlights, whatever you can find, and meet back here in 20
minutes,''' the 52-year-old McElroy said.
   The group managed to get forklifts and tore down a cyclone fence
to position the machinery under the freeway. Others went into a
nearby factory to get ladders and lumber, while still others
brought small hydraulic jacks they used to lift mangled cars.
   McElroy estimated they evacuated 40 to 50 people off the
highway. Twenty-one were injured and had to be taken off on gurneys.
   Reynolds said the community where former Black Panther leader
Huey Newton was slain recently has suffered from a bad reputation.
   ``They've got a lot of good people who are trapped here by their
drug problems. In general they are good responsible citizens,'' he
said.
   Kim Barnes, a janitor who lives a few blocks from the freeway,
spent all Wednesday at the scene after volunteering.
   ``After all you here about Oakland and its problems, a disaster
hits and boom you find out everybody's pulling together,'' he said.
</TEXT>
