<FIRST>r i PM-China-FangLizhi     10-19 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Fang Lizhi,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Criticizes Human Rights Award For Fang Lizhi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China today called the selection of dissident
Fang Lizhi for the 1989 Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Human Rights
award a ``provocation against the Chinese people'' and ``wanton
interference'' in China's internal affairs.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing, at a weekly briefing,
said the 53-year-old astrophysicist ``is a criminal wanted by the
Chinese public security organs'' and the award ``represents open
support to Fang Lizhi's criminal activities aimed at subverting the
legal Chinese government.''
   Li said: ``We express our utmost regret and strong indignation
at this fallacious decision.''
   Fang was China's best-known and most eloquent advocate of
democratic reform before the June military crackdown on the
pro-democracy movement silenced all dissent.
   Shortly after the military shot their way to student-occupied
Tiananmen Square on June 3-4, Fang and his wife, physicist and
political activist Li Shuxian, sought refuge in the U.S. Embassy,
where they remain today.
   Although Fang and his wife did not take an active role in the
student movement this spring, the government has accused them of
inciting counterrevolution and demanded that the United States turn
them over to police.
   The award, announced in Washington on Wednesday, honored Fang
for ``his commitment to speaking out against injustice and tyranny
at grave personal risk.''
</TEXT>
