<FIRST>r a PM-Sheriff'sTrial     10-19 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sheriff's Trial,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jurors Clear Two Oklahoma Lawmen Conspiracy Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHERMAN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury found two Oklahoma lawmen innocent
of charges they plotted to kidnap and torture a suspected drug
dealer to obtain evidence on drug laboratories.
   Jurors returned the verdicts Wednesday for Love County, Okla.,
Sheriff Wesley Liddell Jr. and his son-in-law, Roger Ray Hilton, a
Marietta, Okla., police officer.
   Liddell, who suspended himself after his arrest by FBI agents on
May 18, said he will return to work today.
   ``I just voluntarily unsuspended myself,'' said Liddell, 47.
   The officers were accused of conspiring to abduct Pearl
``Sonny'' Cornett and torture him to obtain evidence on drug
laboratories in southern Oklahoma and northern Texas.
   Oklahoma State Sen. Darryl Roberts, who represented Hilton, 27,
said several jurors had indicated to him they had felt all along
the government's case was weak.
   The trial ``was a circus from the very beginning. There was not
enough evidence,'' said juror Rebecca Ray.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney H.S. ``Bert'' Garcia said the jury's
verdict was ``based in part on the fact that in this case, no one
was tortured or hurt or harmed.''
   During the trial, defense lawyers claimed Liddell and Hilton
were framed by Marietta Police Lt. Tom Hankins, the prosecution's
lead witness. They said Hankins wanted Liddell's job. Hankins has
denied the claim.
   Hilton testified that the kidnapping plot was a hoax devised by
Liddell to see if Hankins would leak the information to drug
dealers.
   The FBI taped nine hours of conversations between the defendants
and Hankins through a wiring device attached to Hankins. The jury
heard a condensed three-hour version.
</TEXT>
