<FIRST>r a PM-RepossessedElephants     10-19 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Repossessed Elephants,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alleged Elephant Thief Arrested in Texas, Will Return to New Jersey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An animal trainer who fled the state with
two elephants in 1984 said he will return to face charges following
his arrest in Texas.
   Arlan Seidon, 59, repossessed the elephants after a dispute with
two men who bought them from him. Seidon claimed the buyers
mistreated the animals and fell behind on their payments.
   ``I don't think I'm crazy,'' Seidon said Wednesday in an
interview from jail in Jefferson, Texas, broadcast on television
station WWOR in Secaucus. ``It's a very serious thing.''
   Seidon was arrested Tuesday on a fugitive warrant after one of
the men, Richard Drake, tracked him down. Drake has said he has
spent thousands of dollars searching for Seidon around the country.
   Seidon told WWOR he would not fight extradition back to Monmouth
County, N.J., where he faces charges of third-degree theft. If
convicted he would face up to five years in prison and a $100,000
fine.
   Seidon sold the Indian elephants, Tory and Duchess, to Drake's
son, Edward, in 1981 for $80,000. The Drakes owned a now-closed
exotic-animal ranch in Tehachapi, Calif.
   While the animals were on tour in New Jersey in 1984, Seidon had
a dispute with the Drakes and seized the elephants.
   Seidon said he decided to take the elephants back when the
Drakes fell behind in their payments. He also said that while
waiting for money from the Drakes at a New Jersey farm, he
discovered the animals had wounds from hooks used during training.
   The Drakes denied abusing the animals.
   A Monmouth County judge in May 1984 ordered Seidon to return the
7-foot-tall elephants. Instead, Seidon fled with them in a truck
and has hid them ever since.
   He pursued an appeal through telephone contacts with New Jersey
lawyer Isabelle Strauss, an animal-rights activist. But the state
appeals court rebuffed Seidon in January, saying he failed to show
the animals had been abused and provided no reason to believe the
court had erred in 1984.
   Seidon has said he raised the animals, now in their late 20s,
from their infancy. He told a newspaper in 1988 that he left his
Fordland, Mo., farm and his career preparing animals for circus and
television appearances to care for the elephants, which eat about
200 pounds of hay a day. He also said he hadn't seen his four
children or met his only grandson since he took off with the
animals.
   The elephants are in a barn in Texas. The Drakes are trying to
have them returned to New Jersey.
</TEXT>
