<FIRST>r a PM-StudentsRally     10-19 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Students Rally,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Storm Statehouse to Protest Education Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 15,000 people protested higher education
budget cuts in a demonstration that grew unruly when several
hundred students tried to enter the Statehouse and blocked an
entrance.
   Many students wore dunce caps that read ``State Skool,'' and
chanted ``No More Cuts!'' Many urged legislators to support new
taxes to pay for education.
   Capitol Police Capt. Dennis Sullivan said four were arrested:
two for assault and battery and two others for disorderly conduct.
   Sullivan said a window was broken and a drainpipe knocked down,
and officials estimated repairs could total $20,000.
   The higher education system, already strapped by earlier cuts,
faces an additional $25 million in trimming during the next round
of budget reductions.
   State Police Cpl. Joseph Howley estimated the number of
demonstrators to be 15,000.
   One person was removed from the House when he repeatedly yelled
down from the visitors' gallery to ask House Speaker George
Keverian if he intended to discuss the cuts.
   The Statehouse lawn's flower beds were trampled and more than
100 state, Boston, Capitol and Metropolitan District Commission
police closed the front entrances and patrolled the halls.
   From his chair, Keverian asked members to remain in the chamber,
called in police reinforcements and addressed a large gathering of
students outside.
   ``Everything that is being done here is not helpful and is in
fact disgraceful,'' he said. ``Trampling down doors, breaking the
law and breaking windows is not what we expect from our young
people and will not be helpful to you.''
   Higher Education Chancellor Franklyn Jenifer, Board of Regents
Chairman Paul Tsongas, Gov. Michael S. Dukakis' education aide
Robert Schwartz, and others came to counsel the students to remain
orderly.
   Students swarmed over the Capitol steps, carrying signs that
read ``Stop Killing My College,'' and ``We want Mikey.'' One simply
read ``Arrrgh!'' Other students paraded with a coffin.
   The protesters began to disperse after they were informed their
buses were leaving, but one man made a dash for the House lobby
door. State police arrested him and pushed through the crowd to
take him away.
   About 200 students had gathered in front of Dukakis' office
earlier in the day and Schwartz spoke to the group.
   ``The fact of the matter is that we, with you, believe no more
cuts is exactly the right thing,'' Schwartz told them.
   The students were divided on whether to believe the
administration, and some loudly jeered Schwartz.
   ``No more lies!'' one young man yelled.
   Schwartz pressed on, telling the students they had to convince
legislators and voters that new taxes were needed to pay for higher
education and other state programs. ``This cannot be a one-day
rally,'' he said.
   Dukakis, who was out of the building throughout the afternoon,
said he was pleased by the students' show of solidarity, but not by
the rowdy behavior.
</TEXT>
