<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0526EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BusAccident     10-19 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Accident,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Families of 50 Students Sue Over Texas Bus Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURG, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 50 lawsuits have been filed
against the owner of a soft-drink delivery truck that ran a red
light and knocked a school bus into a water-filled pit last month,
killing 21 students and injuring 59.
   Families of victims, survivors and students who came to the
crash scene shortly after the Sept. 21 accident in Alton seek
unspecified damages from Valley Coca-Cola Bottling Co. The truck's
driver also was named in some of the suits.
   The driver had told authorities the truck's brakes failed before
it struck the bus carrying Mission High School students, sending it
over a 40-foot cliff into a roadside pit. But the National
Transportation Safety Board concluded the truck's brakes worked
well enough to halt it at the stop sign.
   Some of the lawsuits accuse the company of ``conscious
indifference for the rights and well-being of the public.''
   A lawyer designated as spokesman for lawyers representing Valley
Coca-Cola was not in his office Wednesday and did not return a
phone call by The Associated Press.
   Families for at least 15 of the 21 dead students are represented
in the lawsuits. Other claims were filed on behalf of survivors,
and at least five were filed on behalf of students who said they
suffered mental anguish after arriving at the scene and seeing
their friends and relatives drowning.
   One suit states that ``Normalinda Perez was at the scene of the
accident in question and observed the bus under the water in the
pit as her daughter, Veronica Perez, still trapped in the bus,
drowned.''
   Most of the cases are consolidated in 275th District Court in
Edinburg; others have been filed in three of the other state
district courts in Hidalgo County, where Alton, 15 miles from the
Mexico border, is located.
   One survivor's family accused a lawyer of trying to bribe them
with $700 to keep him on their case. The family of 12-year-old Nora
Manriquez, which hired San Antonio lawyer Roberto Guerra on Oct. 4
but chose to hire another lawyer Oct. 9, last week filed for a
temporary restraining order to prevent Guerra from contacting them.
   Guerra said Wednesday the $700 was a loan the Manriquez family
had asked him to provide, and he speculated they were unhappy
because he did so a day late.
   ``If that's what they are calling a bribe, well you know I hope
my side gets heard,'' Guerra said. ``It's a lot more sensational to
say an attorney offered a bribe to pursue a fat case than to say he
honored a commitment on an advance.'' No ruling has been issued on
the restraining order.
</TEXT>
