<FIRST>r a PM-OilSpill     10-19 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Insurer of Oil Spilled in R.I. Sues Ship Owner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owners of the tanker that spilled
hundreds of thousands of gallons of oil in Rhode Island Sound this
summer were sued for $500,000 by the company that insured the
ship's cargo.
   The lawsuit Americas Insurance Co. filed Wednesday in U.S.
District Court against Ballard Shipping Co. asks that the tanker
World Prodigy be sold to pay its claim.
   However, attorneys for both sides said Ballard Shipping has
promised to pay any claims, making seizure of the vessel
unnecessary.
   The World Prodigy hit a reef a mile south of Newport on June 23,
tearing two gashes in its hull. The Coast Guard estimated 289,000
gallons of heating oil were spilled.
   The lawsuit alleges that the tanker was unseaworthy, its
officers and crew were ``incompetent or unqualified'' and the ship
was improperly and inadequately crewed, equipped and prepared for
sea.
   Americas Insurance estimated it will have to pay $500,000 in
claims for oil that was not delivered or was delivered mixed with
seawater.
   Ballard attorney Thomas H. Walsh said he had not seen the
lawsuit. He said he was puzzled the insurer would sue before trying
to settle its claim out of court.
   Ballard had promised to pay any claims against the ship in order
to allow the vessel to leave the country, Walsh said. The ship went
abroad for permanent repairs.
   In addition to Ballard, the lawsuit names International Maritime
Agencies Co. as a defendant. Stephen V. Rible, a New York attorney
representing Americas Insurance, said he believed that company was
Ballard's agent for operating the ship.
   After the accident, Ballard and ship's captain Iakovos Georgudis
pleaded guilty to violating the federal Clean Water Act, and
Georgudis pleaded no contest to a state pollution charge. Ballard
paid a $500,000 fine. Georgudis was fined $30,500.
   A group of fishermen have sued Ballard and Georgudis for $40
million in damages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
