<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador-Attack     10-19 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Attack,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Leaders' Houses Bombed, Two Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers early today bombed
the neighboring houses of Ruben Zamora and another prominent
leftist political leader, wounding two people.
   Zamora, a top leader of the Democratic Convergence, and Aronette
Diaz, vice-president of the Nationalist Democratic Union spoke with
journalists outside their heavily damaged homes shortly after the
1:15 a.m. attack.
   Mrs. Diaz blamed the army for the attacks.
   Zamora said his two bodyguards were wounded by the explosion of
a powerful bomb at his front door. Both were taken to the hospital,
though neither man appeared critically hurt, he said.
   Zamora returned to El Salvador in late 1987 after nearly eight
years of exile following the death squad slaying of his brother,
Mario.
   He is also a leader of the Democratic Revolutionary Front, which
is allied with leftist rebels waging a 10-year-old war against a
succession of U.S.-backed governments.
   Zamora, his wife and their five children were uninjured, though
shaken up, by the blast. The roof over the front rooms of the house
was destroyed, as were doors, drop ceilings and walls in four rooms.
   Two cars parked in a carport in front of the house were
destroyed.
   Mrs. Diaz, the widow of Mario Zamora, lives next door to Zamora
with her two sons. Three grenades exploded on her roof and right in
front of her house moments before the bomb went off at her
brother-in-law's door. Damage to the front rooms of her home was
also extensive.
   Zamora, 47, said the attack ``is intended to impede a political
solution to the war.'' But he refrained from directly blaming a
particular sector.
   Representatives of the government and the rebels on Wednesday
wound up three days of peace talks in Costa Rica. The talks
produced no substantive accord, but the two sides agreed to meet
again next month.
   ``This is the work of people in the army who don't want dialogue
and negotiation,'' said Mrs. Diaz, 43. ``They want to start another
spiral of violence like in 1980, when they killed my husband. Do
they want to bring more mourning to my home?''
   The government has urged the Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front, the rebel army, to stop fighting and join the political
process.
   ``Imagine, if this was done to us, who are not the FMLN, what
awaits the FMLN if they convert themselves into a political
party,'' said Mrs. Diaz. ``There are no guarantees for freedom of
poltical activity.''
   The bombing came two days after gunmen killed the 23-year -old
daughter of an army colonel. The government and armed forces blamed
the FMLN, which denied any responsibility in the slaying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
