<FIRST>u w PM-Soci 1stLd-Writethru a0454 10-19 0133</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Social Security-Table, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0454,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Annual Cost-of-Living Increases for Social Security</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to correct sequential number.</HEAD>
<HEAD>INSERTS new penultimate graf to add figure for 1990.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Social Security</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the annual cost-of-living increases
that Social Security beneficiaries have gotten since the system was
linked to the Consumer Price Index in 1975:
   July 1975: 8 percent.
   July 1976: 6.4 percent.
   July 1977: 5.9 percent.
   July 1978: 6.5 percent.
   July 1979: 9.9 percent.
   July 1980: 14.3 percent.
   July 1981: 11.2 percent.
   July 1982: 7.4 percent.
   Jan. 1984: 3.5 percent.
   Jan. 1985: 3.5 percent.
   Jan. 1986: 3.1 percent.
   Jan. 1987: 1.3 percent.
   Jan. 1988: 4.2 percent.
   Jan. 1989: 4.0 percent.
   Jan. 1990: 4.7 percent.
   Six months were skipped in 1983 to help bail Social Security out
of a crisis.
</TEXT>
