<FIRST>r a PM-IngersollMoves     10-19 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ingersoll Moves,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ingersoll Publications Names New President, Executive VP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ingersoll Publications Co. has announced
the appointment of a new president and executive vice president.
   Ralph Ingersoll II, chairman and chief executive officer of the
Princeton-based company, said this week that Robert M. Jelenic is
taking over the jobs of president and chief operating officer.
   Jean B. Clifton will become executive vice president, treasurer
and chief financial officer.
   Ingersoll, 43, will take on the additional responsibilities of
editor-in-chief of the company. He succeeds John Wilpers, who the
company said resigned to pursue other interests in his hometown of
Boston.
   The job of president had been vacant for a year, with Ingersoll
serving as acting president.
   Jelenic, 39, of Lawrenceville, N.J., joined Ingersoll
Publications in 1988 as executive vice president for operations. He
was involved in the start-up of The St. Louis Sun, which began
publishing last month, and will continue as president and chief
executive officer of the St. Louis Sun Publishing Co., Ingersoll
said.
   Ms. Clifton, 28, of Yardley, Pa., succeeds Michael A. Appelbaum,
who resigned last week. She began at Ingersoll in 1987 as executive
financial assistant in charge of financing projects in the United
States and Britain.
   Ingersoll Publications has more than 40 daily and 200 non-daily
newspapers in the United States and Europe. The privately held
company has more than 11,000 employees and has said its 1989 sales
will exceed $800 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
