<FIRST>u w PM-Quake-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0557-a0561-a0566 10-19 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0557-a0561-a0566,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Will Visit Northern California Quake Area Friday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today he will visit
Northern California on Friday to get a first-hand look at
earthquake damage and ``to provide encouragement'' to victims.
   ``We will stay on top of it,'' the president vowed.
   He announced his travel plans at a picture-taking session in the
Oval Office as he met with Vice President Dan Quayle and
Transportation Secretary Samuel K. Skinner, just back from their
own inspection tour of the stricken San Francisco Bay area.
   White House aides said Bush would spend about three hours in the
bay area.
   The visit will include a helicopter survey of the affected areas
and the president will also meet with local officials, said
presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
   The president cited an ``all-out federal effort'' in responding
to the earthquake.
   ``Our hearts go out to the victims of this disaster and I will
be going out there tomorrow to take a look and to provide
encouragement to people,'' the president said.
   He voiced special praise for the Red Cross and other volunteer
efforts, saying: ``Thank God for the volunteers.''
   He said volunteers helping in the earthquake effort exemplified
what he meant in various speeches by ``a thousand points of light.''
   Bush thanked Quayle and Skinner for visiting the stricken area.
The president also said he had spoken by phone Wednesday night with
California Gov. George Deukmejian, who the president said expressed
satisfaction with federal efforts.
   He praised volunteer organizations for responding with ``this
concern for their neighbors that just exemplifies the volunteer
concept.''
   Bush said the visit by Quayle and Skinner ``did signal very much
of a concern on the part of the federal government.''
   ``We will stay on top of it. We will be in touch with the state
officials who in turn are dealing with the local officials
there...We're doing what we should do,'' Bush said.
   He said that ``there was a preparation here that was very, very
sound,'' noting earthquake simulation exercises conducted by the
Federal Emergency Management Ageny last August.
   Asked by Bush in front of reporters and cameras to give his own
evaluation of the situation, Quayle said: ``I think volunteerism
and preparation are the two important lessons.''
   Skinner told Bush that, as far as he could determine, there were
no outstanding requests from California state or local officials
that weren't currently being met by the federal governmemnt.
   As he met with the officials, the president held in his lap
several Bay area newsapers, topped by a San Jose Mercury with the
huge headline: ``MASSIVE QUAKE.''
   The president, whose administration came under criticism from
Congress and local officials for not responding faster when
Hurricane Hugo devastated South Carolina last month, has been
making forceful promises over the past two days of federal aid to
earthquake victims.
   On Wednesdsay, he declared his administration will ``take every
step and make every effort'' to aid the San Francisco area.
</TEXT>
