<FIRST>r w PM-SFQuake-Congress 1stLd-Writethru a0465 10-19 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0465,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake Funds Cut as Quake Threat Lingers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake-Federal Response Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 2, We've had, to CORRECT Walgren's party.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government is spending 40 percent
less on reducing earthquake hazards than it spent a decade ago even
though scientists predict more major temblors, not only in
California but in the South and Northeast.
   ``We've had essentially no funding for several years,'' Rep.
Doug Walgren, D-Pa., said Wednesday. ``It's hard for the public and
government to be serious about something that may or may not happen
next year.''
   President Bush asked Congress this year to cut $3.1 million _ or
about 5 percent _ from the earthquake research and emergency
preparedness programs of four key agencies.
   U.S. Geological Survey experts told the House subcommittee n
science, research and technology that Tuesday's quake in the San
Francisco Bay region raises their concerns another one of similar
size will occur closer to the city _ but not in the near future.
   ``We're talking about decades rather than days or weeks,'' said
Robert Wesson of the USGS. ``It might be slightly more likely we
could have an earthquake along the fault but in an area to the
north.''
   But Wesson said he doubts the Bay area faces an earthquake that
would rival the 1906 San Francisco quake, which experts calculated
at an 8.3 magnitude on the later-developed Richter scale.
   ``I don't think we expect a magnitude 8 earthquake in the San
Francisco area,'' he said.
   Tuesday's quake registered a 6.9 on the Richter scale, close to
the power of last December's earthquake in Soviet Armenia.
   The USGS had warned the House subcommittee in June to expect an
earthquake of least 6.5 magnitude in the San Francisco area in the
next 30 years.
   Other officials have said areas alog active faults in the East
also may face a quake greater than 7 magnitude in the next 20
years. They said Charleston, S.C.; Buffalo, N.Y., and Memphis,
Tenn., are possible sites.
   Meanwhile, a draft presidential executive order prepared by an
interagency task force to improve the safety of federal buildings
in quake-prone areas has languished in the White House's budget
office since 1986.
   Sen. Albert Gore, D-Tenn., blames inertia in Congress and the
Reagan and Bush administrations for a failure to earthquake
response capabilities even though the technology is readily
available.
   ``It's partly the case of not thinking about fixing the roof
until it's raining, and then not fixing it because it is raining,''
Gore said Wednesday.
   Congress in 1977 established the National Earthquake Reductions
Hazard Program to coordinate research into quakes and improve
preparedness.
   But annual federal spending on the effort has dropped from $94.4
million to less than $66 million in fiscal 1989. This year, Bush
asked Congress to cut the program to $62.9 million.
   As a result, according to the Senate Commerce, Science and
Transportation Committee, regional seismic networks covering the
central and eastern states have been cut back sharply along with
programs to develop safer buildings, roads and highways.
   Supporters of the program also say the Federal Emergency
Management Agency has been languid in carrying out its designated
lead role for implementing the 1977 law.
   The agency coordinates its quake-related activities with the
Geological Survey, the National Science Foundation and the National
Institute of Standards and Technology.
   A committee of outside experts appointed by FEMA concluded in
1987 that FEMA's performance was ``unacceptable.'' It recommended
switching the leadership role to the USGS but also called for
tripling _ to $199 million annually _ what the government spends on
earthquake preparedness.
   That panel said much of its recommended increase should go
toward developing supercomputers that might enable scientists to
better predict when and where earthquakes will occur and enhance
emergency response capabilities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
