<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0537,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saudi Foreign Minister Meets Assad; Christian Official Sets Deadline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Gen. Aoun advisor saying parliamentary
deputies should come home if no progess made; picks up 3th graf `Arab diplomats...';
SUBS 9th graf `The Christians...' with 1 graf to conform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia's foreign minister met with
President Hafez Assad today to work out a plan for the withdrawal
of Syrian troops from Lebanon as part of a settlement of that
nation's civil war.
   In Taif, Saudi Arabia, sources at the meeting of the Lebanese
parliament said the Saudi government also was trying to satisfy
Christian demands for withdrawing Syria's 40,000 troops withdraw
from Lebanon.
   In Beirut, an aide to Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun today
urged Christian lawmakers to leave the conference if there is no
agreement by Friday.
   ``We demand clear guarantees that the Syrians would withdraw,''
said Farouk Abillama, secretary general of Aoun's Foreign Ministry
and one of the general's closest advisers.
   Abillama, after a meeting with the Christian leader, told
reporters that Maronite Christian parliamentary deputies have
agreed to political reform that would shift some power to the
Moslems.
   ``So let them give us something in return,'' he said. The
Christian deputies ``should return in 24 hours if they fail to
reach agreement,'' he said at midday.
   Arab diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Saudi
Foreign Minister Prince Saud arrived unexpectedly in Damascus late
Wednesday carrying a letter from King Fahd on the issue.
   Presidential spokesman Jibrane Kourieh said Syrian Vice
President Abdul-Halim Khaddam and Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa
also attended the meeting.
   Saud was expected to meet with Lebanese Christians in Taif later
today to discuss results of the trip.
   The Lebanese parliament has been meeting in Taif under the
auspices of the Arab League for the past 20 days to try to settle
that nation's 14-year-old civil war.
   Talks have been at a standstill for days over the Christians'
call for guarantees that the Syrians will withdraw.
   The Syrians have been in Lebanon since 1976 under an Arab League
peacekeeping mandate and have become the main power brokers in the
country.
   The Christians, led by Aoun, charge that Damascus violated its
mandate by siding with the Moslems and have declared a ``war of
liberation'' against the Syrians.
   Conference sources said Saud has advised the Christians that the
guarantees they seek would be contained in amendments to a peace
accord.
   They also said Syria's agreement to the proposed amendments
would cool opposition from Lebanon's Moslem lawmakers and allow the
Taif conference to move ahead to discussion of a new power-sharing
agreement.
   The 33 Christian and 30 Moslem lawmakers have agreed to
political reforms that would give some of the power of the
traditionally dominant Christians to Moslems.
   But Aoun has insisted that without guarantees of a Syrian
pullout a peace settlement cannot be completed. Any peace accord
worked out in Taif must be approved by the militia commanders in
Lebanon.
   An Arab League mediating committee of Saudi Arabia, Morocco and
Algeria has proposed a two-year phased withdrawal of the Syrians
from the Beirut area.
   The troops would be redeployed in Lebanon's eastern Bekaa Valley
until a strong central government were established and the nation
signed a security pact with Syria.
   Aoun, however, has insisted that Syrian troops begin leaving
Lebanon as soon a charter for national reconciliation is ratified
by a parliamentiary session in Beirut.
</TEXT>
