<FIRST>r a PM-BodiesFound     10-19 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bodies Found,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Search More Farms After Bodies Found</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AMANDA DAVIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHILLICOTHE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities searching for missing
transients have continued digging at a farm where they found the
bodies of three unidentified men buried in a barn.
   Members of a police task force formed last week used a backhoe
Wednesday around a well between a farmhouse and the barn where the
bodies were found Monday in shallow graves.
   Investigators searched two other sites in the Livingston County,
northeast of Kansas City, but would not say exactly where.
   Sheriff's deputies began digging last week at the 40-acre farm
of Ray and Faye Copeland after arresting the couple Oct. 9 and
charging them with conspiracy to steal in an alleged cattle swindle.
   The bodies were found on another farm about 12 miles south of
the Copeland home. Neil Bryan, owner of the farm, said the
75-year-old Copeland had worked for him doing odd jobs for 20 years.
   A man who said he rented the farm until about a week ago, John
Hovey, said Copeland warned him and his four children to stay out
of the barn.
   Asked if he noticed anything, Hovey said: ``Just the stench. It
stunk in the barn. I thought an animal had crawled in there and
died.''
   Authorities declined to say if the Copelands were murder
suspects. No charges have been filed except the conspiracy to steal
charge, but the squad has said that the search was for several
missing transients who have worked for them.
   Bryan is not a suspect, authorities said.
   The charge against the Copelands alleges they bought cattle with
a check that bounced, then sold the cattle without making good on
the check.
   Copeland and his 68-year-old wife remained in jail on bonds of
$25,000 each.
</TEXT>
