<FIRST>r i PM-Greece-Rashid     10-19 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece-Rashid,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judges Turn Down Suspected Terrorist's Release Plea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court today refused to release
a Palestinian wanted in the United States for the fatal 1982
bombing of a Pan Am jet over Hawaii.
   The three-member council that rules on requests for the
temporary release of people held in pretrial custody said that it
had no jurisdiction over the matter because Mohammed Rashid's
extradition was in the hands of the justice minister.
   American officials have said Rashid's case is a test of Greece's
willingness to fight terrorism.
   Rashid, 39, has been held by Greece since his arrest on a false
passport charge in May 1988. The Supreme Court last May upheld a
U.S. request for his extradition but also said the final decision
rests with the justice minister.
   The Greek government put the matter on hold after the June
elections, when the country was ruled by a conservative-Communist
coalition. The present caretaker government has a mandate only to
lead the nation to elections on Nov. 5 and will not make any
foreign policy decisions, such as one on Rashid's extradition.
   The Palestinian is accused of planting a bomb on a Pan Am jumbo
jet in 1982. A Japanese teenager was killed and 15 other people
injured in the blast over Hawaii.
   On Sept. 14, Rashid asked a public prosecutor to present his
case to the appeals court council, saying that his continued
detention after the Supreme Court ruling ``stretches out my
detention indefinitely, thus violating basic human rights.''
   Rashid was first held for entering Greece on a false passport.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization claims that Rashid is one
of its members and that he is the victim of a conspiracy intended
to present Palestinians as terrorists.
</TEXT>
