<FIRST>u a PM-Espionage     10-19 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Espionage,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendant Ordered Held Without Bail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal magistrate today ordered a
former Marine and Air Force communications officer held without
bail on charges he passed classified material to the Soviet Union.
   Magistrate W. Curtis Sewell said he found ``a preponderance of
evidence'' against Frank Nesbitt, 44, to send the case to a grand
jury.
   Nesbitt was arrested last week at a hotel in McLean, Va., by the
FBI and wss charged with delivering and attempting to deliver
unauthorized information to agents of the Soviet government.
   At today's hearing, FBI Special Agent Lizzie Cassell, who
related conversations she had with Nesbitt starting on Oct. 4.
   Ms. Cassell said Nesbitt came to the FBI office in Washington,
D.C., accompanied by an official from the U.S. Embassy in
Guatemala, to tell his story.
   According to the agent, Nesbitt left his home near Memphis,
Tenn., last June and began an odyssey that took him from Central
and South America to the Soviet Union and back to Guatemala.
   Ms. Cassell said Nesbitt told her he sought citizenship, housing
and a job in the Soviet Union. ``He stated to me he had defected,''
she testified.
   She said Nesbitt gave classified communications intelligence
information to the Soviets during his 10-day stay in Moscow and
also provided Soviet agents with diagrams and charts.
   Nesbitt's court-appointed attorney, Gregory English, said his
client believed the information that he passed on was unclassified.
He said Nesbitt also had broached the idea of working as a double
agent when he voluntarily went to the FBI.
   Nesbitt served from 1963 to 1966 in the Air Force's Electronic
Security Command in West Germany and from 1969 to 1979 in the
Marine Corps, where he dealt with classified
communication-gathering.
   He did not testify at today's court proceeding.
</TEXT>
