<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Rebels     10-19 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Rebels,0383</SECOND>
<UNK>Military Investigation Says Communist Rebels Killed Americans</UNK>
<DATELINE>SAN FERNANDO, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military said an
investigation completed today proved Communist rebels were
responsible for killing two Americans the day Vice President Dan
Quayle arrived on a visit last month.
   The rebel New Peoples' Army has not claimed responsibility for
the Sept. 26 slaying of William H. Thompson, 45, and Donald G.
Buchner, 44, who were gunned down by six assailants who sprang from
a passenger jeep and opened fire on the victims' car near Capas in
Tarlac province.
   They were civilian technicians working for Ford Aerospace Corp.
at Camp O'Donnell, a U.S. military installation about 60 miles
north of Manila.
   ``We have established the Communist angle in the incident,''
Capt. Carlos Flores, deputy chief of the Criminal Investigation
Service in Central Luzon, told reporters.
   The regional command of the Philippine Constabulary said the
investigation's findings were based on captured rebel documents and
witness accounts, but Flores refused to release the report or give
details. He said he will submit the report to law enforcement
agencies.
   Flores said an assassination plan for the two Americans was
captured from two rebel leaders, including Danilo Cunanan, alleged
deputy commander of the rebel Mariano Garcia Brigade, who was
arrested Oct. 5 in San Fernando.
   Cunanan was killed soon after his arrest when he allegedly tried
to grab the rifle of his guard. His colleague escaped, fleeing with
his guard's weapon, the military said.
   Flores said initial results showed that fingerprints found in
the vehicles used in the killings included those of Noli Paniza,
alleged chief of the rebel brigade.He said the other assailants
were unknown.
   In April, rebels killed U.S. Army Col. James ``Nick'' Rowe as he
drove to work to the headquarters of the Joint U.S. Military
Assistance Group in suburban Quezon City.In October, 1987, rebels
killed three Americans in separate attacks outside Clark Air Base.
   Clark is among six military installations run by Americans under
an agreement with the Philippines, whose lease expires Sept. 1991.
   Marxist insurgents, who are waging a 20-year old rebellion, have
vowed to kill Americans involved in counter-insurgency. They have
also called for the closure of the bases and threatened to launch
more attacks.
</TEXT>
