<FIRST>u i PM-EastGermany 2ndLd-Writethru   10-19 0837</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0555,0861</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Criticizens New Leader as Too Conservative</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD report of protest, reax from Gorbachev and
Poland. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY8,12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders today criticized East Germany's
new leader, Egon Krenz, for his dedication to hard-line
conservatism that has caused dissent across the country. A
pro-democracy protest was reported hours after Krenz was appointed.
   Krenz, who took over from Erich Honecker on Wednesday, made it
clear in a speech that the Communist Party will resist
pro-democracy movements like those under way in Hungary and Poland.
   The change in leadership was praised in other East bloc
countries, but opposition leaders here said Krenz's style will not
end dissatisfaction that has caused street protests and driven tens
of tens of thousands of East Germans to flee West.
   Activists said today that about 1,000 people held a peaceful
protest in the northern city of Greifswald hours after Krenz was
named party chief. The protesters reportedly demanded democratic
reforms and the release of those detained during demonstrations
earlier in the month.
   Reinhardt Schultz, a co-founder of the New Forum opposition
group, said today, ``I don't think that the protest movement will
settle for a few cosmetic changes.''
   Another government critic, East German author Rolf Schneider,
told West Berlin's RIAS radio in an interview Wednesday: ``The
crisis will keep dragging on.''
   ``Egon Krenz doesn't enjoy any particular trust among the
people,'' said Baerbel Bohley, another New Forum leader. He blamed
the 52-year-old leader for unleashing police forces that attacked
pro-democracy demonstrators in East Berlin on Oct. 7 and Oct. 8.
   Communist Party sources have said Krenz ordered security forces
to use more restraint in later demonstrations.
   The Communist Party's Central Committee named Krenz to succeed
his hard-line mentor, 77-year-old Honecker, who ruled the nation 18
years. Krenz, the youngest member of the ruling Politburo, also
will assume the duties of head of state and head of the military,
replacing Honecker in all three roles.
   Honecker said he stepped down because of health reasons, but
rising public opposition to his authoritarian rule had fueled
pressure for his resignation.
   More than 53,000 East Germans have fled the West in recent weeks
via Hungary, Poland and Czechoslovakia. In Austria, authorities
said today that more than 1,000 East German refugees crossed from
Hungary into Austria since Wednesday morning. Most have gone on to
West Germany, where they are granted automatic citizenship.
   Addressing East Germans on television a few hours after his
elevation, Krenz said discussion of change is important and
promised the ruling party ``would initiate a new course.''
   But he stressed that ``without the Communist Party there would
be no German Democratic Republic'' and indicated he does not intend
to enter dialogue with opposition groups agitating for a more open
society, free elections and a free press.
   ``Our society already has enough democratic forums in which
different interests from various parts of the population'' can
express themselves, Krenz said.
   He hinted that rigid restrictions on travel abroad could be
modified or lifted. The difficulty of getting permission to travel
outside the country has been a chief complaint of protesters.
   The new leader also accused West German officials of meddling in
East Germany's affairs.
   The state-controlled Der Morgan newspaper in East Berlin said
today that ``at the center of the demands and suggestions (for
change) is the longing for deeds and decisions.''
   The newspaper called for ``open, productive and democratic''
discussions of the nation's problems but said they should take
place within the current socialist structure.
   West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher, speaking at
an East-West security conference in Frankfurt, urged Krenz to make
``fundamental reforms'' in the troubled nation and to make good on
a pledge to talk to ``all levels of society.''
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, whose reforms have been
rejected by East German leaders but embraced by much of the
populace, expressed confidence in a telegram published today that
Krenz will find solutions to the problems facing his country.
   Poland's Communist president, Wojciech Jaruzelski, commended the
contribution of Honecker to the development of Polish-East German
relations but said the new leadership will benefit the country.
   However, Poland's pro-Solidarity newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza said
Krenz may be a disappointing change for those who want greater
change.
   Poland has the East bloc's first government not led by
Communists. The 24-member Cabinet has only four Communist ministers.
   Hungary, which also is moving toward democratic reforms,
predicted that Krenz may only be a transitional leader until a
party congress due in May.
   The Magyar Nemzet daily, one of the more outspoken state-run
newspapers, said that meeting could bring a breakthrough for more
outspoken reformers.
   Two other Politburo members who had been heavily criticized
within the party lost their jobs Wednesday.
   They were Joachim Herrmann, 60, who ran the country's news media
and Guenter Mittag, 63, who made the East German economy the envy
of its East European neighbors but had come under criticism for a
lack of innovation.
</TEXT>
