<FIRST>r a PM-MineExplosion     10-19 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mine Explosion,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kentucky Mine Where 10 Died in Explosion Found to Have 280 Safety
Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHEATCROFT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal mine safety officials will
require the mine where 10 men died in an explosion last month to
correct 280 safety violations before it is allowed to reopen, a
spokesman said.
   A list of citations against Pyro Mining Co. was released
Wednesday by the federal Mine Safety and Health Administration
office in Arlington, Va.
   The violations, which included 253 judged to be ``significant
and substantive,'' were found during an inspection following the
blast at the William Station Mine near Wheatcroft.
   The western Kentucky mine has been shut since the Sept. 13
methane gas explosion, the nation's worst mining disaster since
1984.
   MSHA spokeman Joey Lucas said Pyro, which owns the mine, would
``have to submit necessary plans, make required changes before the
mine is allowed to reopen.''
   Attempts to reach officials at Costain Co. Inc., Pyro's parent
company, Wednesday and today were unsuccessful. A receptionist at
Costain's office in Evansville, Ind., said no officials were
available for comment.
   The list released by MSHA did not give details of the violations.
   Mine safety officials found 12 violations ``highly likely'' to
result in an accident or illness, while 241 were likely to result
in an accident or illness.
   Eighteen violations represented a ``high degree'' of negligence,
MSHA found, while 246 violations represented a moderate degree.
   Of the citations, 37 were issued in the area of fire protection;
43 in the area of electrical equipment-general; 16 in roof support;
and 18 in the ventilation category.
   Costain President Charles Schulties said earlier that MSHA gave
informal approval for the removal of a ventilation barrier at
William Station Mine, an action that investigators say may have led
to the fatal explosion.
   Schulties said MSHA was ``well aware of this ventilation change
we were going to make,'' the Lexington Herald-Leader reported
Wednesday.
   The barrier was knocked down about 15 minutes before the fatal
explosion.
   However, Rexford Music, manager of MSHA's western Kentucky
district, said MSHA had not approved the barrier's removal. Music
charged that Schulties was ``just trying to shift some
responsibility, and it's not there to shift.''
   Shortly after the accident, MSHA reported that the Pyro mine had
been cited for 1,508 violations and fined $215,757 over the past
seven years.
</TEXT>
