<FIRST>r a PM-DeConcini-Fund     10-19 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DeConcini-Fund,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former DeConcini Campaign Treasurer Indicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former campaign treasurer for Sen. Dennis
DeConcini has been indicted on five counts of mail fraud in the
theft of $500,000 from the senator's campaign fund.
   Thomas Karlsen, indicted Wednesday, was contrite and planned to
``do everything he can to make restitution,'' said his lawyer,
Craig Mehrens. ``He deeply regrets any embarrassment he has caused
the senator.''
   ``There is no great joy in seeing a friend indicted,'' DeConcini
said. ``I was very upset about this and still am, because I feel
very much violated.''
   DeConcini, D-Ariz., said he used his own money to pay about
$50,000 in campaign-related bills that Karlsen did not pay. In
addition, an audit of the fund will cost him $30,000 to $40,000,
DeConcini said.
   The indictment outlines charges dating to 1982 and accuses
Karlsen of devising a scheme to convert funds from political
contributions to his personal use.
   If convicted, Karlsen could face a maximum penalty of five years
in prison and a $250,000 fine on each of the five counts.
   Mehrens said much of the money went into tax shelters that the
Internal Revenue Service later disallowed. As a result, Karlsen
ended up owing the IRS, prompting him to divert more campaign
funds, the lawyer said.
   Karlsen also served briefly as campaign treasurer for Gov. Rose
Mofford but resigned shortly before the DeConcini fund was found to
be short in April.
