<FIRST>r w PM-Quake-Communications 1stLd-Writethru a04istrict 10-19
0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Communications, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0466,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phone Network Better Equipped to Withstand Natural Disasters</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS pvs grafs 4-6, This time, to UPDATE with record long-distance
volume and CORRECT spelling of Bedminster, N.J. Picks up 7th graf pvs,
When Hurricane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Computer controls and improved construction
techniques are dramatically improving the ability of the nation's
telephone network to withstand natural disasters such as hurricanes
and earthquakes, telephone officials say.
   During Tuesday's earthquake in Northern California, millions of
callers simultaneously went to their telephones to inquire of
friends and relatives ``Are you OK?'' or ``Did you see the
earthquake on TV?''
   That huge upsurge in long-distance calling _ more than 2{ times
normal nationwide between 8 p.m. and midnight Eastern Daylight Time
_ could have caused chaos 20 or 30 years ago.
   This time, computers rerouted calls and selectively blocked
others to keep the system from experiencing gridlock, said Jim
Nelson, director of AT&amp;T's network operations center in Bedminster,
N.J.
   AT&amp;T spokesman Herb Linnen said the company received a record
144.7 million long-distance calls nationwide between midnight
Tuesday and midnight Wednesday.
   Approximately 123.6 million calls were completed Wednesday,
Linnen said.
   Volume early today in Northern California ``has diminished but
continues to be above normal,'' Linnen added.
   Thanks to improved phone equipment, ``We are able to manage the
volume to at least not bring the system to a halt much more
effectively than ever before. ... We don't allow that extra load to
bog the system down,'' Nelson said.
   When Hurricane Hugo slammed ashore in South Carolina last month,
people in Charleston, S.C., received long-distance calls from
relatives during the worst of the storm, Ted Creech, a spokesman
for Southern Bell, said Wednesday.
   ``The reason they had that capability is that some 80 percent of
our cables are underground,'' Creech said. Much of that cable is
fiber-optic, which Creech said ``is much less susceptible to
moisture or corrosion.''
   Of Southern Bell's 1 million customers in South Carolina, 13,523
remained without service Wednesday, mostly because of water damage
to inside wiring or downed lines to their homes, Creech said.
   ``By far, especially in this kind of situation, underground
cable has proved to be the best in terms of service reliability,''
Creech said.
   Solid-state components, reinforced buildings, underground
fiber-optic cable and redundant systems have improved the phone
system dramatically from the days when high winds, snow or ice
could knock out service for days.
   ``The physical construction has improved dramatically, just like
the building construction on the high-rises'' in California, Nelson
said.
   Equally powerful is AT&amp;T's network of computers that sense where
backlogs are developing and reroute traffic through other parts of
the country.
   ``Unlike 20 or 30 years ago where you had very defined routing
paths ... that could easily overload and congest, we essentially
have a spider web around the country,'' Nelson said.
   ``The computers are smart enough to use any of the capability
anywhere in the country. We can talk to those computers ... to make
sure they allow enough of those calls through without gridlock,''
Nelson said.
   Sue Galloway, district manager for Pacific Bell's network in
Southern California, said Pacific's phone network has been designed
to withstand the largest earthquakes.
   ``We've done an awful lot of reinforcing ... at our central
office locations, and we've done a lot of changes of our network,''
she said.
   To keep the phone system operating, AT&amp;T blocked 60 to 70
percent of the incoming calls to the San Francisco area and 30
percent of the outgoing calls, Nelson said.
   US Sprint, the nation's No. 3 long-distance carrier, doubled its
volume of calls immediately after the earthquake Tuesday night,
said Al Butson, Sprint's director of network management and control
in Kansas City, Mo.
   Calls were running 40 percent above normal on Wednesday, Butson
said.
   Sprint spokesman Phil Hermanson said the Sprint network
``functioned very well, no losses, no outages. We weren't hit.''
   MCI officials said their system was functioning at capacity, but
with no breakdowns.
   Like AT&amp;T, MCI and Sprint were blocking many calls to the San
Francisco area.
</TEXT>
