<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Panama     10-19 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Panama,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speedier Evacuation of Dependents Under Consideration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is considering a
speed-up of its withdrawal of U.S. military dependents from Panama,
the White House said today.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said that since last spring, 6,300
Defense Department personnel had either been relocated onto U.S.
bases in Panama or sent home. But there are still roughly 11,000
dependents in the country.
   The Washington Times reported today that the newly appointed
U.S. military commander in Panama, Gen. Maxwell R. Thurman, has
asked his superiors to evacuate most dependents from Panama.
   The newspaper, citing military sources in Panama, said Thurman
wanted the dependents evacuated to heighten the sense of war among
his troops in Panama, where the United States has pressed for the
removal of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega as leader of the Central
American country.
   Noriega is wanted in the United States on indictments charging
drug trafficking. He recently quashed an attempted coup that
received minimal support from U.S. forces.
   Fitzwater told reporters the administration was reviewing
whether the withdrawal of dependents ``should be accelerated (and)
whether there should be any special efforts made.''
   The ``ultimate purpose,'' he said, has always been to have
``people leave Panama and return to the United States.''
   ``We have been reviewing this matter since the spring, and we
announced a program in May which called for the return to the
United States of many of the dependents in Panama,'' he said.
   As of July 1, he said, 6,300 Defense Department employees and
their dependents had either been sent home or relocated from
civilian housing into U.S. military installations in Panama.
   Currently, he said, the United States has 10,000 soldiers
permanently assigned to Panama, 2,500 military people there on
temporary duty, 7,700 military dependents, 2,700 U.S. civilian
Pentagon employees and 3,300 civilian dependents.
   Asked whether the White House considered the situation in Panama
akin to a state of war, Fitzwater replied:
   ``We have always said that there is a status involving some
danger in Panama. That was the reason for our first actions, to try
to move people, certainly dependents of military people, back onto
the base.
   ``You'll recall incidents of harassment, people in some cases
being assaulted physically. And so there has always been a
dangerous situation there that we were trying to alleviate,'' he
said.
   But pressed on whether it was amounted to war, Fitzwater said,
``We haven't used that term.''
</TEXT>
