<DOCNO> AP891019-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1217EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Hastings 2ndLd-Writethru a0619 10-19 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hastings, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0619,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Specter Says He Will Vote to Acquit Miami Jurist</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: CORRECTS Specter to R-Pa. sted D-Pa. in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The vice chairman of the Senate panel that
heard four weeks of evidence against federal Judge Alcee L.
Hastings this summer said today he will vote to acquit the Miami
jurist in his impeachment trial.
   ``On the totality of this record ... weighing the incriminating
circumstantial inferences against the exonerating factors and
giving due weight to his other unblemished lifetime record, I
conclude there is insufficent evidence to convict,'' Sen. Arlen
Specter, R-Pa., said of the bribery conspiracy charge against
Hastings.
   Specter, the top Republican on the evidence panel, also said in
a 76-page paper that he would vote to acquit Hastings of charges
that he lied to a jury that found him innocent of bribery
conspiracy charges in 1983.
   Prosecutors in that case told the jury that testimony from
Hastings was false, Specter said. ``Obviously the jury did not
accept those arguments.''
   He said impeachment evidence that Hastings had improperly
disclosed information obtained from a wiretap ``was neither
convincing nor substantial.''
   Specter's comments came as the Senate prepared to close its
doors and deliberate the charges against Hastings.
   In final arguments the Senate was urged on Wednesday to
disregard race as a factor in the case and decide the matter soley
on the facts.
   ``There have been a lot of cases in our judicial system in which
race has been a problem,'' Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., told the
Senate on Wednesday. ``This isn't one of them or I would be the
first to tell you.''
   Hastings, the first black federal judge in Florida history, is
accused of conspiring to get a $150,000 payoff and lying to a jury
that acquitted him of the charges in 1983.
   He also is accused of improperly disclosing information obtained
from a government wiretap.
   The Senate heard final arguments Wednesday and planned to
deliberate behind closed doors today. A vote is expected before the
weekend.
   ``I wish I could be a fly on the wall for those deliberations,''
said the 53-year-old Hastings as he emerged from the Senate chamber.
   Conviction by the Senate on any of the 17 impeachment articles
approved by the House in August 1988 would immediately remove
Hastings from the U.S. District bench in Miami and stop his $89,500
salary.
   It would make Hastings the sixth official in history removed by
impeachment. The most recent was Judge Harry Claiborne of Nevada in
1986 who fought in vain to remain on the bench while serving a tax
fraud sentence.
   District Judge Walter Nixon of Mississippi, convicted of lying
to a grand jury, is also currently fighting to remain on the
federal bench.
   Conyers, a leading House proponent of civil rights legislation,
warned against any notion that race was a factor in the Hastings
case.
   He said Hastings was given a position of trust ``but he has
betrayed that trust and he has betrayed those who looked to him for
leadership.''
   ``We did not wage the civil rights struggle in order to trade
one form of judicial corruption for another,'' Conyers said.
   The Senate galleries, filled about equally with black and white
faces, broke into applause after Hastings himself took the Senate
floor and denied he was claiming racial discrimination as part of
his defense.
   ``I am not guilty of having committed any crime _ that is my
defense,'' Hastings said. ``Please act fairly.''
   Hastings attorney Terence J. Anderson of Miami told senators the
evidence was only circumstantial.
   ``What you have here is Swiss cheese,'' he told the Senate.
   Hastings appeared at a Miami restaurant at a time set by an FBI
undercover agent who was part of a ``sting'' operation against a
Washington lawyer claiming the power to influence the judge's
actions.
   The judge also ordered the government to return $845,000 in
confiscated funds as Washington lawyer William Borders said he
would in negotiations with the undercover agent.
   Both actions were offered by Borders as proof that Hastings
would do as he was told and change two prison sentences to
probation for a $150,000 bribe.
   House managers rejected a contention that the impeachment trial
was unfair in light of his previous acquittal.
   ``What if all the facts indicate the judge's guilt?'' Rep. John
Bryant, D-Texas, told the Senate. ``We deeply believe that Judge
Hastings conspired to obtain a bribe from defendants in his court,
that to avoid conviction for this crime he fabricated evidence and
lied to a federal jury 14 times.''
</TEXT>
