<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Bombings 3rdLd-Writethru   10-19 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Bombings, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0591,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Throws Out Convictions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with one suspect arrested again;
picks up 10th pvs: The prosecution's ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court today threw out the convictions
of four people blamed in a 1975 IRA terrorist bombing after the
government said investigators may have faked evidence.
   Relatives and others in the gallery of Old Bailey court cheered
as Lord Lane, the chief justice, announced that the convictions had
been reversed. The court also reversed the convictions of two of
the four in a second bombing.
   ``I've been in prison for 15 years for something I didn't do,''
Gerard Conlon, 35, shouted to a cheering crowd outside the court as
he walked free.
   Two co-defendants also were freed. A fourth was freed and then
immediately arrested in connection with a murder case in Belfast.
   In addition to Conlon, the defendants included Carole
Richardson, 32, Patrick Armstrong, 39, and Paul Hill, 35. They were
sentenced to life in prison for killing five people in an explosion
at a pub in Guildford, southwest of London, on October 5, 1974.
   But new evidence ``throws such doubt upon the honesty and
integrity of a number of the Surrey officers investigating this
case in 1974 that the Crown now feels unable to say that the
convictions of any of the four are safe or satisfactory,'' Roy
Amlot of the Office of Public Prosecutions told the hearing.
   Amlot said there was evidence that officers had altered notes of
interviews and, in one case, covered up the fact that a defendant
had been interviewed after being charged, a violation of English
law.
   ``It is clear that a full criminal investigation of these
matters is called for,'' Amlot added.
   Armstrong and Hill also were convicted of a pub bombing in the
London suburb of Woolwich on Nov. 6, 1974, which killed two people
and injured 26. The appeals court also reversed those convictions.
   Hill, who was also serving a life sentence for the murder of a
British soldier in Northern Ireland, was rearrested as he left
court. He was to fly today to Belfast, where his attorneys said
they would ask a court to release him on bail pending an appeal of
the murder conviction.
   The prosecution's case in the bombings was based solely on
confessions the four repudiated in court. The convictions were
upheld in 1977 even after four members of an Irish Republic Army
gang made their own detailed confessions in the attacks.
   The presence in court of Ireland's ambassador to Britain, Andrew
O'Rourke, reflected the Irish government's efforts to have this
case and other bombing cases from the 1970s reviewed.
   In 1980, Lord Denning, then the chief civil judge in England,
ruled against the six, who claimed police had beaten them.
   Justice, a non-partisan legal reform group led by a former
appeals judge, said in July that false confessions were a leading
cause of unjust criminal verdicts, of which it estimated there were
15 or more every year in Britain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
