<FIRST>u a PM-Quake-Quayle 2ndLd-Writethru a0546 10-19 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Quayle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0546,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Finds `Great Sadness' on Tour of Quake Damage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 6 grafs after 6th graf, ``I understand ...' with White
House saying Agnos refused to accept phone calls, attend meetings.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Art Agnos said he was ``ticked off''
that Vice President Dan Quayle had time for television cameras but
not for him during a tour of earthquake-damaged areas of the city.
   Quayle, who promised federal relief for earthquake victims after
visiting the Bay area Wednesday, today dismissed the liberal
Democratic mayor's criticism.
   ``I would hope that the mayor would resist any kind of political
rhetoric at this time and concentrate all the energies and all of
our dedication to helping the victims and helping the families of
the victims, and let's get the situation stabilized first,'' Quayle
said on CBS's ``This Morning.''
   And on NBC's ``Today'' show, he said that he thought it was
``very unfortunate to take that kind of a shot at a very difficult
time. ... I was there to help people.''
   Agnos said Wednesday he was ``ticked off'' that Quayle ``flies
around in a helicopter, makes a bunch of television spots'' but
didn't meet with him. The mayor had said before Quayle's visit that
he planned to meet with Quayle to urge immediate federal help.
   ``I understand he was in the Marina and in the shelters and then
left. If he did so without visiting the mayor, I have real
questions about what he was doing here. It may have been just a
publicity stunt,'' Agnos said.
   President Bush said today he would go to the Bay area on Friday
and presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Agnos would
be invited to a session between Bush and local officials.
   Fitzwater denied that the Republican vice president had snubbed
Agnos.
   Agnos was invited to two meetings with Quayle ``and he declined
to attend both meetings,'' Fitzwater said.
   Furthermore, ``we offered to send a helicopter to pick him up
wherever he was and deliver him to the meetings and he declined
that.''
   White House chief of staff John Sununu has ``been trying to
reach him on the phone for several days and he has declined to talk
to us,'' Fitzwater said. ``We regret very much that the mayor of
San Francisco has decided not to cooperate with us in this matter.''
   Quayle met with officials in Alameda County across San Francisco
Bay to assess the need for federal assistance.
   On his tour, Quayle appeared stunned by the magnitude of damage
and loss of life inflicted by the temblor. Quayle and his wife,
Marilyn, spent six hours touring the area by helicopter and on foot
after President Bush authorized federal disaster assistance.
   Upon his return to Washington late Wednesday, Quayle said that
federal aid would be forthcoming.
   Quayle, accompanied by Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner
and Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., met with mayors of more than half a
dozen cities around the bay and emergency officials at the Alameda
Naval Air Station.
   ``My impression was one of great sadness for the number of
people that lost their lives and the families that are impacted,''
Quayle said after seeing crushed cars on collapsed portions of the
San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge and Interstate 880 in Oakland.
   ``You can't help but be impressed by the magnitude of the
earthquake,'' he said. ``To see 880 flattened like a pancake, it's
really a sobering sight.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
