<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Vatican-Soviet     10-19 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Vatican-Soviet,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Official to Moscow for Talks on Gorbachev Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Vatican official left Thursday for
Moscow, apparently to help plan an historic meeting between Pope
John Paul II and President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Archbishop Angelo Sodano, secretary for relations with states,
the equivalent of foreign minister, would meet with Soviet
government officials, according to a brief Vatican announcement.
   His trip follows the visit to Rome in August of Juri Karlov, a
representative of the Soviet Foreign Ministry, who was received by
the pope and gave him a letter from Gorbachev, the Vatican said.
   The statement gave no details, but a Vatican source, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said Sodano clearly was going to prepare
for the Gorbachev visit.
   Gorbachev will meet with the pope during a Nov. 29-Dec. 1 visit.
It would be the first meeting between the head of the Soviet
Communist Party and the leader of the Roman Catholic Church.
</TEXT>
