<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Arrests     10-19 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Arrests,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>15 Dissident Workers Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen dissident workers have been
arrested for organizing illegal strikes as part of a campaign to
promote socialist ideology, police said Thursday.
   Charges will be filed after further investigation, they said.
   Police said the workers were arrested Wednesday in raids on
houses near factories west of Seoul, and more arrests are possible.
   The workers, all college graduates, set up a dissident labor
organization called the Alliance of Democratic Labor Unions last
year and have instigated 20 illegal strikes, police said.
   In a strike at a kitchen utensil manufacturing plant, two
workers and a company executive were burned to death in a fire
started by union members, police said.
   The alliance sought to promote socialism and spread propaganda
bills and newsletters accusing the government of suppressing labor
activity, police said.
   Also on Thursday, about 500 fired teachers continued sit-ins at
offices of the three main opposition parties for a second straight
day, demanding their outlawed labor union be sanctioned.
   The teachers demanded that the three opposition parties, which
control a majority of seats in the 299-member National Assembly,
agree to a bill legalizing the formation of South Korea's first
teachers' union.
   The government outlawed a union formed by dissident teachers
this year and fired about 2,000 teachers who refused to give up
membership. About a dozen union members also were arrested.
   There are about 300,000 primary, middle and high school teachers
in South Korea.
</TEXT>
