<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1322EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Spain 4thLd-Writethru a0612 10-19 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Spain, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0612,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Spanish Foreign Minister Meet</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 11 grafs new with departure statements. Editing throughout
to shorten.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spanish Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez and
President Bush met today and discussed what Bush called ``the
unique role'' Spain can play in furthering democracy in Eastern
Europe and Latin America.
   Both leaders hailed the 90-minutes of talks as a reaffirmation
of close ties between the two nations.
   Gonzalez also extended to Bush an official invitation from King
Juan Carlos to visit Spain.
   Bush said they reviewed Western efforts to bolster the economies
of Poland and Hungary, communist states struggling to enact
political and economic reforms.
   ``Spain's successful transition to strong and flourishing
democracy makes it a powerful model for Eastern European countries
now attempting similar transformations,'' Bush said in departure
remarks.
   ``In supporting democratic change in Eastern Europe, Latin
America and elsewhere, I am convinced that Spain can play a unique
role, for Spain provides the world with a very special example,''
he said.
   Gonzalez, speaking in Spanish, said that in reviewing the
international situation, including arms control, ``we agreed that
the prospects today are encouraging.''
   ``We also underlined the importance of making the greatest
possible effort in disarmament and arms control talks,'' he said.
   He also expressed sorrow for the victims of Tuesday's earthquake
in California.
   Gonzalez was thought to be carrying fresh proposals for bringing
about an elected government in Panama while allowing Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega to remain in the country. The United States wants
Noriega to relinquish power and stand trial here on drug
trafficking charges.
   American officials said Bush and Gonzalez did not discuss Panama
in their initial talks, but it was expected to come up tonight in
their discussion at a private dinner at the White House.
   Gonzalez believes a solution might be possible if the focus on
Panama shifts away from Noriega's personal fate and emphasizes
instead the transfer of power to an elected government.
   His visit took place 16 days after the failed coup attempt
against Noriega by dissident elements of Panama's Defense Forces.
The administration has been searching for new ideas on how to deal
with Noriega, and officials said they were eager to listen to
Gonzalez.
   The official, who briefed reporters on the condition of
anonymity, said there were some areas of agreement and of
disagreement with Gonzalez's proposal.
   ``The point of agreement is that Noriega ought to get out. What
happens after that _ we have a point of view, and perhaps the prime
minister's got a different point of view, and we'll hear it when
he's here,'' the official said.
   Meanwhile, a published report said the newly appointed top U.S.
military commander in Panama has requested the evacuation of most
dependents of American servicemen stationed there.
   The Washington Times reported in today's editions that unnamed
sources in Panama say Gen. Maxwell R. Thurman raised the subject
with Bush earlier this week at a White House dinner.
   The sources told the newspaper Thurman made the proposal to
evacuate some 3,500 dependents of U.S. military personnel in Panama
to heighten the sense of war among U.S. troops. The Times said the
request is being studied by Gen. Colin Powell, chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said today the
administration is considering whether to accelerate its plan,
ongoing since spring, to get all federally employed civilians and
military dependents either relocated to U.S. bases or home to the
United States.
   He said that as of July 1, 6,300 Defense Department employees
and dependents had either been sent home or relocated on the bases.
   The U.S. population break down in Panama, he said, is 12,500
military personnel, 2,700 Pentagon civilians and 11,000 dependents.
   Under Gonzalez's proposal, outlined to American reporters in
Madrid in recent days, a newly elected president in Panama would
have the power to name a new military commander to replace Noriega,
who would have the option to remain in Panama.
   Bush has held out hope Noriega could be extradited to the United
States to face drug smuggling charges. He has given no serious
consideration to determining whether it would be legally possible
to drop the charges in the interest of promoting democracy in
Panama.
</TEXT>
