<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     10-19 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>South African Foreign Minister Confers With Rival Party Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa's foreign minister held
what he called friendly and constructive talks Thursday with the
South-West Africa People's Organization, the group that has fought
South African rule of the territory for 23 years.
   Foreign Minister Pik Botha, on a one-day visit to Namibia, met
with SWAPO and the other nine parties competing in pre-independence
elections planned for Nov. 7-11. No date has been set for
independence, but it is expected early next year.
   Botha said the United Nations-supervised independence process
was on track, but technical matters still needed to be worked out.
He cited Namibia's currency, telecommunications system, and its
participation in a customs union for southern African nations.
   Asked about his meeting with SWAPO leaders, including its
President Sam Nujoma, Botha said it was ``friendly, and I would go
so far as to say constructive.''
   He said South Africa would accept the results of a ``free and
fair election'' and ``was not interested in the ideology or color
of the future government.''
   SWAPO said South Africa was falsely accusing the guerrilla
movement of detaining dissidents and deploying combatants in
southern Angola.
   SWAPO said there was no evidence to support either claim. The
left-leaning organization also accused South Africa of taking
inadequate steps to demobilize Koevoet, a police counterinsurgency
unit active during the guerrillas' independence war.
   A U.N. team that visited Angola and Zambia said they found no
evidence that SWAPO was still holding prisoners, but they could not
account for 315 people.
   A group of U.S. human rights lawyers, the Commission on
Independence for Namibia, last week called for a full accounting of
the missing detainees.
   Relatives of missing people have taken SWAPO to court, trying to
get details on all people held by the organization outside Namibia
since 1980.
   SWAPO said the case is an attempt to embarrass the organization
before the elections. The elections are for an assembly that will
draft a constitution for independent Namibia, which has about 1.3
million people.
   The U.N. independence plan stipulates that a two-thirds majority
within the assembly would be required for adoption of a
constitution.
   But one of the minor parties, the National Patriotic Front, said
SWAPO may be trying to remove the two-thirds requirement because it
fears it won't win such a high percentage.
   Botha said the head of the U.N. monitoring force in Namibia,
Martti Ahtisaari, supported the two-thirds requirement.
   The United Nations will have 1,395 poll watchers monitoring the
elections. Another 500 police supervisors are expected soon, which
would raise the force to 1,500.
   The U.N. Transition Assistance Group in Namibia also consists of
4,650 peacekeepers, and more than 1,500 civilians.
   South Africa, which has ruled the territory since World War I,
signed accords in December with Angola and Cuba agreeing to
independence for Namibia if 50,000 Cuban troops stationed in Angola
are sent home by mid-1991.
</TEXT>
