<FIRST>r a AM-WrongMurderAward     10-19 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wrong Murder Award,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Awards $1.9 Million to Man Who Spent 6{ Years in Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who spent 6{ years in prison for a murder
and robbery he did not commit has been awarded $1.9 million in
damages by a state Court of Claims.
   Robert McLaughlin, 30, was awarded $1.5 million Wednesday for
``loss of liberty, mental stress, anguish and loss of reputation,''
by Judge Adolph Orlando, settling a lawsuit that was filed three
years ago.
   Orlando also ordered the state to pay the former Brooklyn
resident $225,000 in medical expenses, noting that his prison
experience had contributed to a dependency on drugs and alcohol
that required hospital treatment.
   With amounts awarded for lost of past and future earnings, the
total award was $1,935,000, a record in New York for damages in a
case of unlawful conviction, said civil rights lawyer Richard
Emery, who represented McLaughlin.
   McLaughlin had sought $20 million.
   McLaughlin was convicted in 1979 and sentenced to 15 years for
taking part in an armed robbery of 15 people, one of whom was
killed for resisting.
   The conviction was overturned in 1986 after his foster father,
Jarold Hohne, persuaded Emery and a police lieutenant to get the
court to reinvestigate the case. The only witness who identified
McLaughlin from photographs later acknowledged he was wrong.
   Orlando praised Hohne, saying he ``sought any available
information, left no stone unturned to prove his son's innocence.''
   McLaughlin now works in St. Paul, Minn., as a painter.
</TEXT>
