<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Oscar     10-19 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Oscar,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Curious Tale of the Quake-Predicting Fish</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORONA DEL MAR, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tale of Oscar the fish, Orange
County's earthquake prophet, took another curious turn this week:
The one-eyed denizen of the deep was sequestered due to death
threats.
   Four hours after Tuesday's San Francisco Bay area quake, Oscar
was doing the sidestroke _ the same pre-temblor behavior that
brought the 10-inch fish notoriety as a quake prognosticator.
   Oscar may have been swimming on his side moments before the Bay
area quake, but no one was around to see.
   Observers insist the South American red oscar, which usually
lives in an aquarium in Corona del Mar High School's biology lab,
has rolled over and predicted 15 to 20 Southern California quakes
in three years.
   But recent publicity surrounding his talents spawned a series of
death threats. Fearing Oscar might be ``deep-sixed,'' Principal Tom
Jacobson said the famous fish was taken to an undisclosed location
two weeks ago.
   So Oscar was alone during Tuesday's 6.9-magnitude quake, said
biology teacher Ron Schnitger. But Schnitger visited the fish hours
later, he saw another unusual occurrence.
   ``He was sleeping on his side, and I've never seen that happen,
sleeping with his good eye down,'' said Schnitger, explaining fish
usually sleep the same way they swim.
</TEXT>
