   Dolly Parton and Ricky Skaggs will join
other country stars to honor Bill Monroe for his 50 years on the
Grand Ole Opry, officials said Thursday.
   Monroe, considered the father of bluegrass music, will be
saluted Oct. 28 during special ceremonies on the regular Opry show.
   Cable TV's The Nashville Network will broadcast the salute live
during a 60-minute special.
   Performers ho will honor Monroe, 78, also include Ralph Stanley
and Mac Wiseman, network spokeswoman Nancy Neil said.
   Monroe is known for such songs as ``Blue Moon of Kentucky,''
``Mule Skinner Blues'' and ``Uncle Pen.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Football star Eric Dickerson isn't ready to
get married, but when he is, he said it won't be to an ugly woman.
   ``I'm not the best looking guy and I don't want an ugly wife
because we will have ugly kids, no doubt,'' the Indianapolis Colt
said in an interview broadcast Thursday on ESPN.
   ``My mother even said, `Please, don't have an ugly wife and make
ugly babies,''' he said.
   Dickerson, 29, has a girlfriend, but he said he isn't ready to
get married. The running back said his annual salary of nearly $1.4
million a year has something to do with it.
   ``Look at all the women that go get married to older men or rich
men and stay married for a couple months or a year and boom,
they're out and they want $10 million or $20 million because they
feel like they've had mental cruelty,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Audrey Hepburn arrived in Dhaka
on Thursday to begin a six-day, fact-finding mission on welfare
projects for Bangladesh children.
   She is scheduled to visit programs on education, slum
improvement, immunization and income generation for poor women,
said United Nations officials. Earlier this week, she visited
Thailand to publicize the plight of poor children there and met
with welfare officials.
   Miss Hepburn, 60, was appointed fund-raiser and
ambassador-at-large for the United Nations Children's Fund two
years ago. She will report to the executive board of UNICEF and the
U.N. General Assembly on her visit.
   Among Miss Hepburn's movies are ``Roman Holiday,'' ``My Fair
Lady,'' and ``Breakfast at Tiffany's.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The screenwriter of hit films such as
``Flashdance'' and ``Jagged Edge'' accused the president of a
powerful Hollywood talent agency with threatening to ruin his
career, according to a published report.
   Joe Eszterhas says that Michael Ovitz, head of Creative Artist
Agency, threatened to damage Eszterhas' reputation in the film
industry if he left the agency, the Los Angeles Times reported
Thursday. Ovitz denied the allegation.
   ``What you were threatening me with was a twisted new version of
the old-fashioned blacklist,'' Eszterhas wrote Ovitz in an Oct. 3
letter quoted in the Times. ``Plain and simple, cutting out all
smiles and friendliness, it's blackmail.''
   In response, CAA released a letter Ovitz wrote to Eszterhas to
deny the allegations.
   ``When I received your letter this morning, I was totally
shocked, since my recollection of our conversation bore no
relationship to your recollection,'' Ovitz wrote.
   The Times said the four-page Eszterhas letter had circulated
throughout the Hollywood community, which for years had speculated
that the agency put pressure on people who wanted to switch agents.
The newspaper did not specify where it got a copy of the letter.
   Ovitz would not comment further on the letters or the charges,
but CAA agent Ray Kurtzman issued a statement to the press, calling
Eszterhas ``a very talented writer'' who had every right to change
agencies and was not threatened when he did so.
   Ovitz has become a ``super agent'' in the industry, using an
extensive client list to exert influence over projects. Some
believe Ovitz does have the power to break even established
careers, the Times reported.
