<FIRST>r a AM-JunkFoodRebellion     10-19 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Junk Food Rebellion,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Protest Banning of Junk Food</HEAD>
<DATELINE>METAMORA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than half of the students at Metamora
High School students are boycotting the lunch program because the
school board decided to offer only a pro-nutrition, no ``junk
food'' menu.
   The rebellion is hitting the school financially. And the
students are getting backing from a local radio station and a major
corporation _ which is offering free Twinkies.
   Particularly rankling to students has been the administration's
recent ban on the sale of soda and candy during lunch at the
Student Council Store. That has put a significant dent in the
Student Council's fund raising, cutting projected annual revenue
from $35,000 to $6,000.
   Protesting students have been bringing bag lunches for over a
week instead of paying $1.25 for the school's hot lunch. Business
has dropped in the cafeteria from 550 students daily to about 250.
   ``Students are old enough to choose what they want to eat,''
said Student Council President Stephanie Smith, a proud brown
bagger.
   ``We just want to get the candy and sodas back,'' said Brent
Rohman, the unofficial leader of the rebellion, who also lobbied
for _ and won _ a salad bar and milk shake machine for the
cafeteria last year. ``Kids get addicted to it, almost.''
   Superintendent Ken Maurer, who claims to admire the students'
stand of passive resistance, says he has no intention of feeding
that addiction, even if it means running a deficit in the lunch
program.
   Radio station WMBD and the Continental Baking Co., based in St.
Louis, will sponsor a promotion Tuesday offering the company's
Hostess Twinkies free to anyone inclined to indulge.
   ``We obviously do not disagree with the school board's point of
view that nutrition should be stressed,'' said Continental Baking
spokesman Pat Farrell. ``But we all know kids are not going to eat
just spinach, pasta and high protein. To each life a little
enjoyment. That's what Hostess cake products are all about.''
   Maurer responds by eating granola bars, running three miles a
day, and lecturing on the benefits of exercise and a proper diet.
   ``You are what you eat,'' he said. ``Do you want to look like
Roseanne Barr or Jane Fonda? John Candy or Tom Selleck?''
</TEXT>
