<FIRST>r i AM-Mosbacher     10-19 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mosbacher,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Commerce Secretary Calls for Radical Changes in Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed For Release 4 p.m. EDT _ time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Secretary of Commerce Robert
A. Mosbacher said Thursday that Soviet bloc nations must boldly
commit themselves to free market economies if they want to solve
their dire financial problems.
   ``Our hope is to see the Soviet Union and all the countries of
Eastern Europe fully integrated into the community of nations, with
their citizens enjoying the benefits of free enterprise,''
Mosbacher said.
   Mosbacher was in Frankfurt for a conference sponsored by the
Institute for East-West Security Studies. His remarks came in a
speech prepared for delivery Thursday evening.
   The commerce secretary said that much work is necessary before
East bloc nations that strengthen their economies.
   ``There is no escaping the fact that the East's economic
problems were home-grown, and they can only be solved at home by
radical _ and genuine change,'' he said.
   Mosbacher added: ``Only the market place, only free enterprise,
can solve the desperate economic problems of the Eastern
countries.''
   The Bush administration official said the leaders of Hungary and
Poland are committed to working for a market economy, while ``each
day Soviet leaders come closer.
   ``The leaders of the other Eastern economies, though, are still
living in the past,'' he asserted.
   Communist East German leaders, including new party chief Egon
Krenz, have called for a strengthening of an orthodox socialist
structure. East Germany has an economy that is the envy of many of
its Soviet bloc neighbors.
   Mosbacher also addressed the critical question of financing
changes in Eastern Europe.
   ``Competition in production alone is not enough,'' he said.
``Independent banks are essential, allocating capital on the basis
of markets and interest rates and offering financial services that
we in the West take for granted.''
   Mosbacher, 62, also referred to his own background as a
multimillionaire oil company executive.
   ``As a businessman, I'm not accustomed to couching my views in
the language of euphemism. I prefer to speak forthrightly,'' said
Mosbacher. ``And I'll say what we all know: Marxist economics do
not work.''
   Among the topics at the East-West security conference Mosbacher
was attending is the integration of the ``reforming socialist
countries into the world economy.'' Other topics include arms
reduction and international cooperation.
   West German Foreign Minister-Hans Dietrich Genscher and Italian
Foreign Minister Gianni de Michelis were among the approximately
200 participants.
</TEXT>
