<FIRST>r w AM-ComanchePeak     10-19 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Comanche Peak,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulators Deny Request to Delay Low-Power License</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission on Thursday
turned down a citizen group's request to delay issuing a low-power
testing license for the Comanche Peak nuclear power plant in Texas.
   The request by Citizens for Fair Utility Regulation came just
days after the NRC opened an internal investigation into
allegations by an anonymous group of NRC inspectors that senior
agency officials had covered up problems at Comanche Peak.
   The anonymous inspectors, in a letter to commission Chairman
Kenneth Carr on Oct. 4, said Comanche Peak, operated by Texas
Utilities Electric Co., was far from being ready to safely begin
low-power testing.
   The commission has not said when it would issue a low-power
license, but staff members indicated Thursday it would be at least
a few weeks.
   Betty Brink, a leader of the citizens group, said that as a
result of the NRC's refusal to put Comanche Peak's low-power
license application on hold her organization would go to the 5th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans next week.
   The plant is situated near Glen Rose, Texas, about 40 miles
southwest of Fort Worth.
   The group's main argument is that Comanche Peak should not be
allowed to fire up the reactor until the courts rule on the group's
existing suit seeking to force a licensing rehearing. The hearing
process was officially closed in July 1988.
   Mrs. Brink said her group believed that the plant was not ready
to operate safely and that even low-power operation would put area
residents at undue risk.
   In denying the group's request, the commission said it was a
matter for the courts to decide because the commission previously
had ruled that the group had no legal standing to intervene in the
late stages of the licensing hearings.
   The commission added, however, that it was ordering its staff to
look into the group's charges of possible safety hazards associated
with low-power operation of the plant.
   The owner of Comanche Peak, Texas Utilities Electric Co., told
the commission Thursday it expected to be ready to request
permission to load fuel and start low-power testing early next
month, although it gave no exact target date.
   Erle Nye, chairman of the utility, said, ``I am confident that
Comanche Peak has been built safely.''
</TEXT>
