<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1909EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Falklands     10-19 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Falklands,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain, Argentina Agree to Normalize Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCISCO CONDE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentina and Britain agreed Thursday to
resume normal diplomatic and economic relations seven years after
they fought a war over the Falkland Islands.
   A joint communique read in Spanish and English by Argentine
Ambassador Lucio Garcia del Solar and British United Nations
Ambassador Crispin Tickell said both governments noted that all
hostilities had ceased.
   The announcement followed two days of meetings, the first held
between Britain and Argentina since Buenos Aires surrendered to a
British task force on June 14, 1982, after invading the windswept
South Atlantic archipelago.
   The 74 days of fighting, during which neither side formally
declared war, left 1,000 dead.
   ``Today we've taken a very large step towards normalization of
relations,'' Tickell said. ``But we're not there yet.''
   The agreement includes re-establishment of consular relations at
the consul general level in London and Buenos Aires ``to be
announced at an early date.'' Garcia del Solar said that date ``was
not too far off.''
   The agreement to resume consular ties is a precondition to the
establishment of full diplomatic relations.
   Spanish sources had described Argentina as being ``more in a
hurry'' than Britain to come to an agreement because of the Latin
American nation's pressing need to normalize economic relations
with London and desire to establish closer ties with the 12-member
European Economic Community.
   The Madrid talks were announced at the United Nations Aug. 18.
They were made possible after Argentine President Carlos Menem, who
took office in July, agreed to drop the insistence of his
predecessors that Argentina's claim to the islands, which it calls
the Malvinas, had to be the first issue considered in any
discussion of normalization.
   Tickell said there had been no discussion of the reduction of
the 2,000-man British military contingent in the 200-island
archipelago off the southern tip of Argentina, a move the
Argentines reportedly favored.
   ``I think you can assume there will be no change,'' Tickell said.
   ``It remains one of the priorities of the British government to
protect the security of the islands,'' he said, adding the
maintenance of the British military presence remains important to
that end.
   The two countries also agreed to:
   _ resume air and maritime communications following negotiations
by competent authorities;
   _ lift all remaining commercial and financial restrictions and
restrictive practices imposed since 1982;
   _ not pursue any claim against the other, including nationals of
the other, in respect of loss or damage from hostilities and
actions in and around the Falkland Islands, South Georgia and the
South Sandwich Islands;
   _ exchange views and proposals about measures to build
confidence and avoid tension;
   _ exchange views on contacts between the islands and the
continental mainland;
   _ renew normal cultural, scientific and sporting exchanges; and
   _ hold the next substantive meeting in Madrid Feb. 14-15.
   For its part, Britain said it would send a trade mission to
Buenos Aires Nov. 27 to Dec. 1, make available short-term credit
cover for British exports under irrevocable letters of credit from
Argentine banks and facilitate cooperative links between Argentina
and the 12 member nations of the European Economic Community.
   Britain also said it agreed to allow Argentine merchant ships to
enter the 150-mile zone of exclusion around the islands and to
align the limits of the zone with those of a zone designed to
protect the islands' fishing resources.
   Both countries also agreed to an umbrella clause that protects
their respective claims to sovereignty over the islands, which are
inhabited by 1,800 people, most of whom are descended from British
sailors in the 19th century.
   Argentine claims to the islands are based on the 1494 Treaty of
Tordesillas by which Spain and Portugal settled conflicts over land
claimed in the New World and on Spanish possession, to which
Argentina succeeded after declaring independence from Spain in 1816.
   British claims are based on continuous and effective occupation
since 1833.
</TEXT>
