<FIRST>r a AM-ChildKilling     10-19 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Killing,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Charged in Accidental Death of Sister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old boy has been charged with
manslaughter in the accidental shooting death of his 7-year-old
sister, who was shot while he was playing with a sawed-off shotgun
at home.
   Prosecutors said they determined that Marvin Williams was
grossly negligent in deliberately aiming the weapon at the girl
with his finger on the trigger. The gun went off and Calandra
Graham was shot in the face.
   The shooting in which the boy was charged Wednesday occurred on
Sept. 13, before the Oct. 1 effective date of a new state law that
penalizes adults who leave weapons left where they can be easily
obtained by children.
   The two children were alone at home at the time of the shooting,
and the boy told investigators conflicting stories of what
happened, said state attorney's spokesman Randy Means.
   Investigators later determined Marvin took the gun from an
unlocked cabinet in his 18-year-old brother's bedroom and played
with it for a few minutes before returning to his brother's bedroom
to put it away.
   There he saw his sister. Means said the boy pointed the gun at
the girl and told her ``something to the effect of: `Don't worry.
It's not dangerous.''' The gun then went off.
   Prosecutors believe the shooting was an accident, but Means said
the boy's conduct was so careless that it rises to the level of
culpable negligence, the standard used to prove manslaughter.
   Marvin's mother, Mattie Williams, said when told of the charge:
``I don't understand it. But we will deal with it.''
   Means said prosecutors had not decided whether to charge
Marvin's brother, Efrem Bolden, with illegal possession of the
short-barreled shotgun, an outlawed weapon.
   In a similar case in Orlando in June, a 10-year-old was shot and
killed by a 13-year-old, who was not charged. The 13-year-old was
not paying attention to where he was aiming the gun when it went
off, prosecutors said.
   That was among a series of similar cases last summer around the
state in which children playing with guns accidentally shot other
children, injuring or killing them, and led to the new law that
took effect Oct. 1 aimed at keeping loaded guns out of the hands of
children.
   Since that law took effect, Tallahassee police have filed one
charge against a man whose 8-year-old granddaughter shot herself in
the thumb with a pistol taken from an unlocked box. And a
prosecutor in Palatka has said he would go to a grand jury with a
case in which a 12-year-old was killed by a 9-year-old playmate
showing off a rifle.
</TEXT>
