<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-TeachingSafety     10-19 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Teaching Safety,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Experts Teaching Bridge Safety at Time of Quake</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California experts were teaching
Pennsylvania engineers how to make bridges earthquake-resistant
when reports of the killer San Francisco Bay area quake flashed
across the nation.
   Lindsay R. Jones, team leader and vice president of Dynamic
Isolation Systems, wasn't surprised at the news, but was concerned
about the safety of his family in Lafayette, six miles east of
Berkeley, where his office is.
   ``We don't consider this a big quake _ a 6.9 on the Richter
scale,'' he said at a Pennsylvania Department of Transportation
office where he had been discussing earthquake technology. ``The
next one could be the big one _ an 8.0 on the scale _ that would be
10 times as destructive as yesterday's quake.''
   Nonetheless, Jones couldn't make contact with his wife until a
day after the Tuesday earthquake that shook Northern California.
She was unhurt.
   Jones also learned Wednesday that a bridge on which DIS
installed special shock-absorbing equipment withstood the quake.
The Sierra Point Bridge on Route 101 is just north of San
Francisco, two miles south of Candlestick Park.
   ``One of our employees drove over the Sierra Point bridge
(Tuesday) night and it performed well. This is very significant
because the freeway bridge was retrofitted three years ago and it
proves that our technology works,'' he said.
   The bridge had been retrofitted with seismic isolation bearings
designed, cube-shaped devices made largely of layers of rubber with
a solid lead core. In bridges, the 3-foot-square isolators are
installed between the piers and the bridge deck to absorb
vibrations caused by an earthquake.
</TEXT>
