<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Attack     10-19 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Attack,0484</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Bombings Continue Terrorist Violence ^By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The homes of two prominent
leftists were bombed early Thursday, continuing violence that both
the military and leftists say is intended to frustrate a fledgling
peace process.
   Two sleeping bodyguards were slightly wounded when a bomb
exploded at the home of Ruben Zamora, a leader of the Democratic
Convergence, a leftist coalition.
   Earlier, three grenades exploded on the roof and outside the
front door of the house next door, where Aronette Diaz, vice
president of the Nationalist Democratic Union, lives with her two
sons.
   Mrs. Diaz, who is the widow of Ruben Zamora's brother, Mario,
blamed the army for the attacks.
   The armed forces press comittee, COPREFA, condemned the assaults.
   ``This kind of action serves only to escalate the violence
generated by those who do not want to live in peace,'' said an army
communique.
   Zamora, his wife and their five children were shaken up but
uninjured by the blast. The explosion destroyed the roof over the
front rooms of the house in the southern part of the city, as well
as doors, ceilings and walls in four rooms. Two cars parked in a
carport in front of the house were demolished.
   Damage to the front rooms of Mrs. Diaz's home also was extensive.
   Zamora said the attack on the homes ``is intended to impede a
political solution to the war.'' He did not accuse anyone.
   ``This is the work of people in the army who don't want dialogue
and negotiation,'' said Mrs. Diaz. ``They want to start another
spiral of violence like in 1980, wheh insurgents waging the war
against a succession of U.S.-backed governments.
   Representatives of the government and leftist rebels on
Wednesday ended three days of peace talks in Costa Rica. They
produced no substantive advances toward a cease-fire in their
10-year-old war and managed only to agree to meet again.
   But both the guerrillas' Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front, known as FMLN, and the rightist government of President
Alfredo Cristiani said the groundwork was laid for greater progress
in a meeting scheduled Nov. 20 and Nov. 21 in Venezuela.
   The government has proposed an immediate cease-fire, while the
rebels first want a series of economic, political and social
reforms along with guarantees they will be able to participate in
national affairs as a legal political party.
   A major obstacle has been differences on what constitutes a
cease-fire and on how to establish one.
</TEXT>
