<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1536EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-MilitarySpending     10-19 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military Spending,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Commander: US Forces Face `Austere' Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of the U.S. and allied forces in
Europe, Gen. John Galvin, said Thursday that budget pressures force
the nation's military chiefs to haggle over Pentagon spending in
discussions that resemble Aztec ``bloodletting ceremonies.''
   Galvin, who is the Supreme Allied Commander in Europe and the
commander-in-chief of the U.S. European Command, spoke of the
internal negotiations that go on among the nation's highest
military leaders as they grapple with budget cuts.
   For the past five years, the Pentagon has had to deal with
declining funds.
   The four-star general was asked at a meeting with reporters to
address the issue that dwindling budget resources means the
Pentagon ``can't have everything'' it wants and may be forced to
cut entire weapons systems.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, currently embroiled in budget
discussions with Capitol Hill lawmakers over the Pentagon's $295
billion budget, has attempted to cut programs such as the V-22
Osprey tilt-rotor aircraft and the F-14D jet fighter, but has met
stiff opposition.
   Galvin said it is clear, that given budget pressures, the
nation's military will be pared down.
   ``Everybody is looking at this ...it's a big thing for us. We
face an austere future,'' Galvin said. ``At the same time ... we
are responsible for deterrence and defense, and so how are we going
to do this? How are we going to draw up these priority lists?''
   The four-star general said he is taking part in Pentagon
sessions over the next two days where ``a lot of that is being
discussed.''
   ``Those are kind of bloodletting ceremonies, like the Aztecs. We
get up on top of the pyramid and try to work it out,'' Galvin said.
   Told that such ceremonies included trying to ``pull the other
guy's heart out,'' Galvin, with a smile, shot back, ``That's what
I'm talking about. This is hard work, and hard negotiating among
service chiefs.''
   The general, who elicited a hearty round of laughter from the
reporters with his remarks, hastily added that such negotiations
are ``really done in a good spirit.''
   The general said he did not want to give the impression that the
military chiefs are ``only looking out as far as the end of my
nose,'' and ``don't care what is happening the day after tomorrow.''
   He said that in order to respond to the changes that are
sweeping the Soviet Union and the Warsaw Pact, as well as the
ongoing arms control negotiations, the U.S. military chiefs are
``doing a lot of thinking'' and are trying ``to draw closer and
closer together on ... If you can't have it all, what do you give
up?''
   Galvin said that such infighting among the service chiefs
``always goes on, but as you get into more austerity, it gets
worse.''
</TEXT>
