<FIRST>r i AM-Ivory     10-19 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ivory,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ivory Ban to Cover Stockpiled Supplies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARE NULLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A worldwide ban on trade in ivory
was formally extended Thursday to cover hundreds of tons of
supplies already stockpiled, despite arguments that the move will
increase smuggling.
   Environmentalists welcomed the decision by the 103-nation
Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species, which on
Tuesday agreed to a ban on ivory trading to protect the dwindling
African elephant population.
   The convention's secretariat proposed that the sale of existing
stockpiles be exempt, but delegates Thursday rejected this and
endorsed by consensus a decision to apply it to all ivory.
   Spokesman Jean-Patrick Le Duc said the secretariat made the
proposal because of fears smugglers will move in to meet demand if
the sale of legally acquired stocks is outlawed. That view was
echoed by Hong Kong, which is believed to hold the majority of
stockpiled ivory.
   ``If existing stocks were allowed to be traded under close
monitoring, it would not enhance poaching. A ban might pose more
difficulties,'' a Hong Kong representative on the British
delegation said on condition of anonymity.
   He said the ban would have a ``drastic impact'' on the 3,000
people in Hong Kong who carve and work ivory, many of whom are
elderly craftsmen.
   Hong Kong, a British colony, has no separate voting rights and
officials said Britain abstained in the committee vote out of
respect for Hong Kong.
   On Tuesday, the conference approved by consensus a formal ban on
ivory trade with a provision that countries that prove sound
wildlife management can apply for a resumption of limited trade.
   This amounts to at least a two-year moratorium because any
exemptions are not likely to be considered before the next
conference in 1991.
   Welcoming the decision to include stockpiles in the ban,
environmentalist Tom Milliken said continued trade in stockpiles
``would have unleashed a nightmare for enforcement (of the ban).''
   Steve Cobb of the Ivory Trade Review Group agreed. ``There is
far less sympathy for the owners of stockpiles, the majority of
which are of illegal origin, than for the African nations affected
by the ban which manage their herds well,'' he said.
   The conference, which ends Friday, was attended by about 400
government delegates and 400 observers from numerous environmental
groups.
   While considering about 300 endangered animals and plants,
delegates focused on the African elephant, whose numbers are
estimated to have been cut in half to 600,000 in the past decade.
</TEXT>
