<FIRST>u w AM-SFQuake-Politics     10-19 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Politics,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Accused of Snubbing Disaster Areas' Democrats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry words flew between the White House and
San Francisco's city hall Thursday as the Bush administration came
under attack for the second time in a month for steering clear of
the Democratic mayor of a city devastated by a natural disaster.
   ``A publicity stunt,'' was how Mayor Art Agnos characterized
Vice President Dan Quayle's tour of the earthquake-stricken San
Francisco Bay area.
   ``We regret very much that the mayor of San Francisco has
decided not to cooperate with us in this matter in making sure that
there is adequate federal support for the disaster,'' White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater retorted.
   The spat between Quayle and Agnos was reminiscent of the
controversy surrounding President Bush's visit to South Carolina
after Hurricane Hugo.
   The president bypassed Charleston despite an invitation from
Democratic Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. Instead, Bush toured suburban
Summerville, a community about 20 miles inland which was not as
hard-hit as the city.
   ``Airplane rides and helicopter rides are nice, but everything
is on the ground,'' Riley said. ``The buildings are on the ground,
the people are on the ground, the stress is on the ground and we
need a president who is on the ground.''
   Bush flew to South Carolina eight days after Hugo devastated the
Charleston area, with his administration under fire from officials
including Riley and Democratic Sen. Ernest F. Hollings who said the
federal government was bungling relief efforts.
   Riley was left at the airport as Bush took his whirlwind tour.
Republican Gov. Carroll Campbell, who was Bush's Southern campaign
chairman in the last election, and Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C.,
accompanied the president.
   Asked by reporters at the time why he was left behind, Riley
replied: ``I wasn't invited.'' In an interview Thursday. Riley said
he shook hands with Bush at the airport, but ``I didn't really have
a chance to discuss anything with him. I just had a chance to tell
him the people of Charleston were really hurting.''
   The Quayle-Agnos flap erupted as Bush was preparing to fly to
California on Friday to view earthquake damage.
   When Fitzwater was asked if the president would meet with Agnos,
the spokesman at first replied:
   ``The president will meet with mayors and local officials from
the local area, absolutely.''
   ``What about that mayor?'' pressed reporters.
   ``Everyone will be invited, absolutely,'' Fitzwater said.
   A short time later, the White House announced that the mayors of
San Francisco, Oakland and Alameda would accompany the president on
his tour of the area.
   The White House insisted that Quayle's decision to pass up a
visit with Agnos was not politically motivated.
   Agnos said he was ``ticked off'' by Quayle's decision not to see
him separately.
   Quayle and Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner visited the
Bay area on Wednesday, met with dozens of local and state officials
and paved the way for Bush's visit.
   Agnos complained that Quayle ``flies around in a helicopter,
makes a bunch of television spots. ... I understand he was in the
Marina (district), and in the shelters and then left.''
   ``If he did so without visiting the mayor, I have real questions
about what he was doing here. It may have been just a publicity
stunt.''
   Quayle, in turn, called Agnos' charge ``a political shot'' and
said: ``We invited all the mayors to come and sit down with us.''
   Interviewed on ``CBS This Morning,'' Quayle said: ``I would hope
the mayor would resist any kind of political rhetoric at this time
and concentrate'' on helping victims.
   Fitzwater said Agnos was invited to two separate meetings that
Quayle and Skinner held with local officials.
   ``We offered to send a helicopter to pick him up wherever he was
and deliver him to the meetings and he declined that,'' Fitzwater
said.
   He also said chief of staff John Sununu repeatedly tried to
contact Agnos by phone ``and he has declined to talk to us.''
</TEXT>
