<FIRST>r a AM-HazelwoodMotion     10-19 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hazelwood Motion,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Captain Of Exxon Valdez Claims Immunity In Alaska Oil Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former tanker captain whose ship
spilled nearly 11 million gallons of crude oil wants a federal
court to block his prosecution, arguing that his prompt reporting
of the spill grants him immunity.
   In a motion filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court in Fairbanks,
former Exxon Valdez skipper Joseph Hazelwood's attorneys argue that
a 1976 clean water law precludes criminal prosecution over the
nation's biggest oil spill.
   Hazelwood has filed a similar motion in state Superior Court,
claiming Alaska law also grants immunity from prosecution to people
who promptly report spills they cause.
   The state has filed three felony charges and three misdemeanors
against Hazelwood. They accuse him of criminal mischief, operating
a ship while intoxicated, reckless endangerment and negligent
discharge of oil.
   Defense attorney Dick Madson said state officials are prohibited
by federal law from using Hazelwood's statements to the Coast Guard
in any criminal proceedings.
   Soon after the Exxon Valdez ran aground on Bligh Reef on March
24, Hazelwood called the Coast Guard by radio to report the
situation.
   Within a week, the state filed the misdemeanor charges, and
later added the felony criminal mischief counts. Hazelwood was
fired by Exxon.
   The charges have been consolidated for a single trial, but the
case has been postponed repeatedly. A hearing on motions is
scheduled Friday. A hearing a week from Friday will determine where
his trial is to be held.
   There was no indication when the federal courts might consider
the matter.
</TEXT>
