<FIRST>r i AM-Mideast-US 1stLd-Writethru a0659 10-19 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mideast-US, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0659,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Efforts Stalled by Israeli-US Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to ADD comment from Egyptian foreign minister,
Shamir letter to Baker. Pickup 9th pvs, `The latest...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A public argument on Middle East policy between
Israel and the United States has stalled peace efforts at least
until Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir visits Washington next month,
officials said Thursday.
   Shamir declared Tuesday the two allies were ``entering a period
of tension'' and Israel ``will not be pushed or pressured.''
   The next day, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
described his comments as ``unhelpful.''
   Frank G. Wisner, U.S. ambassador to Egypt, said Thursday the
United States and Egypt feel ``creative diplomacy'' can renew
progress toward peace in the region.
   ``No doors have been closed; no last words have been spoken,''
Wisner said in Cairo after spending more than three hours at the
Foreign Ministry. He delivered a message from Secretary of State
James A. Baker III to Esmat Abdel-Meguid, the Egyptian foreign
minister.
   Abdel-Meguid would not say what the message contained. He later
told a meeting of the U.S.-Egyptian chamber of commerce that Egypt
wants the American role in Middle East politics to continue.
   Until the remarks Tuesday to members of his right-wing Likud
bloc, Shamir had avoided confrontations with U.S. leaders despite
his disagreement with the dialogue Washington began in December
with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Yossi Ahimeir, director of Shamir's office, said the prime
minister spoke out because of what he considered growing attempts
by the Bush administration to get Israel into negotiations with the
PLO. Israel defines the PLO as a terrorist group and refuses to
deal with it.
   ``What he meant was that there is liable to be a period of
differences, but he is doing everything to prevent it,'' Ahimeir
said in an interview Thursday.
   On Thursday, Israel radio revealed another apparent effort to
diffuse tensions. The radio said Shamir wrote Baker praising his
efforts to advance peace in the Middle East but emphasizing
Israel's opposition to talks with the PLO.
   Shamir aides could not be reached for comment on the letter.
   The latest U.S. efforts, led by Baker, are aimed at starting
Israeli-Palestinian talks about Israel's plan for residents of the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip to elect delegates for
negotiations with the Israelis.
   Israel's Cabinet leadership rejected Baker's suggestions two
weeks ago, claiming they opened the door to indirect PLO
involvement, but Baker pursued the matter in private conversations
with Foreign Minister Moshe Arens.
   Ahimeir indicated Shamir felt the United States had betrayed the
essence of the Israeli plan, which excludes the PLO.
   ``We are sorry that only five months have passed'' since Shamir
introduced the peace plan ``and everyone has already lost patience
and is running to the PLO with open arms,'' he said.
   ``There are now changes in the American position and they want
to add things. We will not accept anything where the bottom line
will be to sit down with the PLO.''
   News reports in Israel said Shamir called President Bush on
Tuesday, after making his comments, to take issue with the latest
U.S. peace moves.
   Ahimeir confirmed the 10-minute conversation occurred, but would
not give detais. He said only that the tone was ``friendly'' and
Shamir expressed his views.
   The daily Haaretz, quoting a senior Bush administration official
it did not name, said the president told Shamir he was
``disappointed'' by the remarks.
   Two senior Israeli officials said privately the result of the
conversation was a decision to put a temporary hold on American
peace efforts until Shamir's trip to Washington in mid-November. A
statement from Shamir's office Thursday said he and Bush decided to
discuss peace issues further at that time.
   Israeli newspapers criticized the prime minister's comments.
Even the conservative Maariv published an editorial Thursday called
``Shamir is Looking for Confrontation.''
   It said the Americans might respond by turning to pressing
domestic matters and putting the Middle East on the back burner
because, ``after all, advancing toward peace in the region is more
important for Israel than for them.''
</TEXT>
