<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Hotel     10-19 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Hotel,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angels Anti-Drug Effort Victim of Quake</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Among the casualties of the earthquake was
an anti-drug beachhead that the Guardian Angels had established on
a seedy block in the Tenderloin district.
   The six-story Camelot Hotel was condemned because of earthquake
damage and police evacuated residents early Thursday. The Angels, a
volunteer group known for its red berets and controversial
crime-fighting tactics, left shortly after Tuesday's quake.
   ``They're going to relocate us somewhere, I suppose,'' said
resident Austin J. Mahoney, 65, who leaned on a metal cane as he
looked up at the white stucco building, sandwiched between a
peep-show video parlor and a bar.
   ``I came out of prison and it was the only place I could get,''
said Mahoney, who moved in four years ago.
   The Angels made their headquarters on the third floor, where a
``Crackdown on Crack'' sign hung in a window. Neighbors said the
Angels used citizen's band radios and called the police when they
saw trouble.
   ``They helped clean out this block,'' Mahoney said. ``Crack was
sold on this block.''
   ``It was better that they were here than not,'' said another
resident, who identified himself only as Lionel. ``People did
(drugs) in their rooms, not in the hallways like it used to be.''
   The Angels, numbering about 10 residents and staff, left for an
unknown location after the earthquake, Camelot residents and
neighbors said.
   Lionel, 42, said the hotel, which charged between $250 and $350
a month, was in bad repair, but its closure leaves him nowhere to
live.
   A desk clerk awakened the 20 to 30 remaining residents about 4
a.m. Thursday, and told them the building had been condemned. A
large crack was visible on the hotel's top floor, and tenants said
the top two floors were uninhabitable.
   Like others displaced from rundown Tenderloin hotels, the
residents were taken by bus to emergency shelters at Moscone
Center, a half-mile away.
   ``I'm tired. I need a bath. This is rough, man,'' said Claude
Greenfield, whose hotel three blocks away was cleared of more than
100 residents Tuesday night. ``I need money. I need help.''
</TEXT>
