<DOCNO> AP891019-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1615EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Hastings     10-19 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Specter Says He Will Vote to Acquit Hastings at Impeachment Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top Republican on the Senate panel that
heard evidence against federal Judge Alcee L. Hastings this summer
said Thursday that he will vote to acquit the Miami jurist of
impeachment charges.
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said in a 76-page paper that after
weighing the evidence and considering an ``unblemished lifetime
record,'' he decided ``there is insufficient evidence to convict''
Hastings of plotting to obtain a bribe.
   The paper was circulated by Specter among his fellow lawmakers
as the Senate closed its doors to the public to deliberate in the
impeachment trial.
   The Senate on Wednesday heard closing arguments from Hastings
and his attorneys as well as House members who brought the 17
impeachment charges.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, said that if
the lawmakers finished their closed-door deliberations on Thursday
they would vote on Friday on whether to remove Hastings from the
U.S. District Court bench.
   Hastings would immediately be removed and his $89,500 salary
would be stopped if he were convicted of any one of the 17
impeachement charges approved in August 1988 by the House.
   Hastings, the first black federal judge in Florida history, is
accused of conspiracy to obtain a $150,000 payoff, lying about it
to a jury that acquitted him of the charge in 1983 and improper
disclosure of information obtained through a court-authorized
wiretap.
   In his statement to the Senate on Wednesday, the affable,
53-year-old Hastings reaffirmed his denial that he took part in a
bribery conspiracy.
   Specter, vice chairman of a Senate panel that heard 18 days of
evidence this summer, noted that prosecutors at the 1983 trial told
jurors that Hastings was lying. ``Obviously the jury did not accept
those arguments.''
   He said the case that Hastings had improperly disclosed
information obtained from a wiretap ``was neither convincing nor
substantial.''
   Conviction would make Hastings the sixth official in history
removed by impeachment. The most recent was Judge Harry Claiborne
of Nevada in 1986 who fought in vain to remain on the bench while
serving a tax fraud sentence.
   District Judge Walter Nixon of Mississippi, convicted of lying
to a grand jury, is also fighting to remain on the federal bench.
   Hastings was accused of plotting with Washington attorney
William Borders in 1981 to obtain the payoff from two defendants in
his court. He had sentenced them to prison terms for their role in
a pension fraud scheme.
   An FBI undercover agent posing as one of the defendants
contacted Borders and offered him $150,000 in exchange for a
reduction of the sentences to probation. The attorney was arrested
Oct. 9, 1981, as he left a suburban Virginia motel with the agent
and a garment bag containing $125,000 in cash.
   Hastings, in Washington for a testimonial dinner in honor of
Borders that night, was told that the FBI wanted to contact him but
immediately returned to Miami by an indirect route without checking
out of his hotel.
</TEXT>
