<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 2033EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Drugs-Information     10-19 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Information,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maker Giving Patients Easy-to-Understand Information</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major drug manufacturer on Thursday
announced a new program to provide easily understood information to
patients about its most widely used prescription drugs.
   G.D. Searle and Co. said it was initiating the program in light
of a new survey showing that nearly half the drugs prescribed
yearly are taken incorrectly.
   The Bush administration, along with Sen. Orrin Hatch, ranking
Republican on the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee,
endorsed the program as a voluntary, private sector effort
important to public health.
   Hatch called it ``a step forward that should be followed by
other pharmaceutical manufacturers in this country,'' but he said
he would not want the government to require companies to initiate
their own programs. ``I don't like to make matters mandatory if we
can do it on a voluntary basis,'' he said.
   The Food and Drug Administration requires drug companies to
provide to patients information on certain drugs, including birth
control pills. It also has encouraged companies to distribute
information voluntarily for some drugs that have more serious side
effects.
   An FDA program to require package inserts for 10 prescription
drugs was initiated during the late 1970s. But the program ran into
resistance from pharmacists, physicians and the prescription drug
industry and was scrapped in 1981, before it got off the ground.
   Consumer groups have long favored efforts to distribute more
information to patients about prescription drugs, and some
countries are moving in that direction. The European Economic
Community will require drug companies to distribute such
information beginning in January 1992.
   Sheldon G. Gilgore, Searle chairman, said the plan, which will
be instituted worldwide by the end of 1990, is the most
comprehensive voluntary patient-information program by a U.S. drug
company.
   He said the company initially will provide to physicians
information sheets they can give to patients explaining in
nontechnical terms the potential side effects of three drugs and
the possible interactions the medicines can have with other drugs.
   The three drugs are Calan and Calan SR, used to treat high blood
pressure, and Cytotec, an ulcer preventive. These account for about
three-quarters of Searle's nearly $1 billion in annual domestic
sales.
   Company officials said the rest of Searle's products, as well as
future products, will be covered by the program. About 15 percent
of the company's drug products are oral contraceptives, for which
the FDA already requires written information for patients.
   Searle said a telephone survey of 1,000 prescription drug users,
conducted during the last week of September by Pracon Inc. of
Reston, Va., said nearly half do not follow the dosage instructions
of their medicine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
