<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1625EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SuperfundWaste     10-19 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Superfund Waste,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forty Cents of Every Dollar to Cleanup, OTA Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's Superfund money has not been
spent wisely, with only some 40 percent going to clean up toxic
waste dumps, a congressional study said Thursday.
   ``Analysis breeds paralysis,'' the Office of Technology
Assessment said in noting that only about three dozen of the 1,200
priority cleanup sites have been declared completely clean.
   During the last three years, 60 percent of the $4.4 billion
spent by the Environmental Protection Agency on Superfund went for
administration, management or site studies rather than cleanup,
said a report from the Office of Technology Assessment.
   OTA concluded that while the EPA has estimated another 900 toxic
waste sites likely will be added to its priority list over the next
decade, the number could be 10 times that with a better
administered program.
   The report, entitled ``Coming Clean,'' said while private
Superfund contractors keep busy, ``reports pile up, contamination
spreads into soil and groundwater, many sites wait to get into the
(cleanup) system.''
   Lew Crampton, EPA associate administrator for communications and
public affairs, said the agency's figures show 60 to 70 percent of
the money is related to site cleanup. The percentage will increase
starting later this year, he said, when major construction work
begins on a number of sites.
   ``It depends on how you define what is spending directly on
cleanup and what is inefficient,'' he said, adding the agency has
asked OTA to explain its percentages.
   Crampton, defending preparatory studies, added, ``You can't
expect to stick a shovel in the ground and get rid of this stuff
(toxic waste).''
   Studies are needed to characterize the hazard, decide on the
proper remedy and test different technologies, all work that must
be handled by contractors, he said.
   Reps. John D. Dingell, D-Mich. and James Scheuer, D-N.Y. both
noted EPA Administrator William K. Reilly has taken steps to
improve Superfund.
   Dingell added ``the constructive aspects of the OTA report may
be overshadowed by its excessive emphasis on speculative
statistics.''
   Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., said the study ``paints a disturbing
picture which questions just how permanent and complete these
cleanups actually are and how wisely the money used to administer
the program has been spent.''
   The report said the Superfund's problem is not one of money, but
that funds too often were misdirected rather than aimed at reducing
the significant health and environmental threats posed by toxic
waste sites.
   Often, money spent directly on cleanup efforts went toward
``reducing hypothetical risks which may not materialize'' instead
of to dealing with immediate health threats, it said.
   At the same time, the report claimed that too often the
government has chosen _ or allowed the polluters themselves to
choose _ cleanup methods that ``are unlikely to work over the long
term.''
   In an attempt to reduce government costs, the EPA is getting
industry to assume more cleanup activities, but also is allowing
industry to use less stringent cleanup technologies, possibly
saving as much as $1 billion, the study said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
