<FIRST>r i AM-Cyprus-Bullet     10-19 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cyprus-Bullet,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Girl Fails to Notice Bullet Lodged in Her Hair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHERYNIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old girl was working so hard
on her school examination paper Thursday that she wasn't aware a
bullet had lodged in her hair.
   It was only after a classmate told Demetra Achilleos, ``Look,
you are dropping bullets from your hair,'' that she made the
unusual discovery.
   The incident occurred in this Greek Cypriot village in east
Cyprus, less than a mile from the fortified buffer zone dividing
the Mediterranean island.
   Demetra and other girls in her class were busy on a written test
when they heard a fusillade of shots from the zone. A window in the
classroom shattered and small pieces of plaster fell on their heads
from the ceiling.
   ``I felt something like a slight burning pain on top of my head
but I did not give it much thought at the time,'' Demetra said
later.
   ``I thought it was a piece of glass from the broken window. When
I realized what had happened and how close I had come to being
seriously hurt I became frightened and cried.''
   The bullet apparently hit her head after ricocheting off the
ceiling, with much of its force spent.
   Police asked U.N. peacekeepers who patrol the zone to
investigate.
   Dherynia villagers said shots are occasionally fired from the
Turkish lines toward the village, though nobody has been hurt.
   Cyprus has been divided since a 1974 Turkish invasion.
</TEXT>
