<HEAD>Sportscar Giveaway Sparks Donation Bonanza</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake Bjt and AM-SF Quake-Relief Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talk about a gift that keeps on giving.
   Mark Smith, a 32-year-old Montrose man, won a $15,000 Mazda
Miata sportscar in a name-that-tune radio contest Wednesday and
promptly turned the prize over to the Red Cross fund to help
victims of the Northern California earthquake.
   Morning disc jockey Rick Dees and KIIS-FM management were
thunderstruck, so they decided to match Smith's $15,000 gift and
gave him another car.
   ``I still don't know what I'm going to do. I may yet give this
one up, too. It's been a crazy day,'' said Smith, a local YMCA
program director. Smith said he was concerned about victims of the
quake and, ``Hearing (Dees) talk about the Red Cross needing money
made me think of it.''
   ``It was a real catalyst,'' said Craig Rogers, an assistant to
Dees. ``Since Smith did that, we've been getting calls from
businesses wanting to donate money ... everyone is moved by this
guy's generosity.''
   A later contestant for the Miata also planned to give the cash
equivalent to the Red Cross if she won, and when she lost she gave
the $100 consolation prize instead.
