<FIRST>u w AM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru   10-19 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speedier Evacuation of Dependents Under Consideration</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `The United ..., to CORRECT date of elections;
picks up 4th graf pvs, `U.S. officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration may speed up the
planned withdrawal of U.S. military dependents from Panama, the
White House said Thursday.
   Gen. Maxwell R. Thurman, the newly appointed U.S. military
commander in Panama, also has recommended shortening soldiers' tour
of duty so that fewer bring their families to Panama, a Pentagon
official said.
   The United States imposed sanctions against Panama in March 1988
in a campaign to oust strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
Noriega has held onto power, nullifying last May's elections and
installing a crony on Sept. 1 as president.
   U.S. officials last May began evacuating military dependents,
and as of July 1, some 6,300 Department of Defense personnel had
either been sent home or relocated onto U.S. bases in Panama, White
House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   But there are still roughly 11,000 American dependents in the
country, said Fitzwater, who added, ``We are reviewing the issue
right now of whether or not that (withdrawal) should be
accelerated.''
   Currently, the United States has 10,000 soldiers permanently
assigned to Panama, 2,500 military personnel there on temporary
duty, 7,700 military dependents, 2,700 U.S. civilian Pentagon
employees and 3,300 civilian dependents.
   The ``ultimate purpose'' is to get family members back to the
United States, Fitzwater said.
   At the Pentagon, spokesman Pete Williams said Thurman had
formally recommended to the Joint Chiefs of Staff that tours of
duty in Panama be reduced so that fewer soldiers bring families
with them to the troubled region.
   Thurman wants to cut from 15 months to 12 months the tour length
for those going alone to Panama.
   The standard tour for military personnel bringing family members
to Panama would be cut from 30 months to 24 months, and ``only a
very few'' would be allowed to remain there on a full 24-month
rotation, Williams said.
   Williams said Thurman's recommendations were designed ``to
ensure the security of all U.S. military members and their families
in Panama.''
   Thurman wanted to emphasize that while the U.S. forces have no
quarrel with the Panama Defense Forces, the American military
personnel serving in Panama must remember ``the situation is a
sustained, classic, low-itensity conflict,'' said Williams. ``Their
mission is counter-terrorism, their mission is protection of U.S.
military personnel and U.S. military assets.''
   Noriega is under indictment in the United States for drug
trafficking. On Oct. 3 he quashed an attempted coup that received
minimal support from U.S. forces.
   The withdrawal of dependents began last spring following a
series of incidents, including harassment and physical assaults
against some Americans.
</TEXT>
