<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cuba     10-19 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cuba,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Urges Cuba To Respect UN Resolutions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Thursday that Cuba,
as a newly elected member of the U.N. Security Council, should
start showing respect for U.N. resolutions by ending assistance to
leftist rebels in El Salvador.
   Cuba was one of five countries to be elected to Security Council
seats Wednesday. It is the first time Cuba has been chosen for a
seat since the 1959 revolution.
   ``We hope Cuba will recognize that it has a special
responsibility as a member of Security Council to act
constructively to end regional conflicts, not contribute to them,''
State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said.
   She said Cuba should bear in mind that the Central American
presidents have asked the United Nations to create a force to
ensure that no state provides support to irregular forces, which
include the Salvadoran rebel group known by its Spanish initials
FMLN.
   She noted that a U.N. resolution approved several weeks ago
called on all member states to halt all overt or covert aid to
insurrectional forces in Central America.
   ``Cuba is the principal violator of that Security Council
resolution and the principal arms supplier to the FMLN,'' she said.
``We hope its tenure on the Security Council will begin with Cuban
adherence to the resolution.''
   Cuba had the endorsement of other Latin American nations for the
Security Council seat. The action of the Latin American countries
suggested that the Bush administration's policy of hostility toward
Cuba is not widely shared elsewhere in the hemisphere.
   On a related subject, Ms. Tutwiler deplored the bombing in El
Salvador of the home of leftist political leader Ruben Zamora.
   On Wednesday, Ms. Tutwiler condemned the killing of the young
daughter of a military officer in El Salvador and Thursday, she
said, ``we condemn with equal vigor this reprehensible act against
Mr. Zamora and his family.''
   The spokeswoman said she not know who was responsible for the
attack.
   Ms. Tutwiler also responded to a report contending that the
Salvadoran military has conducted a nationwide campaign of
killings, harassment and torture against doctors and health care
workers and attacked rebel field hospitals in violation of the
Geneva Convention.
   Based on the report, written by seven Americans, including five
doctors, the U.S. government has requested specific information on
cases in which there were claims of harassment, she said.
   ``There is no evidence of a Salvadoran governmment policy of
harassment or abuse of health workers,'' she said. ``There is no
doubt that the provision of health care and services by the
government could be improved.''
   The team concluded that the alleged persecution of medical
personnel was part of a campaign to obstruct religious and relief
workers in order to undermine support for the guerrillas.
</TEXT>
