<FIRST>r w AM-Grain-Soviets     10-19 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-Soviets,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buy Additional 1.2 Million Tons of Corn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private exporting companies have sold the
Soviet Union an additional 1.2 million metric tons of U.S. corn for
delivery in 1989-90 under a long-term supply agreement, the
Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   Orders since Oct. 1, the beginning of the agreement's new year,
now total more than 5 million tons of corn, 143,700 tons of
soybeans and 325,000 tons of soybean meal.
   U.S. grain sales to Moscow in 1988-89 were a record of more than
21.7 million tons, including more than 16.3 million tons of corn
and nearly 5.4 million tons of wheat.
   In addition, 1988-89 sales included 1.35 million tons of soybean
meal and 1.02 million tons of grain sorghums.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 1.2 million tons
of corn would be more than 47 million bushels.
   The new sales were made by unidentified private exporting
companies, which are required to report large sales to the
department. No selling prices or further details were released.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.27 per bushel at the
farm level, according to USDA's five-day average, meaning that the
latest sale could have a farm value of about $107 million.
</TEXT>
