<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru   10-19 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0661,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockets Hit Capital, Largest Soviet Airlift Reported Since Pullout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with reports of massive Soviet
airlift, conflicting reports on casualties. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `Areas
of...' EDITS thereafter to trim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockets slammed into the capital's
airport and civilian flights were halted Thursday as the Soviet
Union was reported to be undertaking the largest airlift since its
military withdrawal eight months ago.
   The government said shelling in Kabul killed 12 people and
wounded 35, though two doctors at a hospital that monitors
casualties said they did not know of any victims.
   The U.S.-backed guerrillas also shelled a strategic town near
the Pakistan border, killing nine people, the government said.
   Diplomatic sources in Kabul and Islamabad, Pakistan, said it was
the largest Soviet airlift since February, when Soviet troops ended
their nine-year intervention in Afghanistan.
   Diplomats in Kabul said Soviet-built Antonov-12 transport planes
were flying continuously into the airport, dropping off weapons and
food for soldiers. They said the planes were also flying night
missions.
   Two soldiers said all commercial traffic was shut down for most
of the afternoon but Soviet transport planes were operating despite
the shelling. Witnesses said at least five rockets hit the airport
grounds, but there were no immediate casualty or damage reports
there.
   U.S. Rep. Don Ritter, R-Pa., estimated Moscow has increased its
aid to $400 millinagers to take early
retirement.
   AT&amp;T outperformed its Bell offspring, which reported diverging
results. Profits rose 6.5 percent at Philadelphia-based Bell
Atlantic Corp., but fell 8.9 percent at Denver-based U S West Inc.,
fell 12.6 percent at San Francisco-based Pacific Telesis Group, and
fell 14.8 percent at strikebound Nynex Corp., based in White
Plains, N.Y.
   While AT&amp;T said it is not aiming to eliminate a specified number
of jobs, spokesman Burke Stinson said, ``It would not be
unreasonable for 5,000 to 15,000 managers to take advantage of the
plan.''
   Analysts praised AT&amp;T's cost-cutting step, saying the company
has too many managers in light of its sluggish sales of computers
and network equipment.
   ``They're doing exactly what I think they need to do,'' said Lap
Lee, a Salomon Brothers Inc. analyst.
   AT&amp;T will double to 34,000 the number of managers eligible to
retire with immediate pension payments. It is also offering a
special sweetened pension plan for managers who choose to retire on
Dec. 30.
   AT&amp;T embarked on an aggressive cost-cutting program beginning in
1984, the year it lost its local operating companies in the breakup
of the Bell System.
   Since then the company has cut its payroll from 373,000 to
298,000. This is the first program aimed only at managers.
   The largest single job cut in the company's history came in late
1986, when AT&amp;T eliminated 32,000 jobs. The company has relied on
incentives when slashing employment, but Stinson noted that this is
the first ``pension sweetener'' in AT&amp;T history.
   ``We are in a topsy-turvy marketplace, and we need to have as
many people at the elbows of our customers as possible and as few
people in non-sales, behind-the-scenes jobs as possible,'' Stinson
said.
   The retirement option will increase expenses in the fourth
quarter, but the amount cannot be determined until the number of
participants is determined. The company said the higher expenses
would be offset by other items, including a gain from a share
exchange that ends its direct investment in Ing. C. Olivetti &amp; Co.
SpA.
   AT&amp;T reported profits rose 19 percent to $699 million, or 65
cents a share in the quarter ended Sept. 30, from $587 million, or
55 cents a share a year ago. Revenue increased 1 percent to $8.9
billion from $8.81 billion in the third quarter a year ago.
   For the nine-month period, profit totaled $1.99 billion, or
$1.85 a share, up 19 percent from $1.67 billion, or $1.56 a share,
a year ago. Revenue increased 3 percent to $26.81 billion, from
$26.00 billion in the year-ago period.
   AT&amp;T Chairman Robert E. Allen said that while the company is
pleased with the results, ``we are keenly aware that we face stiff
competition in all our markets.''
   He said AT&amp;T will ``continue to be aggressive in the marketing
of our products and services, and aggressive as well in continuing
to drive costs out of every part of our business.''
   Bell Atlantic and U S West, two of the companies carved out of
AT&amp;T in the 1984 breakup, reported differing results. Bell Atlantic
attributed its gains partly to strong growth in telephone usage,
while U S West said its profit dip was the result of special
factors that masked ``modest earnings growth.''
   Bell Atlantic said its profit rose to $363.2 million, or $1.82 a
share, from $341 million, or $1.72 a share, a year earlier. Revenue
rose to $2.91 billion from $2.76 billion.
   For the first nine months, Bell Atlantic said profit rose to
$1.07 billion, or $5.43 a share, from $1.01 billion, or $5.12 a
share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $8.56 billion from $8.11
billion.
   U S West said profit fell to $258.1 million, or $1.39 a share,
from $283.2 million, or $1.55 a share, a year earlier. Revenue fell
to $2.32 billion from $2.43 billion.
   ``Nevertheless, we're not satisfied with these results. The
major negative factor is the cumulative impact of regulatory
activity over the past two years on our telephone operations,''
said Jack McAllister, U S West's chairman and chief executive.
   For the year to date, U S West said earnings fell to $766.3
million, or $4.17 a share, from $860 million, or $4.68 a share, a
year earlier. Revenue rose to $7.15 billion from $6.87 billion a
year earlier.
   Nynex blamed a continuing strike by about 60,000 employees as a
factor in its downturn in its installation of phone lines and
delays in repairs and directory assistance. It said its
third-quarter earnings fell to $288.7 million, or $1.47 a share,
from $338.9 million, or $1.72 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose
to $3.31 billion from $3.18 billion a year earlier.
   For the first nine months, Nynex earnings fell to $851.3
million, or $4.32 a share, from $972 million, or $4.90 a share, a
year earlier. Revenue rose to $9.84 billion from $9.42 billion.
   Pacific Telesis Group said earnings fell to $278 million, or 68
cents a share, from $318 million, or 75 cents a share, in the third
quarter of 1988, which had been the best third quarter in the
company's history. Revenue edged down to $2.37 billion from $2.38
billion.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Pacific Telesis
said earnings fell to $920 million, or $2.23 a share, from $939
million, or $2.22 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $7.12
billion from $7.06 billion.
</TEXT>
