<FIRST>r a AM-People-Reagan     10-19 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Reagan,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former President Heads for Japan, Takes Military Kin for Ride</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Reagan and his wife, Nancy,
left Thursday morning for an 11-day trip to Japan with more than
240 military relatives they invited to hitch a free ride to the
Orient.
   The Reagans and the spouses and dependents of U.S. military
personnel stationed in Japan left Los Angeles International Airport
aboard a chartered TWA Boeing 747 bound for Tokyo.
   The Reagans went to Japan at the invitation of the Japanese
government and the Fujisankei Communications Group. They will
attend several charitable events and meet with the prime minister,
emperor and other government figures.
   At the Reagans' suggestion, Fujisankei provided the jumbo jet,
said Reagan spokesman Mark Weinberg.
   ``Nancy and I promised ourselves that if we ever had a chance to
bring families together, we would,'' Reagan said in a statement.
``When we learned we would have so many extra seats on the airplane
being provided to us, we knew immediately what to do.''
   The Reagans, who are expected to receive $1 million for their
charitable and public appearances in Japan, were to return Oct. 28.
</TEXT>
