<FIRST>r w AM-Bacon-Nitrate     10-19 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bacon-Nitrate,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Ordering Cutback In Use Of Nitrate In Bacon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department said Thursday it
will prohibit use of sodium nitrate in the processing of dry-cured
bacon, which makes up about 2 percent of the total bacon made in
the United States.
   Officials said also that the amount of sodium nitrite used in
the dry curing of bacon will be reduced. The regulation for both
will be effective Jan. 18, 1990.
   Lester M. Crawford, administrator of the department's Food
Safety and Inspection Service, said the move ``will help avoid any
health risk from nitrosamine formation when these types of bacon
are fried.''
   Nitrites can combine with amines in meat to form nitrosamines,
and certain types of those have been shown to cause cancer in
laboratory animals.
   About 98 percent of the bacon in the United States is made by
``pumping'' curing solutions containing nitrite into pork bellies.
The agency has prohibited nitrates and limited nitrites in the
pumping solutions since 1978.
   Nitrites are used in the curing of meat to guard against
spoilage and harmful organisms, and to give bacon a distinctive
color and taste.
</TEXT>
