<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Relief 1stLd-Writethru a0714 10-19 0950</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Relief, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0714,0972</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relief Aid Pours Into Northern California For Quake Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with Soviet Armenians organizing aid;
INSERTS 3 grafs after 11th graf, `The Japanese ...' with further detail
on Armenian aid, earthquake; SUBS 19th graf, `Closer to ...' with Anheuser-Busch
donating $2 million; ADDS 1 graf with man's donation prompting others.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY RYCKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans touched by scenes of devastation, of people left
homeless by disaster, sent what they could to earthquake victims in
Northern California on Thursday just one month after shipping aid
to those in Hurricane Hugo's wake.
   Even Charleston, S.C., still reeling from last month's pounding
by Hugo, sent a plane load of bottled drinking water. And on the
other side of the globe, tens of thousands of Armenians organized
aid for California victims.
   Private groups and officials sent search dogs and special
equipment to hunt for survivors, donated blood and money and
offered their expertise. A Southern California man donated a
$15,000 sports car he won in a radio contest.
   Wyoming remembered the help it received from California
firefighters in the 1988 fires at Yellowstone National Park. Gov.
Mike Sullivan asked emergency officials to help with structural
inspections and search and rescue.
   ``While we are few in number and they are many, their needs are
many, and we stand ready to help in any way,'' Sullivan said.
   The Wyoming Red Cross sent a mass feeding van to California from
Casper to join other Red Cross units delivering hot food door to
door. The Red Cross also took cash donations for the relief effort.
   Missouri Red Cross officials said about a dozen staff members
and volunteers were still on the East Coast helping victims of
Hugo, but one person is preparing to head to San Francisco.
   ``It's been the double whammy,'' spokeswoman Colleen McQuillan
said. ``We're still trying to raise money to pay for Hugo and now
we need money for this.''
   The international headquarters of the Church of the Nazarene,
located in Kansas City, told its churches to pass the plate for
earthquake victims at Wednesday night services.
   ``We're getting calls from all over, `What are we going to do to
help?' We tell them to get money,'' said Steve Weber, coordinator
for the church's charity services.
   The Japanese Red Cross Society sent $35,000 to its American
counterpart for earthquake victims. In New York City, a group of
Manhattan co-workers donated the $50 in a World Series betting pool
to the Red Cross.
   In Yerevan, Soviet Armenia, tens of thousands of Armenians met
in the central square Thursday night to gather aid for California
quake victims, an activist said in a telephone interview.
   ``People came from all over, from factories, institutes, work
collectives,'' said Galstyan Ambartsumyan. ``We are collecting
money, clothing _we just have to find out what is needed.''
   Soviet authorities say 25,000 people died in an earthquake in
Armenia last year, many of them when shoddily built multi-story
apartment buildings collapsed. Aid flowed into the area from all
over the world.
   The Kansas City regional office of the Federal Emergency
Management Agency, one of 10 nationwide, was unable to send help to
California.
   ``I have all of my capability committed to Hugo,'' said Warren
Pugh, the agency's division director of disaster assistance. ``I
don't really have anybody left to send out.''
   New York Air National Guard crews who joined hurricane relief
efforts in the Carribean and South Carolina flew to Northern
California. The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey also
offered engineers to help assess the damage to buildings and
bridges.
   ``As you determine your priority needs, New York stands ready to
assist in any way we can,'' New York Gov. Mario Cuomo said.
   People in Charleston, S.C., had a special understanding of
natural disaster. They're still digging out from Hugo, which
smashed ashore on Sept. 21 with 135 mph wind. Relief poured in from
across the nation.
   The city sent bottled water and gasoline generators to
earthquake victims in the San Francisco Bay area, as well as five
police officers to help with emergency operations.
   ``I know we still have and will have great needs here and
charity certainly begins at home. However, it would be wrong for
this community ... not to reach in and contribute to those who are
hurt and suffering right now,'' Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. said.
   Closer to home, an Anheuser-Busch Inc. brewery 35 miles
northeast of San Francisco filled cans with drinking water instead
of beer for free shipment to relief agencies, the company said. The
Anheuser-Busch Foundation in St. Louis said it will donate $2
million along with food, clothing and water.
   And a cellular telephone company in Burlingame, Calif., offered
to lend free telephones to emergency service agencies.
   In San Francisco, lawyer Melvin Belli and his staff set up
tables in front of his downtown offices Wednesday, offering free
legal counsel. The attorneys' office building was apparently unsafe.
   The most unusual donation was probably from Mark Smith, who won
a Mazda Miata sportcar in a name-that-tune radio contest in Los
Angeles. Smith gave the car to the Red Cross earthquake fund.
   Morning disc jockey Rick Dees and KIIS-FM management decided to
match Smith's $15,000 gift and awarded him another car _ demanding
that he keep it.
   ``I still don't know what I'm going to do,'' said Smith, a YMCA
program director. ``I may yet give this one up, too. It's been a
crazy day.''
   Since Smith's gift, people and businesses began calling the
station wanting to donate money. A woman who lost the contest
donated her $100 consolation prize, said Craig Rogers, an assistant
to Dees.
</TEXT>
