<FIRST>r w AM-NAACP-Hooks     10-19 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NAACP-Hooks,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hooks: Blacks Will Form New Group to Fight Social Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NAACP Executive Director Benjamin Hooks said
Thursday that a new group will soon be formed to better coordinate
black organizations' efforts to pull other blacks out of the
underclass.
   He said the group, which has no name yet, will be a
clearinghouse for ideas that the many black oriented and controlled
organizations can use to fight poverty, teen-age pregnancy, drugs,
AIDS, crime and other problems that are dragging down a large
segment of the population.
   ``I happen to believe the might of the black community is large
enough'' to do something about these problems, the leader of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People said at
a press conference.
   ``Not counting the churches, there are 2 million black people in
organized groups,'' he said.
   He said he envisions a ``war on poverty using sweat and tears''
of volunteers. However, he said, ``We don't intend to let the
federal government off the hook.''
   At a three-day meeting starting Oct. 29, billed a ``conference
on the present crisis,'' the NAACP will form the new group and make
plans to lobby Congress for legislative relief from recent Supreme
Court decisions viewed as setbacks to civil rights.
   The gathering is a follow-up to the Aug. 26 march on Washington
that protested those decisions, Hooks said.
   He said legislation is being drafted by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., that the NAACP hopes ``can pass muster with the very
conservative court.''
</TEXT>
