<HEAD>House Approves $837 Million in Aid for Hungary, Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs, inserts new graf after 16th graf pvs, In addition,
with maritime subsidy fight; adds 3 grafs on threat to reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Thursday gave overwhelming
approval to an $837 million aid package for Poland and Hungary that
nearly doubles what President Bush has requested.
   The vote of 345-47 sent the measure to the Senate.
   ``The ice of the Cold War is rapidly melting,'' said Rep. David
Bonior, D-Mich., during debate. ``We have a unique opportunity to
seize a very special moment in history. With our help, the march of
freedom in Eastern Europe will become irreversible.''
   The package was brought to the House floor with unusual speed,
just 15 days after it was introduced. The urgency was an indication
of Congress' eagerness to swiftly reward Poland and Hungary for
their moves toward democracy and free-market economic reform, as
well as Democrats' desire to underscore what they call Bush's
``timid'' response to the sweeping changes in the East Bloc.
   ``The administration has failed to grasp that this is a critical
turning point in the history of East-West relations,'' said Bonior,
a senior member of the chamber's Democratic leadership.
   The package has a three-year price tag of $837.3 million,
compared to the $450 million Bush has sought. During a trip to
Eastern Europe in July, the president originally proposed about
$150 million in aid, and has ratcheted the amount upward since then
in the face of congressional criticism.
   House Republicans flocked to the bill. One, Rep. Jim Leach of
Iowa, said the bill was ``an extraordinarily cheap way of helping
redirect the course of history.''
   The situation clearly has made administration officials
uncomfortable. In a policy statement, the White House said it would
generally support the bill but ``has reservations about the
excessive funding levels'' and would work to decrease the amount
when the bill goes to the Senate.
   Included in the package were:
   _A $200 million grant to help stabilize Poland's economy. That
would be the U.S. contribution to a $1 billion multilateral fund
sought by Poland.
   _$160 million for Poland and $40 million for Hungary to promote
private enterprise.
   _$10 million to set up a technical training program in business
skills for Poles and Hungarians, plus $4 million for Poland and $1
million for Hungary for programs in job training, labor-management
relations and occupational health and safety.
   _Up to $125 million in food aid for Poland.
   _$200 million in short-term guarantees and insurance for U.S.
exporters selling products to the two countries.
   _$30 million for clean coal-burning technology for Poland, and
$10 million for other environmental protection programs for both
countries.
   In addition, the bill provided $12 million for building
democratic institutions in Poland and Hungary, possibly through the
National Endowment for Democracy, and money for the Peace Corps,
cultural exchanges, scientific projects and medical aid.
   In an ironic twist, the bill uses some of the money aimed at
helping the Solidarity government, an estimated $37.5 million, to
subsidize U.S. maritime unions, because it requires that 75 percent
of food aid be shipped on more expensive U.S. vessels. An effort to
trim that subsidy, mostly pressed by farm-state lawmakers, failed
228 to 170.
   Last June, in the first open elections in four decades,
candidates of the trade union Solidrity won enough seats to take
control of Poland's government. A week ago, the new government
outlined plans for sweeping economic reforms.
   Hungary this year became the first Warsaw Pact nation to
physically dismantle the Iron Curtain and opened its borders to
allow East Germans to flee to the West. It is developing a new
multi-party political system under a liberalized constitution and
plans parliamentary elections early next year.
   But serious problems in both countries pose a threat to the
reforms.
   With inflation running at an annual rate of 200 percent and
climbing, food shortages, and a $39 billion foreign debt burden,
leaders of the fledgling Polish government face particularly
crucial tests.
   The aid package will help relieve economic pressures and buy
time for the new leaders to institutionalize their reforms,
proponents said, and keep alive the prospects for change in the
rest of Eastern Europe.
   Citizens in Germany, Romania and Czechoslovakia are watching
what is happening in Poland and Hungary, said Rep. Stephen Solarz,
D-N.Y. ``If these experiments fail, it will stifle the prospects
for political and economic reform in the other countries,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
