<DOCNO> AP891019-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1743EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Scene     10-19 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Scene,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grief, Destruction Jumbled With Laid-Back California Lifestyle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Lai buried his face in his hands,
sobbing as he sat grief-stricken Thursday on a curb outside the
rubble of a four-story apartment building where two of his friends
died in the earthquake.
   ``I came here and it was gone. It happened so fast,'' said Lai,
26, who learned of the deaths when he came to check on their
building. For him, like other Californians, the earthquake not only
jumbled a landscape but heaved up grief and misery that clashed
with a laid-back lifestyle.
   Damage was heaviest in the Marina district, a trendy, upscale
neighborhood of pastel buildings, stucco facades and terra-cotta
roofs with a view of the spires of the Golden Gate Bridge and the
mountains across San Pablo Bay, drenched on Thursday with the
golden California sunshine.
   One section of the Bay Bridge linking Oakland and San Francisco
caved in, giving it the look of an alligator with its jaw stuck.
   San Franciscans whose lives revolve around their cars endured
clogged or closed freeways and city traffic snarled by non-working
traffic lights.
   Other changes were less subtle.
   Joggers whizzed past carcasses of collapsed buildings without
breaking stride. Tanned people in athletic wear toted tennis
rackets and bought fruit juice chilled in ice buckets.
Skateboarders and bicyclists competed with cars on streets. But the
air carried the scent of leaking natural gas and sounds of sirens,
generators, heavy equipment, helicopters and crackling police
radios.
   Evacuees carrying coolers, suitcases and boxes of belongings
competed for sidewalk space with tourists hefting video cameras and
snapping pictures.
   ``It's bad enough we're going through what we are without the
picture-taking. The tourists think this is a carnival,'' said Marie
Plaja, 71, sitting on a curb outside a Red Cross shelter where she
spent the night. She carried a Red Cross bag filled with
essentials, including lipstick and an emery board.
   One woman openly and randomly admonished those viewing the
wreckage.
   ``San Francisco has survived another earthquake. We've come
through. We're not a city of kooks or something that falls apart.
We are survivors,'' said Cynthia Woods, talking loudly to no one in
particular.
   On Chestnut Street, Pete Pallari set up his own emergency
kitchen to feed neighbors with leftovers from his restaurant, the O
Sole Mio Pizzeria. Cooking was done on a gas grill and a charcoal
fire, and the menu ranged from bacon and eggs to soup and French
bread.
   ``My refrigeration was gone, so it was either throw it away or
give it away. I couldn't save it,'' said Pallari, 42, operating
from the back of a pickup truck in an alleyway.
   Sanitation workers shoveled debris into garbage trucks,
including bricks and concrete shaken from buildings.
   The people who were ordered from their Marina district homes
because of the fear of leaking gas did what they could to get back
to normal. Junior Gale, who was staying at a hotel that still
lacked electricity, put her name on a waiting list for hot water so
she could wash her hair.
   Jim Braden, 38, was on his way to his law office with the
clothes he was wearing Tuesday _ surfer T-shirt, gray sweat pants
and brown dress shoes. ``My boss told me to come in with whatever I
was wearing,'' Braden said.
   In a gas station parking lot, Nita Blake sold $10 T-shirts that
said, ``Earthquake Survivor, 5:04 p.m. Oct. 17, 1989, the time and
day that the quake hit. Ten hours after that time she had 1,000
printed up. ``It was the biggest earthquake since 1906, so we
wanted to mark the occasion,'' she said.
   Pubs and taprooms stayed open despite lack of refrigeration and
ice. At Bachelors II, bartender Fred Miller stored dirty glasses in
boxes because he had no water to wash them. He served cocktails and
beer over ice in foam cups.
   At a nearby tavern, patrons drank by candlelight and toasted
their survival. ``We're glad were all here,'' said bartender Dick
Welsh. ``Some of our homes may be a shambles, but they can be
replaced. Life can't.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
