<FIRST>u i AM-Yeltsin 1stLd-Writethru a0678 10-19 0836</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeltsin, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0678,0853</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Interior Minister Calls Yeltsin a Liar</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 15: `We know ...' to CORRECT transposed words in quote.
Picks up graf 16 pvs, `He suggested ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOSB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The interior minister on Thursday called Boris N.
Yeltsin a liar and said the maverick Communist concocted a phony
tale of his own kidnap and attempted assassination apparently to
help his political popularity.
   ``He invented the entire story,'' said Interior Minister Vadim
V. Bakatin at a hastily called news conference. ``What the reason
was, I don't know. You should ask him.''
   Bakatin, the top Soviet policeman, said that by exposing the
populist lawmaker's alleged falsehood and rumors it spawned, ``we
have simply prevented a new outburst of popularity for Yeltsin.''
Yeltsin could not be reached for comment.
   It was the lastest twist in Yeltsin's remarkable career, which
has seen him ousted from his post as the Communist Party leader in
Moscow in 1987, only to stage a stunning comeback in legislative
elections this year.
   The interior minister spoke less than 24 hours after Yeltsin
issued a statement accusing his former mentor, President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, of staging a nationally televised ``political farce'' to
scuttle his political career.
   Before the cameras of state-run TV on Monday, Bakatin told the
Supreme Soviet legislature that Yeltsin, an anti-establishment hero
to millions of Soviets, appeared at a police post Sept. 28. Yeltsin
was dripping wet, and falsely reported that men in a car had
abducted him, put a sack over his head and tossed him from a bridge
into the Moscow River, Bakatin said.
   When he was given the floor, Yeltsin, 58, denied to fellow
lawmakers that he had ever made a formal police report of such an
incident or that an attack occurred. But he did not say whether he
had approached a policeman informally with such a story.
   In his toughly worded statement Wednesday, Yeltsin called the
glaring public exposure given his reputed claims ``a new attempt to
ruin my health and to knock me out of the sphere of political
struggle.'' He claimed Gorbachev was responsible.
   Bakatin's rapid appearance before reporters showed the Kremlin
was eager to counter Yeltsin's accusations.
   Yeltsin, a strapping, silver-haired Siberian who calls for an
end to official privilege and a better life for the average Soviet,
enjoys wide popular support, which seems to boom every time people
here perceive he has been targeted for attack by officialdom.
   Bakatin claimed that if any lies were being told about the
supposed kidnapping, they were coming from Yeltsin. ``I stated only
what Comrade Yeltsin told the policeman,'' Bakatin said. ``There
was no attempt on his life. These rumors are false.''
   He said Yeltsin ``lied publicly'' when he told his story to the
Supreme Soviet, and a second time a day later when he issued the
statement to the press accusing Gorbachev of staging a farce.
   Pressed to say what lies Yeltsin had told, Bakatin referred to
the lawmaker's statement claiming Bakatin mixed ``truth and lies''
in his report to the Supreme Soviet on the investigation into the
incident.
   He also said Yeltsin's alleged story to police couldn't possibly
be true.
   ``We know the terrain,'' Bakatin said. ``One can't be thrown
from the bridge into the water without suffering serious injuries.
There's also the time factor _ one can't do all these things in one
hour.''
   He suggested Yeltsin lied to police for political ends. ``This
is my personal guess, and it's nothing but a guess, that this false
declaration by Comrade Yeltsin was made on purpose: to distribute
information of interest to him,'' Bakatin said. ``He tried to gain
something by making those statements. Time will show how he
succeeds.''
   By puncturing the rumors sweeping Moscow that an attempt was
made on Yeltsin's life, ``we are putting an end to unfounded rumors
of political persecution,'' he said.
   However, evident official attempts in the past to discredit
Yeltsin have misfired badly. The Communist Party's policy-making
Central Committee, to which Yeltsin belongs, launched an
investigation into charges that his views violate the party line,
but 89 percent of Moscow voters subsequently elected him to the new
Soviet parliament in March.
   Last month, Pravda reprinted an article from an Italian
newspaper that claimed Yeltsin boozed and shopped his way through a
U.S. speaking tour, but later had to print a public apology
admitting the allegations were hearsay that couldn't be documented.
   Thousands of Muscovites formed a chain on Gorky Street to show
their support for Yeltsin, who was named Moscow party boss by
Gorbachev in December 1985 but fired less than two years later for
criticizing the slow pace of the Kremlin leader's reforms.
   Asked if Yeltsin would be prosecuted under Article 130 of the
Soviet criminal code for allegedly filing a false police report,
Bakatin said there were no such plans. Besides, he said, Yeltsin's
status as a lawmaker means his fellow legislators would have to
sanction any criminal investigation of him.
</TEXT>
