<FIRST>r w AM-US-Mideast     10-19 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Denies Trying to Get Israel to Talk Indirectly With PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a round of public recriminations, the
State Department sought Thursday to smooth over its differences
with Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and denied the Bush
administration was trying to steer him into negotiations with the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Shamir, vowing not to yield on basic principles, this week
questioned the strategy Secretary of State James A. Baker III is
following in trying to implement the prime minister's proposal for
Palestinian elections.
   Shamir questions the need for an Israeli meeting with
Palestinians in Cairo before the elections, seeing such a session
as pre-empting the talks that would be held with elected
Palestinian representatives from the West Bank and Gaza.
   The State Department, in response, on Wednesday accused Shamir
of hindering the attempt to arrange negotiations with what the
department characterized as unhelpful and disappointing remarks.
   On Thursday, however, spokeswoman Margaret D. Tutwiler said
Shamir had sent a letter to Baker ``that applauds our efforts and
encourages us to keep them up.''
   At the same time, she said:
   ``The United States is not trying to get the Israelis to
negotiate with the PLO. We are trying to get the Israelis and the
Palestinians together behind the Shamir election proposal.''
   Baker had already assured the prime minister that Israel would
have to be ``satisfied'' with the composition of any Palestinian
delegation. But Baker also has supported Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak's effort to negotiate the selection with the PLO.
   The PLO Central Council, meanwhile, rejected Baker's five-point
proposal at a meeting this week in Baghdad, Iraq.
   Still, Ms. Tutwiler rejected reports from Egypt and Israel that
the U.S. initiative had come to a stop. ``Every single thing that I
know certainly leads me to believe that we're all still engaged,''
she said. ``Nothing's changed.''
   The PLO has denounced Shamir's proposal as a ploy designed to
avert creation of a Palestinian state on Israeli-held land. Shamir,
meanwhile, has ruled out any negotiations with the PLO or including
PLO members in any Palestinian delegation.
</TEXT>
