<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-19 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Snowfall, Record Cold</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Unusually early snow fell Thursday across parts of the Midwest,
and temperatures dropped to record lows across the Plains.
   It was the earliest snowfall on record for many cities,
including Cincinnati; Dayton, Ohio; Indianapolis; Fort Wayne, Ind.,
and St. Louis.
   About 6 inches of snow fell overnight and in the morning over
sections of Indiana.
   By midday, snow was falling over lower Michigan, Illinois,
Indiana and western Kentucky.
   Snowfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included 4 inches
in Fort Wayne and Indianapolis; 3 inches in Grand Rapids, Mich.;
and 2 inches in Detroit and Flint, Mich.
   Rain extended from southern New York and southern New England
into North Carolina, and from Ohio to Tennessee, northern
Mississippi and northern Alabama. Showers and thunderstorms fell in
southern and central Florida.
   Winter-like air settled over the central half of the nation.
   Record lows for the date were posted in North Platte, Neb.,
where it was 11 degrees; Valentine, Neb., 13; San Angelo, Texas,
28; Hot Springs, Ark., 31; Wichita Falls, Texas, 30; Mena, Ark.,
33; Waco, Texas, and Houston, both 37; San Antonio, Del Rio and
Fort Worth, Texas, all 38; Austin, Texas, 42; Victoria, Texas, 44;
and Galveston, Texas, 47.
   Frost and freeze warnings into Friday morning were posted for
sections of Kansas, Missouri, Tennessee, Arkansas, Oklahoma, Texas,
Louisiana, Mississippi, Alabama and Georgia. Unseasonably low
temperatures were forecast for much of Florida.
   At the other extreme, Miami International Airport reported a
record high for the date of 91 degrees, and Key West, Fla., tied
its record of 89.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 32
degrees in Bloomington, Ill.; Bloomington, Ind., and Muskegon,
Mich., to 91 in Palm Springs, Calif. Thursday's low for the Lower
48 states was 4 degrees in Gunnison, Colo.
</TEXT>
