<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Bombing 1stLd-Writethru a0741 10-19 0864</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Bombing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0741,0885</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Admits Four Wrongly Convicted; Inquiry Begins</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7 grafs for last 4 grafs `While expressing ... Billy Power'
to CORRECT casualties in Birmingham and ADD background on Terrorism Act
and special courts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three people wrongly convicted 14 years ago for an
IRA bombing walked free Thursday, while the government began an
inquiry into police actions that led an appeals court to reverse
the convictions.
   One other man cleared in the pub bombing case was taken to
Belfast where his attorneys sought bail pending an appeal of an
unrelated murder conviction.
   ``This is a very grave matter for all who care about justice,''
Home Secretary Douglas Hurd told the House of Commons.
   The appeals court ruling climaxed years of effort by relatives,
former government officials, church leaders and journalists to
overturn the verdict, and focused new attention on two other
bombing cases from the 1970s.
   The sentence of the four had been upheld in 1977 even though
members of an IRA gang made detailed confessions in the case.
   ``I've been in prison for 15 years for something I didn't do.
I'm totally innocent,'' Gerard Conlon told cheering well-wishers
outside the Old Bailey following his release.
   ``If you're Irish, and you're arrested on a terrorist, political
type of offense, you don't stand a chance. You just don't stand a
chance,'' Conlon said in an interview with Independent Television
News.
   The appeals court threw out the convictions of Conlon, 35,
Patrick Armstrong, 39, and Paul Hill, 35, all of Belfast, and
Carole Richardson, 32, of London, in the bombing of a pub in
Guildford, southwest of London, on Oct. 5, 1974.
   All had been sentenced to life in prison. ``Thank God we've not
got capital punishment,'' Conlon's attorney Anthony Scrivener told
the court.
   The convictions of Armstrong and Hill for a pub bombing in the
London suburb of Woolwich on Nov. 6, 1974, were also reversed.
   Hill was arrested again and taken to Belfast in Northern
Ireland, where he had been convicted and sentenced to life in
prison for the murder of a former British soldier.
   New evidence ``throws such doubt upon the honesty and integrity
of a number of the Surrey officers investigating this case in 1974
that the Crown now feels unable to say that the convictions of any
of the four are safe or satisfactory,'' Roy Amlot of the Office of
Public Prosecutions told the hearing.
   The prosecution case was based entirely on confessions ``and in
particular on the integrity of the officers taking them,'' said
Amlot, who disclosed evidence that five officers had altered
documents, withheld evidence and ``seriously misled the court.''
   Lord Lane, the Lord Chief Justice, responded: ``In fact, they
must have lied.''
   Three of the five officers are still serving on the Surrey
department. Two were suspended Wednesday, said David Williams,
Surrey's deputy chief constable. Hurd said a third officer was
hospitalized, and the other two are retired.
   An independent assessor will recommend financial compensation
for the four, Hurd said.
   ``All the money in the world would not compensate for what my
son has gone through the last 15 years,'' said Eileen Armstrong,
who then burst into tears.
   Hurd said the judicial inquiry, to be headed by retired appeals
judge Sir John May, would also examine the conviction of the
``Maguire Seven,'' including Conlon's late father, on explosives
charges.
   That case developed from statements by Hill and Conlon that
Conlon's aunt, Annie Maguire, had manufactured bombs. She was
convicted of possession of explosives, as was her husband, Patrick,
their sons, Vincent and Patrick, and Patrick Conlon, Patrick
O'Neill and Sean Smyth. Conlon died in prison in 1980; the others
have served their sentences.
   While expressing satisfaction that ``the system has the capacity
to correct its own mistakes,'' Prime Minister Charles Haughey of
Ireland said he believed a similar error was made in the conviction
of six Irish men for two Birmingham pub bombings Nov. 21, 1974, in
which 21 people were killed and 160 wounded.
   The convictions were upheld last year.
   ``The official admission that a miscarriage of justice can
happen and does happen has major implications for other ... cases
and in particular the Birmingham six,'' said Paul May, chairman of
a group supporting the six convicts.
   ``We've still got a long, hard slog, but we can now see the end
of the road,'' said Breda Power, daughter of Billy Power, one of
the Birmingham convicts.
   Eight days after the Birmingham bombing, Parliament passed the
Prevention of Terrorism Act, allowing police to hold terrorism
suspects without charge for 48 hours and, in some cases, five more
days.
   Hill's conviction in the Guildford bombing was in one of the
Northern Ireland ``Diplock courts'' created in 1973, in which
judges decide terrorism cases without juries. A 1986 study found
that 89 percent of defendants in those courts pleaded guilty; of
those who pleaded innocent, 57 percent were convicted.
   Before Surrey police were accused of mishandling the Guildford
case, there were scandals of false confessions in the Kent and West
Midlands police forces. One officer was dismissed, two were
suspended and several were disciplined.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
