<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Thornburgh     10-19 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Thornburgh,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Atty General Signs Nazi Prosecution Accord, Meets KGB Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Richard Thornburgh, the top U.S.
prosecutor, met with the head of the KGB and signed an agreement on
joint prosecution of Nazi war criminals to conclude a five-day trip
to Moscow, Tass said Thursday.
   The memorandum on Nazis signed by Thornburgh and Soviet
Prosecutor-General Alexander Sukharev formalized the existing
practice of cooperating on investigation of suspects and bringing
them to trial, Tass reported. Thornburgh said there are still about
10,000 Nazi war criminals worldwide.
   Thornburgh met with KGB chief Vladimir Kryuchkov, Prime Minister
Nikolai Ryzhkov and their fellow member of the 11-man ruling
Politburo, Alexander Yakovlev. He also spoke with Vice President
Anatoly Lukyanov, Interior Minister Vadim Bakatin and Supreme Court
Chairman E.A. Smolentsev.
   The visit, the first by a U.S. attorney general to the Soviet
Union, came at a time when the Soviet legislature is debating legal
guarantees of human rights, reform of the criminal justice system
and changes in the criminal code. Thornburgh discussed the American
experience in these areas with his Soviet hosts, Tass said.
</TEXT>
