<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-PacificExchange 1stLd-Writethru a0734 10-19
0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Pacific Exchange, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0734,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Logistical Nightmare, But Pacific Exchange Keeps Trading Elsewhere</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with end of trading day; pick
up 4th graf pvs, `Stock trading ...' A version moved on the financial wire.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A chartered plane, a few helicopters and several hotels later,
options dealers from the Pacific Stock Exchange had a smooth day of
trading Thursday at makeshift posts in the Chicago, New York and
Philadelphia markets.
   ``What we pulled off ... was no mean feat,'' said exchange
spokesman Dale Carlson. ``I just shipped 140 guys away from their
families a day after the worst catastrophe in San Francisco
history.''
   If Tuesday's quake wasn't quite the worst catastrophe in the
city's history _ that distinction still belongs to the 1906
earthquake _ the trading airlift was indeed a mean feat. It was an
unprecedented logistical nightmare that involved carpenters,
electricians, computer experts and the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
   Officials at the various exchanges said trading went smoothly.
``There were no hitches,'' said Warren Moulds at the Chicago Board
Options Exchange. ``Once they got oriented, it was an easy do.''
   Stock trading continued Wednesday at the exchange in San
Francisco, a day after the earthquake knocked out power and
computers. Dealers worked by candle and flashlight, rerouting
trades via phone through Los Angeles.
   But the Los Angeles exchange doesn't trade options, so about 150
Pacific options traders and support staffers had to be moved east
so investors could continue trading stock options listed solely on
the Pacific exchange.
   The timing was critical because of the looming expiration of
October stock options. Friday is the deadline for investors to
renegotiate the options, which let them buy or sell specific stocks
at a specific price at a certain time.
   The exchange trades options in 130 stocks, with 70,000 contracts
changing hands on an average day. Among big-name stocks that have
options traded only on the Pacific exchange are Hilton Hotels Corp.
and Compaq Computer Corp.
   In San Francisco, building inspectors OK'd the trading floors
Thursday, but Carlson said options traders would remain where they
were through Friday.
   The marathon effort was sanctioned Wednesday by the SEC. At the
American and New York exchanges, carpenters and electricians worked
through the night on trading areas; at the Philadelphia Stock
Exchange, computer experts laid extra cables and programmed
computers to accept new issues.
   The Pacific crews arrived by chartered jet shortly before dawn
Thursday in Chicago. The jet headed for Newark, N.J., where some
traders caught buses into New York and others caught helicopters
and limousines to Philadelphia.
   ``They haven't slept in 24 hours, plus the trauma of the
earthquake. Our hats are off to them,'' said Philadelphia exchange
President Nicholas Giordano. In Chicago, Pacific trading began at
the market's 8:30 a.m. CDT opening. In New York and Philadelphia,
extra time was needed for traders to arrive and get settled, and
trading didn't begin until 1 p.m. EDT.
   The exchanges ``opened up their doors like good Samaritans,''
said George Kender, executive vice president of the Chicago-based
Options Clearing Corp., which clears all trades in options. ``The
cooperation has been phenomenal.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
