<FIRST>u w AM-Quake-FreddieMac     10-19 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quake-Freddie Mac,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mortgage Agency Holds Off Foreclosing On Quake-Damaged Homes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Freddie Mac, a federally chartered mortgage
agency, on Thursday offered a moratorium on foreclosures for
homeowners whose properties were damaged by the San Francisco
earthquake.
   The agency, formally known as the Federal Home Loan Mortgage
Corp., will permit the moratorium on single-family home mortgages
until Jan. 1. Also, on a case-by-case basis, it will offer a
temporary suspension or reduction in mortgage payments.
   ``We felt it necessary to move quickly in providing immediate
relief. ... We are aware that many homeowners have inadequate or no
earthquake insurance on their properties,'' said Freddie Mac Vice
President Jo Ann Pierson.
   Homeowners should contact their lenders to determine whether
their mortgages were sold to the agency, which helps finance one in
eight of American homes, she said.
   Freddie Mac, which purchases mortgages from lenders, packages
them into securities and resells them to investors, is offering a
similar program to victims of Hurricane Hugo.
</TEXT>
