<FIRST>r e AM-SonyClassical     10-19 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sony Classical,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Classical Division of CBS Records Becomes New Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sony Classical is making plans to record pianist
Vladimir Horowitz this month and operas beginning next year and to
release home videos of concerts.
   The first opera to be recorded will be ``Aida'' next May, with
Metropolitan Opera personnel and conductor James Levine. The
following November, ``Salome'' will be recorded, with soprano Eva
Marton and Zubin Mehta conducting the Berlin Philharmonic. In
February 1991, two recordings will be made at La Scala, both
starring tenor Placido Domingo with Lorin Maazel conducting.
   ``If you want to be taken seriously as an important label, which
I feel is the task I have, you have to show you are looking out for
the best,'' said Gunther Breest, president since January of Sony
Classical, formerly the classical division of CBS Records.
   ``It's not a question you have to make the return of investment
within three years. With top artists we should be allowed to have a
long-lasting catalog buildup,'' Breest said.
   Breest said that CBS-signed artists including Isaac Stern, Yo-Yo
Ma, Midori and Murray Perahia will record for Sony Classical, and
European orchestras including the Berlin Philharmonic, Vienna
Philharmonic and Concertgebouw of Amsterdam. The only American
orchestra on the label will be the Boston Pops with conductor John
Williams.
   Breest moved to Sony Classical after 18 years with Deutsche
Grammophon, where he produced recordings made by conductor Herbert
von Karajan and became executive vice president. Sony Corp. owns
CBS Records.
   The president of Sony Corp., Norio Ohga, who lured Breest away
from Deutsche Grammophon, is a former opera baritone married to a
pianist.
   ``This gives me a good feeling of support that the top
management of Sony has an understanding for our dreams and
ambitions,'' Breest said.
   Sony Classical will have editing and mixing facilities in New
York and Hamburg, with mobile equipment to take where recordings
are done. There will be a recording studio in Berlin.
   Sony Classical will market home videos starting in late spring,
some already made, including some with von Karajan, and some new
ones including this year's New Year's concert in Vienna, Bruckner's
``Fourth Symphony'' with Sergiu Celibidache and the Munich
Philharmonic, Itzhak Perlman with Daniel Barenboim, a recital by
Perahia and ``Pictures at an Exhibition'' by Sir Georg Solti with
the Chicago Symphony.
</TEXT>
