<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Popieluszko     10-19 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Popieluszko,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Honor Solidarity Priest Slain Five Years Ago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and Cardinal
Josef Glemp led 15,000 mourners Thursday at an anniversary Mass for
the Rev. Jerzy Popieluszko, a popular priest slain by the secret
police five years ago.
   Many of the 259 Solidarity members of Parliament attended the
90-minute outdoor evening service at St. Stanislaw Kostka's Church,
Popieluszko's former parish in a residential neighborhood of
northern Warsaw.
   Dozens of buses that brought workers from around the country
lined the street in front of the church. Hundreds of candles
flickered on the sidewalks surrounding the grounds.
   Scores of banners proclaimed representatives of factories and
Solidarity chapters throughout Poland. One banner near the grave
said: ``Jerzy, today we collect the fruit of your suffering.''
   Popieluszko supported workers in the difficult years after the
declaration of martial law Dec. 13, 1981. Pro-Solidarity
demonstrations and clashes with security police have marked
previous anniversaries of his death.
   He became a symbol of Solidarity's struggle for recognition.
Foreign leaders, such as Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of
Britain, visited his grave.
   Glemp, the Roman Catholic primate of Poland, said in his sermon:
``After five years, the nation remembers the brave chaplain and
will remember. Father Jerzy believed, and spread this belief, that
time would come for the victory of truth.''
   Glemp put Popieluszko in the pantheon of great Poles, such as
composer Frederic Chopin, who died in France 140 years ago this
week.
   The crowd warmly welcomed a delegation from Hungary, which, like
Poland, has set a course away from communism and toward democracy.
   ``We'd like to put into practice in our country, in Hungary,
what Father Popieluszko was teaching us,'' said a Hungarian priest
accompanying the group.
   He told the Poles an exhibition on Popieluszko opened in Hungary
this month, and asked for prayers for the Hungarian Roman Catholic
church.
   Walesa went to Popieluszko's grave for a silent prayer before
the Mass, but did not speak at the service.
   Political life in Poland has dramatically changed this year. Not
only has Solidarity been made legal again, but a former Solidarity
editor is prime minister of the first non-Communist government in
the Soviet bloc.
   State radio and television, now directed by a Solidarity member,
carried a range of programs about Popieluszko, including comments
by his mother and an interview with his former driver.
   Three secret policemen abducted the priest Oct. 19, 1984. Ten
days later, his bound and gagged body was pulled from the freezing
Vistula River.
   The three policeman and their commanding officer were convicted
of murder in February 1985.
   Testimony at the trial indicated Popieluszko was killed because
of his activities in defense of workers dismissed or jailed for
supporting Solidarity.
   One of the convicted policeman has been released under a reduced
sentence, but the others remain in prison.
</TEXT>
