<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Transportation     10-19 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Transportation,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commuters Struggle To Reach Work, Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By train, by boat and by car, commuters
struggled to reach work Thursday following the deadly quake that
closed the vital bridge linking San Francisco to Oakland and the
rest of the East bay.
   A 50-foot section of the San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge
collapsed during Tuesday evening's quake, which measured 6.9 on the
Richter scale.
   Many commuters found themselves stuck in traffic jams. Others
arrived at buildings still in the dark or with only partial power.
Others turned back after facing up to four-hour delays on the
overburdened highways.
   ``People are just trying to get back to reality, to make life
like it was before,'' said Steve Tomberlin of Traffic Central, a
private traffic information service.
   Many city residents biked or walked to work, and at least one
businessman roller-skated down from Twin Peaks.
   Commuters from the south faced up to a four-hour delay, compared
to the average hour-long drive, according to Tomberlin. People
trying to reach work from Marin and Sonoma counties to the north
faced delays of up to 90 minutes.
   In the populous southern half of the San Francisco Bay area,
freeways jammed up in both directions from Hayward in the east to
Gilroy in the west. Traffic in the northern, less-populated part of
the nine-county region was lighter. But in some areas, particularly
for eastbound commuters heading from San Francisco and Marin County
to Alameda and Contra Costa counties, traffic was backed up for
several miles.
   In some highway stretches, several of them stretching for 10
miles, traffic was stop-and-go at maximum speeds of 5 mph.
   The Bay Area Rapid Transit system restored full operations for
the Wednesday morning commute, but spokesman Mike Healy said the
passenger load _ typically about 50,000 people each way on weekdays
_ was slightly below normal early in the commute. But trains were
standing-room only by mid-morning, hours past the traditional rush
hour.
   The San Francisco Municipal Railway, the city's bus, cable car
and trolley system, normally carries 800,000 passengers daily. The
system was 30 percent below normal, according to spokesman George
Newkirk.
   The passenger load on buses and ferries operated by the Golden
Gate Transit system from north of the city was about half normal,
officials said.
   About 3,000 commuters arrived in San Francisco by boat. The Red
&amp; White Fleet, Blue &amp; Gold Fleet and Hornblower Yacht Service
offered trips to the Berkeley and Oakland waterfronts, where
ferries don't normally stop.
</TEXT>
