<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Drugs     10-19 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Drugs,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Medellin Cartel Colombians Captured in Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexican authorities have captured the nephews
of two major Colombian drug kingpins and broken up a ring that flew
cocaine into Mexico and shipped it by boat to Florida, authorities
said Thursday.
   The Colombians were captured along with eight other men Sunday
at a clandestine airstrip in the Yucatan Peninsula, according to
federal police commander Fausto Valverde, head of the narcotics
interdiction forces.
   Two other men were captured in the resort city of Cancun, but
one Colombian escaped in an airplane, Valverde said.
   The leaders of the Yucatan ring were Luis Alfredo Aguilar
Castro, a nephew of Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha, and Ricardo Isunza
Ochoa, a nephew of Fabio Ochoa, Valverde said.
   Fabio Ochoa and Rodriguez Gacha, known as ``El Mexicano''
because of his fondness for things Mexican, are top members of the
Medellin cartel and are among the world's most wanted drug
traffickers.
   Valverde said Aguilar and Isunza Ochoa were their uncles'
representatives in the smuggling operation. When asked if the two
might be extradited to the United States, Valverde said, ``Anything
is possible.''
   He said he didn't know what charges the two might be wanted on
in Colombia or in the United States, nor if a U.S.-Colombia
agreement under which drug traffickers can be extradited to the
United States would apply.
   Commander Miguel Rodriguez Lorrabaquio said the case was
unrelated to recent large drug busts along the U.S.-Mexico border,
including the seizure of nine tons of cocaine in Harlingen, Texas,
and 20 tons in a Los Angeles suburb.
   Lorrabaquio said the Yucatan ring brought cocaine in from
Colombia by air, then shipped it by boat to the United States,
usually to Florida, while the cocaine seized along the border was
probably being taken across by land.
   Valverde said the airplane carrying the drugs escaped when
someone on the ground warned the pilot by radio that Mexican police
were at the airstrip.
   He said authorities were looking into whether the drugrunners
had any official or unofficial protection for their ground
operations.
   ``We imagine they made an arrangement for protection,'' Valverde
said.
   Valverde said that in spite of the situation in Colombia, where
drug-related violence has increased since the August assassination
of a presidential candidate, there had been no threats against
Mexican law enforcement officials over the seizure of Aguilar and
Isunza Ochoa.
   Valverde said U.S. and Colombian authorities had no involvement
in the three-month investigation and bust.
</TEXT>
