<FIRST>u a AM-NurseTrial     10-19 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nurse Trial,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arguments Begin in Trial of Nurse Charged With Lethally Injecting
Patients</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Colins is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ex-nurse charged with killing four
hospital patients with lethal injections was a ``monster'' dressed
in white who switched from mice to humans for experiments, a
prosecutor said in opening arguments Thursday.
   Richard Angelo was ``the living embodiment of your worst
nightmare,'' Assistant District Attorney John Colins told the jury.
   ``He conducted uncontrolled experiments on knowingly terribly
vulnerable human beings for his stated purposes of improving his
image and reputation,'' Colins said.
   Police have said Angelo admitted he injected patients at a Long
Island hospital to put them on the brink of death so he could be
the first on the scene to resuscitate them and look like a hero to
his colleagues.
   Angelo, 27, was a nurse for about six months in 1987 at Good
Samaritan Hospital, when four patients, ranging in age from 57 to
75, died within minutes of being injected with the muscle relaxant
Pavulon. Three other patients survived Pavulon injections.
   The Lindenhurst man is charged with four counts of second-degree
murder and three counts of assault.
   Eric Naiburg, Angelo's attorney, conceded that Angelo injected
the patients with the drug and that some of those patients may have
died as a result of what he did. But he said Angelo is not guilty
of murder. He suggested a count of lesser homicide or assault.
   Colins charged that Angelo turned to humans after tiring of
performing drug experiments on mice.
   ``To unsuspecting patients in the special care unit at Good
Samaritan Hospital, (Angelo) was a monster dressed in nurse's
whites,'' Colins said. ``He was not content to stop after
experimenting first with his mice and watching them die.''
   One of those Angelo is charged with assaulting, Gerolamo Kucich,
75, testified that Angelo asked him how he was feeling and then
injected him with a paralyzing drug after saying, ``This will make
you feel much better.''
   ``I became like dead. ... I couldn't move,'' said Kucich, who
had been hospitalized after suffering a heart attack. ``I was
thinking, how long is it going to last before I die?''
   As Kucich testified, Angelo sat at the defense table with his
eyes downcast.
   Kucich said he pressed the emergency alarm and his regular
nurse, Lauren Ball, came in and helped revive him.
   Moments later, Angelo returned to the room, but Kucich said he
still couldn't talk or see. He said he heard Angelo's voice and
pointed toward the voice.
   According to Kucich, Mrs. Ball asked Angelo, ``What did you do?''
   Kucich said Angelo answered, ``Nothing,'' and left the room.
</TEXT>
