<FIRST>r a AM-LaExecution     10-19 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-La Execution,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Execution Delayed Again for Louisiana's Longest Death Row Resident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANGOLA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Thursday stayed the execution
of Louisiana's longest death-row resident less than 12 hours before
he was to go to the electric chair for killing a state trooper in
1977.
   U.S. District Judge Donald E. Walter granted Dalton Prejean, 30,
the stay shortly after receiving Prejean's latest appeal, saying
the early Friday deadline gave him too little time to review it.
   Louisiana State Penitentiary officials had been preparing the
electric chair for use just after midnight.
   Prejean was in another section of the prison at a state Pardon
Board hearing, where friends and family pleaded for clemency. But
the hearing was suspended after Walter's ruling.
   On Wednesday, the state Supreme Court refused to hear an appeal
by Prejean, who was 17 when he shot trooper Donald Cleveland to
death after the officer stopped the car Prejean and his brother
were in.
   The murder occurred only six months after Prejean's release from
a reform school, where he'd been sent for killing a taxi driver
when he was 14.
   Prejean has been on death row 10 years, longer than any other
Louisiana convict. Eight previous execution dates were canceled by
state or federal courts.
   In his latest appeal, Prejean's attorneys claim the prosecution
systematically excluded blacks from the jury.
   No new date was set for the Pardon Board hearing. The board can
recommend a more lenient sentence for a convicted killer. The
recommendation must be acted on by the governor.
</TEXT>
