<DOCNO> AP891019-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 2122EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina     10-19 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Menem Meets with Pardoned Terrorists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Menem spent 45
minutes Thursday with two terrorists he had pardoned, who told
reporters the return of democracy had removed the need for the
anti-government violence they advocated in the 1970s.
   Fernando Vaca Narvaja and Roberto Perdia, who until 12 days ago
were fugitives in hiding outside the country, told a Government
House news conference they had thanked Menem for the pardon and
pledged to work for national reconciliation.
   ``There is no possibility ... of armed action when democratic
institutions are in full force,'' said Vaca Narvaja, who promised
to return ransom money his Montonero guerrillas extorted from
kidnap victims.
   Norvaja, now 41 and in a jacket and tie, looked more like a
middle-class professional than someone once accused of murder,
kidnapping, assault, bombings, jailbreak, airplane hijacking and
other crimes.
   Perdia, paunchy and pinstriped at 48, looked equally unlike a
revolutionary whose actions helped bring on the military coup of
March 1976 and the ``dirty war'' against suspected leftists that
raged until the end of the decade.
   ``It is absolutely essential to think of and construct a future
for the living, without forgetting the past,'' he said.
   On Oct. 7, Menem pardoned 39 colonels, generals and vice
admirals who faced trial for kidnapping, torture and murder in the
disappearances and presumed deaths of 9,000 people during nearly
eight years of military rule. The junta left power upon the
election of lawyer Raul Alfonsin as president in 1983.
   Menem, a former provincial governor who succeeded Alfonsin in
July, also pardoned 64 guerrillas and indicated he soon would free
Jorge Videla and Roberto Viola, army generals who served as
presidents of the military juntas and are in prison for human
rights violations.
   Also on the potential pardon list is Mario Firmenich, co-founder
of the Montoneros, who is serving a 30-year sentence for murder.
   Menem's goal is to end a bloody chapter in Argentine history and
concentrate on dealing with Argentina's chronic inflation, a
protracted recession and uncharacteristically high unemployment.
   The military has insisted since relinquishing power to Alfonsin
in December 1983 that it fought a kind of civil war against
terrorists. Rights groups accuse the military of wholesale killing.
   Rights groups and leftist political organizations opposed the
military pardons and say they hope to gather a million signatures
on a petition for reversal. Opponents also called a demonstration
for Friday outside the faded pink Government House.
   Meanwhile two of the three largest political parties have
endorsed the pardon, as has the Roman Catholic Church, the largest
newspapers and the most influential business and farm groups.
</TEXT>
