<SECOND>AM-East Germany, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0687,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Groups Warn of Continued Unrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Krenz's later activities, indicating
perhaps some softening, details. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BER07</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-democracy activists said on Thursday that the
choice of Egon Krenz as East Germany's new leader could lead to
protesters again filling the streets unless he belies his hard-line
reputation and implements reforms.
   Krenz succeeded Erich Honecker on Wednesday and soon made clear
in an address to the nation the communist party will resist the
democratic trends evident in East Germany's Warsaw Pact allies
Hungary and Poland.
   But he said West Germany's refusal to recognize East German
citizenship was an obstacle to expanding travel to the West.
   Krenz on Thursday visited an East Berlin factory and his
encounter with workers, which touched on broad public
dissatisfaction, was deemed by West Germany's ARD TV network
``unthinkable only a few weeks ago.''
   Excerpts of the footage shown on Aktuelle Kamera, East Germany's
main evening newscast, were carried by West German networks.
   When asked by Krenz why so many co-workers had fled to West
Germany, metal worker Ronald Berus said: ``A lot of things kept
adding up until some people felt there was just no alternative.''
   Several workers complained of the rigid travel restrictions,
which recently were expanded to include Czechoslovakia, Poland and
Hungary after more than 53,000 East German refugeess streamed there
to begin their treks West.
   The unusual presentation may reflect a willingness by Krenz to
allow more frank discussion of national problems in the
state-controlled media.
   Krenz also met with Werner Leich, head of the East German
Lutheran Church Federation, for talks described by East German TV
as ``open and constructive.''
   Krenz said Wednesday he wanted to improve relations between
church and state.
   Also Thursday, the West German newspaper Bild said Poland's
state bank is selling for hard currency 100 million East German
marks it holds in banks in Frankfurt. Bild said the bank acted
because of ``a lack of confidence in (East Germany's) internal
stability'' and as a hedge against a possible revaluation of East
Germany's currency.
   East Germany officially pegs one East German mark equal to one
West German mark. In reality, it is worth perhaps a fourth of that.
A dollar now fetches about 1.85 West German marks.
   Reinhard Schult, a founder of New Forum, the largest
pro-democracy group in East Germany, said Thursday on RIAS radio of
West Berlin, ``Krenz stands for the continuation of neo-Stalinst
politics.''
   He said Krenz ``did not have one word to say about the causes of
the current crisis and made no offer for talks with the
opposition.''
   Author Rolf Schneider, a critic of the government, told RIAS:
``The crisis will keep dragging on.''
   A Lutheran church leader said privately, ``The demonstrations
will start again soon'' unless the government changes its course.
The church has been in the forefront of reform efforts.
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher of West Germany urged
Krenz to make ``fundamental reforms.'' He said East Germans demand
``their basic rights.''
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, a champion of reform,
sent Krenz a telegram expressing confidence he would ``respond to
the demands of the time, following a course of renewal and
continuity.''
   In Poland, the only Soviet bloc nation with a non-communist
government, both pro-Solidarity and communist party newspapers
described Honecker's departure as a welcome change.
   Newspapers in Hungary, which is moving rapidly from communism
toward Western-style democracy, said Krenz was seen as a
``transitional figure.''
   Reform activists in East Germany said 1,000 people peacefully
protested in Greifswald hours after Krenz, 52, a protege of
Honecker, was named leader.
   More than 120,000 pro-democracy protesters marched in Leipzig on
Monday.
   On Thursday, many residents of East Berlin were skeptical about
the leadership change.
   ``Krenz just wants to calm us down,'' said a worker in his
mid-20s. ``We'll have to see if there's going to be anything more
than words this time.''
</TEXT>
