<HEAD>Bush Tours Photo Exhibit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush toured an exhibit of famous
news photos Thursday, from the flag-raising at Iwo Jima to the shot
of Lyndon Johnson taking the oath of office aboard Air Force One
with the newly widowed Jacqueline Kennedy at his side.
   There was also one picture on the wall at the exhibit in Union
Station that was close to home for Bush: a picture of the
president, Barbara Bush and assorted children and grandchildren in
bed at Kennebunkport.
   That picture was shot by White House photographer David Valdez,
who joined dozens of his colleagues at the crowded reception
attended by the president.
   The exhibit, ``Witness to History: 150 Years of
Photojournalism,'' was sponsored by the Eastman Kodak Co., and all
the pictures in the exhibit appear in a special Oct. 23 issue of
Time Magazine.
   Among the photographers crowding around Bush were Cecil
Stoughton, who took the Johnson oath of office picture; David Hume
Kennerly, who was Gerald Ford's White House photographer, and
Michael A.W. Evans, Ronald Reagan's photographer.
