<HEAD>Moroccan King Inaugurates Council</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RABAT, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hassan II of Morocco inaugurated the
first session Thursday of the Union of Arab Maghreb Consultative
Council, comprising 10 parliamentarians each from Algeria, Morocco,
Tunisia, Libya and Mauritania.
   The 50 delegates will elect officers and review the work of the
Union of Arab Maghreb since it was established at a summit meeting
in February in Marrakech. The union aims at setting up a common
market of 100 million people.
   Hassan said he would like to increase the number of council
members but did not specify a figure.
   Morocco will hand over the federation chairmanship to Tunisia at
yearend.
