<FIRST>r i AM-EdenPastora     10-19 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eden Pastora,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Sandinista Commander Zero to Return to Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eden Pastora, a commander in the
Sandinista revolution who later defected to lead a rebel group,
said Thursday he will return to Nicaragua in six weeks.
   Pastora and Nicaraguan opposition presidential candidate Erick
Ramirez held a news conference to sign a pact ``to fight against
the Somozistas who remain in Nicaragua and against the new
Sandinista dictatorship.''
   Ramirez is the candiate of the Social Christian Party.
   Pastora said he would return Dec. 3, a day before the official
start of the campaign for Feb. 25, 1990, general elections.
   The main candidates are Violeta Barrios de Chamorro, an
opposition newspaper publisher from the 14-party United National
Opposition coalition, and President Daniel Ortega, who is running
for re-election.
   The Yatama organization of Indians and other Atlantic coast
minority groups and the small Popular Social Christian Party have
said they will support Ramirez.
   Pastora gained fame for leading an assault on the National
Palace on Aug. 22, 1978, during the Sandinista revolution. The
revolution overthrew President Anastasio Somoza on July 19, 1979,
ending the 42-year Somoza family dynasty.
   After breaking with the Sandinistas in 1982, Pastora formed the
Revolutionary Democratic Alliance, which fought from Nicaragua's
southern border until 1986.
   Five other former Contra leaders have returned to Nicaragua in
recent weeks.
