<FIRST>r w AM-DC-Drugs     10-19 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-Drugs,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Czar Admits Drugs Problem In Nation's Capital Worsening</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Drug Policy Coordinator William J.
Bennett said on Thursday that the drug crisis in the District of
Columbia continues to worsen despite a six-month joint partnership
by federal and local authorities fighting the problem.
   ``No one should be surprised to learn that the nation's capital
is still plagued by a serious drug problem,'' Bennett said at a
news conference. ``We picked a difficult task last April, and I
never had any illusions about the challenges that lay before us.''
   Bennett made his remarks while issuing a six-month ``progress
report'' on a special initiative he generated to help the district
curb its record murder rate and drug-related crime wave.
   So far in 1989, 360 persons have been killed in the district, 12
short of the all-time annual record that was set last year. By this
time in 1988, 270 homicides had been reported in Washington. Police
blame drugs, particularly crack cocaine, for more than 60 percent
of these deaths.
   On Wednesday, city officials complained that Bennett's
contributions have done little to stop the killings and said he has
taken credit for a variety of other anti-drug programs and
initiatives already in effect.
   ``Where we need help, they have not responded,'' said Frank
Jasmine, an assistant to City Administrator Carol B. Thompson.
``There's a long road to go.''
   Bennett defended the federal government's efforts, but said he
knew that local and federal authorities are in for a long battle.
   ``I wouldn't say that (we) haven't made any difference, but I
would still say the situation is intolerable,'' Bennett said. ``We
are in the process of getting control of the situation...but it
will take time.''
   Bennett, who criticized the city government for its handling of
the drug crisis shortly after he took office, said on Thursday that
his office is working better with district officials now.
</TEXT>
