<FIRST>r i AM-Nobel-China     10-19 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nobel-China,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Threatens to Cut Ties with Norway over Nobel Award</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nobels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China threatened to cut economic ties with
Norway if the government or king attends the ceremony awarding the
Nobel Peace Prize to the Dalai Lama, Norwegian TV said, but Norway
showed no sign of give Thursday.
   Egil Aarvik, head of the awarding committee, dismissed the
threat while assessing China's reaction as the strongest by any
government since Adolf Hitler's fury when an anti-Nazi won the
award 53 years ago.
   ``Hitler reacted with a similar rage when Carl von Ossietzky won
the prize for 1935,'' Aarvik told The Associated Press on Thursday.
   Ossietzky, a German journalist, peace activist and opponent of
Hitler, was in a Nazi concentration camp when the award was made in
1936. Hitler responded by saying no German would be allowed to
accept the prize.
   The Dalai Lama, exiled Buddhist leader of Tibet, was named the
peace laureate Oct. 5 for his non-violent struggle to end Chinese
rule of his homeland. The announcement was widely seen as an
implied rebuke to Beijing for its crackdown on pro-democracy
protesters in June.
   Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Sigrid Romundset said the Chinese
have not officially threatened a boycott. The ceremony will be held
on Dec. 10.
   Guisheng Wang, of the Chinese embassy in Oslo, refused to
comment on the threat reported on Wednesday by Norwegian
television. ``It is well known that we protested earlier,'' he said.
   The Chinese Foreign Ministry complained on Oct. 7 that the award
supported the Dalai Lama's efforts to split China and hurt the
feelings of the Chinese people.
   Foreign Minister Kjell Magne Bondevik observed, ``There are
established practices about participating in the awards ceremony
and we have no plans of changing them.''
</TEXT>
