<DOCNO> AP891019-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 2131EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-RoadSafety     10-19 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Road Safety,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transportation Official Said No Hint of Danger to Structures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Engineers delayed strengthening the
32-year-old Oakland freeway that collapsed in this week's
earthquake because they believed it would survive a major quake,
the state transportation chief said Thursday.
   ``We didn't know 10 years ago this was subject to this type of
earthquake damage. We did not know there was any possibility it
would collapse,'' Transportation Director Robert Best said.
   Best said he was unaware of a private engineer's report in 1975
that the collapsed Interstate 880 viaduct had an outdated design
that made it vulnerable to such quakes.
   ``I've been assured there were no experts, no studies, no data
that suggested in any way that it would fall,'' Best said.
   State inspection reports for the collapsed section show a
history of minor problems over the years, including hair-line
cracks, flaking concrete, a cracked girder and sagging deck. Some
problems were corrected and others weren't.
   ``(But) there was no problem of structural failure at all,''
Best said of the reports.
   A 1\-mile-long stretch of the two-tiered Nimitz Freeway
collapsed during Tuesday's earthquake. An upper section of the San
Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge also collapsed.
   Gov. George Deukmejian has called for an immediate investigation
of I-880's collapse. The governor said the freeway should have been
built to survive the quake, which registered 6.9 on the Richter
scale of ground motion.
   A blue-ribbon commission of bridge engineers is being set up to
determine why the structure collapsed and what steps can be taken
to prevent such tragedies in the future, Best said.
   J. David Rogers, a Pleasant Hill engineer, said he determined in
1975 that the structure wouldn't survive a major earthquake. And he
said the information was presented to state transportation
officials at that time.
   Best said it's ``irresponsible'' to suggest the state knew the
structure would collapse. He said it's possible there were
``unusual subsurface conditions that we didn't know about'' which
could have contributed to the collapse. The highway was built on
fill soils.
   The failed structure had undergone only the first phase of a
three-step program to reinforce the roadway, Best said. Engineers
felt I-880 would be at less risk than other highways because ``it
was the least likely to fail.''
   The retrofitting project on I-880 began in 1977 and was the
first road improvement since the highway was designed in 1954 and
constructed in 1957.
   But phase two of the program for I-880 and other roadways with
double-column supports was deferred as officials focused on
strengthening roads with single-column supports, which they
believed were more vulnerable, Best said.
   The first phase involved strengthening the roadway; the second
began on single-column supports two years ago and involves
strengthening existing columns.
   Authorities deferred the I-880 retrofitting pending outcome of a
still-unfinished engineering study to determine the best sort of
repairs. The freeway was last inspected in April.
   Officials had no estimate of when that study might be completed.
They emphasized that I-880 was not neglected or given too low a
priority in the retrofitting project.
   Asked whether the I-880 section had been considered safe from
earthquake damage, Transportation Department chief engineer Bill
Schaefer said, ``There's no such thing as an earthquake-proof
structure, certainly.'' But he added he was ``shocked'' by the
section's collapse.
   ``We thought it would withstand the maximum credible earthquake
we could have in this area, anything that would happen in this
area,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
