<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-NBCAffiliates     10-19 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-NBC Affiliates,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Affiliates Angry, Then Understanding</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake-Television</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some NBC affiliates complained that NBC News
didn't quickly air coverage of the San Francisco earthquake, but
were understanding when the delay was explained, an NBC official
said Thursday.
   The complaints, whose number wasn't tallied, were made to NBC
Television Network President Pier Mapes, NBC News executive news
director Don Browne, and NBC News President Michael Gartner, said
Peggy Hubble, an NBC News spokeswoman.
   NBC was the last of the networks to report Tuesday's earthquake
and to broadcast pictures from the scene. Once it began full
coverage after 9 p.m. EDT that day, NBC stayed on the air with
non-stop coverage that included a five-hour ``Today'' edition
before it signed off at noon Wednesday.
   In an interview Wednesday, Gartner blamed NBC's delay on the
quake itself. He said KRON-TV, NBC's San Francisco affiliate, had
been knocked off the air by the earthquake and was temporarily
unable to help NBC transmit its reports.
   ``We heard from a good number of affiliates, and I would say
they were as unhappy as we were that we weren't on sooner,'' Hubble
said Thursday when asked whether NBC affiliates had complained
about NBC's coverage.
   However, she added, the complaining station executives proved
understanding when told of the situation at KRON-TV. They also
expressed pleasure at NBC's subsequent non-stop quake coverage,
``even though we were late out of the box,'' she said.
</TEXT>
