<FIRST>u w AM-SFQuake-Congress 1stLd-Writethru   10-19 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0826,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Plans To Vote On Aid To Earthquake Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, bgng: Another Democrat xxx to remove reference
to Fazio chairing subcommittee on FEMA. He is not on that subcommittee.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake-Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Tom Foley on Thursday estimated
at least $2.5 billion in federal funds would be needed for
California earthquake damage and said the House would vote next
week to provide it, deficit or no deficit.
   The money will be included in the continuing resolution to be
voted on Tuesday. This is a stopgap money bill needed to keep the
government operating until all the appropriations bills are
approved.
   ``If the deficit has to go up, the deficit will have to rise,''
said Foley, comparing the earthquake to a family emergency. ``If a
family has a tragedy, it may not be in the budget,'' but needs have
to be met, he said.
   Foley said that the federal government is obligated by law to
assist in emergencies such as the earthquake and Hurricane Hugo. He
said the leadership of the House will not make the people of
California, the Carolinas and Virgin Islands suffer because of a
tight federal budget.
   Meanwhile, Former House Speaker Thomas ``Tip'' O'Neill defended
President Bush's response to the earthquake, even though the
president did not visit the scene immediately.
   Foley's comments came after talking to members of the California
delegation who went home to survey the damage. During a telephone
conference call, Rep. Barbara Boxer, a Democrat from San Francisco,
told Foley the scene was ``a heart-breaker'' that would require
funds ``in the billions.''
   Democrat Don Edwards of San Jose, who had just returned to
Washington said ``it's hard to imagine from pictures how bad it
is.''
   Another Democrat, Vic Fazio of Sacramento said Congress has
asked the Office of Management and Budget to estimate by 9 a.m.
Monday how much money will be needed.
   He said he already sees a need for at least $800 million more
for highways and bridges than has been budgeted. He said
legislation would have to be passed to remove certain restrictions
on the amount a single state can get in federal funds for highway
work.
   He also said the Small Business Administration ``is almost out
of money'' and needs at least another $1 billion for California.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., said earlier in the day that he
expected the Senate to act next week as well.
   Speaking at a news conference in Dayton, Ohio, O'Neill said: ``I
don't think it's right to criticize the president of the United
States for local disasters because he doesn't appear on the scene.
They do get the apparatus in motion.''
   ``I think he's responded very quickly to the problems out
there,'' O'Neill said.
</TEXT>
