<FIRST>r i AM-China-Pandas     10-19 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Pandas,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Given Death Sentences for Killing Pandas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Sichuan farmers were sentenced to death and
two others were given life imprisonment for selling panda skins,
the official Xinhua News Agency said Friday.
   An intermediate court in the southwest China province gave Liang
Yongzheng the death sentence for selling seven panda skins for
300,000 yuan, or $81,000. The other condemned man, He Guanghai,
made 30,000 yuan, or $8,100, by selling skins, the agency said.
   It said two of Liang's seven accomplices received life in prison.
   The men were from Pingwu County, a major habitat of the giant
panda. The animal is native to China and only about 1,000 still
survive in the wilds of Sichuan and neighboring Tibet.
   The Chinese government has forbidden hunting of the endangered
species, and courts in Sichuan have repeatedly called for harsh
punishments of people caught killing or selling the animals.
   Several offenders have been given life in prison, although the
death sentence is rare for panda poaching.
   The convicted have the right to appeal, but Chinese courts
rarely accept appeals and executions, with a bullet to the back of
the head, are usually carried out within days of sentencing.
</TEXT>
