<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Homeland     10-19 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Homeland,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>143 Convicted in Coup Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Thursday convicted 143
men of treason for their role in a failed coup last year against
the leader of the Bophuthatswana tribal homeland.
   M.W. Friedman, a judge in the homeland's Supreme Court in
Mmabatho, said he would begin sentencing on Friday for the men,
most of them soldiers.
   The soldiers seized homeland leader Lucas Mangope on Feb. 10,
1988, and held him hostage for several hours before the South
African military rescued him and returned Mangope to power.
   Bophuthatswana is made up of seven separate patches of land in
north-central South Africa and is one of four nominally independent
black homelands. South Africa is the only nation that recognizes
them as independent.
   The homeland has nearly 2 million people and has been ruled by
Mangope since it was declared independent in 1977.
