<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     10-19 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Agency Protests Israeli Raids on Food Center, Offices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. agency that coordinates aid for
Palestinian refugees said Thursday the Israeli army raided its main
food distribution center and three other offices in the occupied
lands and roughed up two staff workers.
   The U.N. Relief and Works Agency said in a statement issued at
its headquarters in Vienna, Austria, that protests were filed with
the Israeli mission to the United Nations in Vienna and with
Israeli military officials in the territories.
   In Wednesday's raids, the soldiers detained UNRWA workers and
confiscated documents at the food distribution center in the Gaza's
Deir El-Balah camp and at service offices in the West Bank refugee
camps of Dheishe, Fawwar and Jalazoun.
   The UNRWA statement said they ``roughed up and detained'' two
international staff members, Christian Saunders of Britain and
Declan Greenway of Ireland, and detained four Arab workers. All now
are free.
   ``UNRWA has discussed with Israeli authorities the serious
breaches of privileges and immunities which the agency enjoys as an
international body providing humanitarian services,'' it said.
   Asked about the case, State Department spokeswoman Margaret
Tutwiler said in Washington, ``We have called on all parties to
exercise maximum restraint to avoid the kinds of confrontations
described in these reports.
   ``As a general matter, we regret any actions that interfere with
the UNRWA's important humanitarian operations in providing
education, medical and relief services to Palestinian refugees.''
   An officer with the military government in the occupied lands
said the troops were investigating reports ``some employees of
UNRWA are either participating in the uprising themselves or aiding
activities of the uprising.''
   The officer, who insisted on anonymity, said he had not seen the
UNRWA complaint and had no comment.
   Claire Grimes, UNRWA spokeswoman in Jerusalem, said, ``We have
no knowledge of any illegal activities inside our installations.
According to staff rules and regulations, political activities are
not permissible.''
   Israel captured the West Bank and Gaza Strip from Jordan and
Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war. The lands have been torn by a
Palestinian revolt since December 1987. They are home to 1.7
million Palestinians, 820,000 of them refugees who qualify for
assistance from the U.N. agency.
   On Thursday, a 12-year-old boy from the Deir El-Balah camp was
hit in the head with rubber-coated metal pellets fired by the army
as a riot control measure.
   Arab hospital officials said the boy, Abdullah Ishmael Abu
El-Aram, was evacuated ``in extremely critical condition'' to Tel
Hashomer Hospital near Tel Aviv.
   Five other Palestinians were shot and wounded Thursday in
stone-throwing clashes with troops, including three with head
wounds from rubber-coated metal pellets or rubber bullets.
   Since the uprising began, 596 Palestinians have been killed by
Israeli soldiers or civilians. Forty Israelis also have died. An
additional 130 Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs, most
on suspicion of collaborating.
</TEXT>
