<FIRST>u w AM-SFQuake-Bush 3ndLd-Writethru a0809 10-19 0889</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Bush, 3nd Ld-Writethru, a0809,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush to Fly to California; Foley Pledges More Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 5: ``Bush announced,'' to note new lower death estimates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Thursday he wanted ``to
take a look and to provide encouragement'' during a tour of
earthquake-shattered Northern California, while House Speaker
Thomas S. Foley pledged up to $2.5 billion in disaster funds from
Congress.
   Foley said that he did not know where all the money would be
found, but promised that the House would provide it in a vote next
week.
   ``If the deficit has to go up, the deficit will have to rise,''
Foley said, comparing the quake to a family emergency. ``If a
family has a tragedy, it may not be in the budget'' but the needs
still have to be met.
   Bush planned to leave Washington before dawn Friday, flying
across country for a five-hour inspection tour of damage sites by
helicopter and car. He planned to make stops in Oakland and Santa
Cruz, two of the most devastated areas.
   Bush announced his trip amid Democratic complaints and
Republican praise over the government's response to Tuesday's
quake, which authorities estimate caused $2 billion in damage.
Initial estimates of more than 250 deaths were proving much too
high, officials said Thursday night without offering new estimates,
and coroners in seven counties reported only 31 bodies recovered.
   The president said he was confident that federal officials were
doing a good job and promised ``we will stay on top of it.''
   After an early-morning flight from Washington, Bush planned to
spend three hours in California on Friday, much of the time in a
helicopter tour.
   ``We'll do as much as we can without disrupting local
activities,'' White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said.
   Bush is to fly to Moffett Naval Air Station near Mountain View
and take a helicopter to Alameda on the east side of the San
Francisco Bay, and then drive to Oakland to view the collapsed
Interstate 880.
   He then is to double back to Alameda for a helicopter hop to
Santa Cruz, where there is extensive damage. Tuesday's quake was
the deadliest since the 1906 temblor that killed 2,500 people in
San Francisco.
   Bush flew to South Carolina on a similar inspection mission
after Hurricane Hugo last month, but the federal government was
accused by some officials there of moving too slowly in providing
disaster relief. In this instance, Bush said California Gov. George
Deukmejian, a Republican, had called ``to express appreciation for
the all-out federal effort.''
   However, the Democratic mayor of San Francisco, Art Agnos, said
he was ``ticked off'' that Vice President Dan Quayle had not met
with him during a tour of quake damage.
   Agnos said Quayle ``flies around in a helicopter, makes a bunch
of television spots. ... I have real questions about what he was
ding here. It may have been just a publicity stunt.''
   Agnos was invited to accompany Bush on Friday, along with the
mayors of Oakland and Alameda.
   In Washington, Quayle said all mayors in the quake area had been
invited to a meeting with him. ``I think it's very unfortunate to
take that kind of a shot at a very difficult time.''
   Fitzwater said Agnos had turned away several administration
approaches.
   Meanwhile, Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams said the Army Corps
of Engineers has begun inspecting federal dams and levees, and, at
the request of the state government, state and private dams. So
far, he said, no damage had been discovered in structures checked
within 50 miles of the quake's epicenter.
   A U-2 reconnaissance plane from Beale Air Force Base flew over
the San Francisco area late Wednesday, and Williams said its photos
might help in the detection of structural problems.
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole said California would be eligible
for federal job-training funds to assist any workers who lost their
jobs because of the quake.
   Bush called Quayle and Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner
to the Oval Office to report on the helicopter tour they took
Wednesday to damage sites.
   ``Our hearts certainly go out to the victims of this disaster,''
Bush said. ``And I will go out there tomorrow to take a look and to
provide encouragement to the people.''
   Skinner, in an appearance on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America''
program, said, ``All federal resources have been marshaled.''
   Quayle was asked on the NBC-TV ``Today'' show if there was
enough money available for the relief effort. He replied, ``We will
put the maximum that we can behind that, working with state and
local levels of government to clean the situation up.''
   The White House said an initial $273 million will be available
for the area from a pool of $1.1 billion that Congress appropriated
after the devastation caused by Hurricane Hugo.
   As for the flap with Agnos, Fitzwater said the mayor was invited
to two meetings up wherever he was and deliver him to the meetings,
and he declined that.''
   He said Bush's chief of staff, John Sununu, had tried to call
Agnos for several days, and ``he declined to talk to us. We regret
very much that the mayor of San Francisco has declined to cooperate
with us in this matte in making sure there is adequate federal
support for the disaster in his city.''
</TEXT>
