<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Computer 2ndLd-Writethru a0736 10-19 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Computer, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0736,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Service Companies Offers Info for Quake Victims, Relatives</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 1 graf to clarify that region isn't isolated. A version
moved on the financial wire.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Computers are giving some worried friends
and relatives around the world their first word about
earthquake-damaged sections of Northern California.
   ``This is sort of like what ham radio operators do, only it's on
a computer,'' said Rich Baker, editorial services manager of
CompuServe. ``It has been instrumental in giving concerned people
the straight scoop. It's getting a lot of the information coming
out of California straight in an accurate and timely manner _ often
more quickly than the news media can.''
   The Columbus-based computer information service, with 550,000
individual and 1,800 corporate customers worldwide, created an
``earthquake forum'' where people could leave messages and
information about 5 p.m. Wednesday. By 11 a.m. Thursday, more than
430 messages _ many seeking information _ had been filed.
   Prodigy, a White Plains, N.Y.-based venture of IBM and Sears,
Roebuck &amp; Co., had a system going less than four hours after
Tuesday's quake, said Brian Ek, communications manager. By Thursday
afternoon, 1,530 messages were posted.
   It also put a psychologist on line Wednesday night ``to help
these people deal with the trauma. We had one person who know some
of the people involved in the Nimitz highway situation who was
pretty distraught,'' Ek said.
   Prodigy has subscribers in more than 100,000 U.S. households.
   Many messages sought information about conditions; others were
personal.
   A New England man trying to find a Burlingame, Calif., couple,
learned in about an hour that they not only had survived but had
become grandparents after the quake _ but that one of their fathers
had died the day before Tuesday's earthquake.
   ``Everyone was in good spirits, given the circumstances,'' a
message said.
   Computer samaritans also acted as messengers for those who
couldn't reach loved ones by phone.
   An Oakland woman reported ``for anybody worrying about their
daughter'' at Mills College in Oakland Hills, students were shaken
but fine. ``Talked to my good friend's daughter there who is a
freshman from Utah and her first time away from home. I told her
`Welcome to California,' as she had never ever experienced an
earthquake, let alone a biggie like the SF quake.''
   A man from Italy sought help finding friends vacationing in San
Francisco, but their whereabouts were not known.
   Word also came from San Carlos that damage there ``was primarily
on the nerves,'' and from Santa Clara that a woman sustained no
damage to her house, though her birdbath was tipped over.
   The system is available only to CompuServe members, who pay
$12.50 an hour to dial into the electronic bulletin board through
their personal computers. It is the first time CompuServe has set
up a forum solely for earthquake-related information, though it has
been pressed into service for other disasters.
   Members exchanged information Jan. 28, 1986, when Challenger
exploded, and when the stock market crashed Oct. 19, 1987.
CompuServe also posted messages in the system last month when
Hurricane Hugo swept into the Carolinas.
   The year-old Prodigy charges subscribers a flat $9.95 a month.
</TEXT>
