<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Typhoon     10-19 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Typhoon,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Typhoon Elsie Leaves Two Dead in Philippines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typhoon Elsie moved into the South
China Sea on Friday after battering the northern Philippines and
leaving at least two dead and thousands fleeing to relief centers,
officials said.
   In a final typhoon bulletin at 4 a.m., the Manila weather bureau
said Elsie was 155 miles west-northwest of the mountain resort of
Baguio in Benguet province, about 240 miles northwest of Manila.
   Forecaster Juliet Dagupa said Elsie, which had 127 mph winds
when it blew ashore Thursday, weakened to 103 mph and was moving
west at 14 mph.
   Reports reaching the Red Cross headquarters in the capital said
one person died in La Union's provincial capital of San Fernando
when an acacia tree fell on him. Another died in a landslide in
Baguio, officials added.
   The military's Office of Civil Defense said over 17,000 people
were ``affected,'' meaning they were temporarily sheltered in
schoolhouses and other government centers or their houses were
either damaged or destroyed.
   The office said Elsie's winds sank two tugboats and caused a
British-registered commercial vessel to slam into port at La
Union's Poro Point. No reports of casualties came from the vessels,
officials added.
   Officials said many northern provinces were without electricity
because of toppled power lines. Fallen trees rendered dozens of
roads impassable.
   Manila radio station DZXL said its affiliate in Bayombong,
capital of Nueva Vizcaya province, 130 miles north, was knocked off
the air by a power failure.
   Elsie roared ashore Thursday in Aurora province and weakened to
116 mph as it slammed into the Sierra Mountain range.
   U.S. Air Force officials said some jets were moved to air bases
in Japan and South Korea until the storm passed.
</TEXT>
