<DOCNO> AP891019-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 2242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-NYCPolitics 1stLd-Writethru a0772 10-19 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NYC Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0772,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dinkins Pelted On His Stroll To The Mayoralty</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Dinkins' troubles ...,' ADDS 4 grafs to UPDATE
with comments by Dinkins worker accused of anti-semitism, Dinkins response.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pounded by a sudden hail of ethics accusations,
mayoral candidate David Dinkins struggled to regain his footing
Thursday in his heretofore stately stroll toward the election.
   Dinkins, the Democratic nominee, lashed at Republican Rudolph W.
Giuliani, accusing him of ``gutter politics,'' bullying and slander
and threatening to respond with negative attacks of his own.
   The uncharacteristic vitriol underlined Dinkins' dismay over a
week of unrelenting criticism by Giuliani _ who has been trailing
badly in polls in the strongly Democratic city _ much of it
prompted by news reports on Dinkins' handling of a stock sale and a
conflict of interest issue.
   Dinkins' troubles were compounded Thursday, first by Mayor
Edward I. Koch's call for him to release a city investigation of
his failure to file tax returns during 1969-72, then by charges he
ducked taxes more recently by understating the value of stock he
sold to his son, and finally by a racist remark by a black activist
who had worked for his campaign.
   Dinkins, who would be the city's first black mayor, has called
his 1969-72 failure to file tax returns an oversight that he
corrected in 1973.
   Giuliani, a former federal prosecutor, accused Dinkins of
intentionally breaking the city ethics law _ punishable, Giuliani
noted, by up to a year in jail.
   At issue, chiefly, was Dinkins' investment in Inner City
Broadcasting, a privately held, highly successful media company
formed in 1972 by his political mentor, former Manhattan Borough
President Percy Sutton.
   In 1986 Dinkins, himself newly elected as Manhattan borough
president, sold his 558 shares of Inner City to his son, David Jr.,
for $58,000, payable with 8 percent annual interest in 1991. He did
not reveal the transaction on financial disclosure forms; aides say
it was an ``installment sales contract'' and thus did not have to
be listed as a gift or receivable note.
   New York Newsday reported Thursday that Dinkins had far
underestimated the stock's value, which has no public market price
because it is not publicly traded.
   Newsday quoted Inner City's general counsel as saying the stock
in 1986 was worth, conservatively, $4,292 per share, or more than
$2 million for Dinkins' shares. Newsday quoted a tax expert as
saying a $58,000 sale price for stock worth much more represented
``a huge gift.''
   Dinkins spokesman David Fishlow maintained that the $58,000
valuation was proper: ``He made appropriate inquiries and valued it
fairly.''
   Fishlow said he did not know with whom Dinkins spoke or by what
formula he valued the stock. The official quoted in Newsday said he
estimated Inner City's worth by a common formula _ 10 times the
company's annual revenues.
   Giuliani also attacked Dinkins' involvement as a city official
in business between Inner City and the city government, even though
the Board of Ethics had warned against it.
   Dinkins had requested the ethics ruling and cited it when he
abstained from a 1987 vote in the Board of Estimate, which handles
contracts and zoning, on a matter involving Inner City. But he
conceded Wednesday that aides sitting in for him on the board voted
in 1987 for a zoning change for Inner City's new office and this
year for a transfer of its cable franchise.
   In another development, Robert C. ``Sonny'' Carson, a black
activist who helped organize a voter drive for Dinkins, scoffed
Thursday at charges that he was an anti-Semite.
   ``I'm anti-white. I don't limit my antis to just being one
little group of people, and I think you would insult me if you
tried to do that,'' Carson said when asked about the accusation
made last week by B'nai B'rith's Anti-Defamation League.
   Carson insisted he had not been hired by Dinkins' campaign and
personally received no money. The campaign has said it paid Carson
$9,800 to organize the drive for the Sept. 12 Democratic primary.
   Carson's comments prompted a terse statement from Dinkins:
``Sonny Carson's comments represent the kind of bigotry and
intolerance I utterly reject and have fought against my whole life.
Had such comments come to my attention, he would never have played
any role in my campaign.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
