<DOCNO> AP891019-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 2217EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-BridgeSurvivors     10-19 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Bridge Survivors,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pair Survives Collapse of Bay Bridge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At first, Bruce Stephan thought all four
tires on his car had gone flat, but when the San Francisco-Oakland
Bay Bridge started bouncing and weaving, he realized it was an
earthquake. Then the bridge gave way and he was plunging toward the
San Francisco Bay.
   ``The ground just opened up and the car started going down,''
Stephan said Thursday. ``All I could think is, `I'm going through
the bridge and into the Bay.' ... I knew it was death. I didn't
think there was anything that could stop us.''
   When it was over, Stephan's gray Mazda stopped only inches shy
of plunging into the bay. He was looking at water, his car wedged
in the gap between the collapsed upper deck and split-open lower
deck.
   In a fluke Stephan and his passenger, Janice Freiburger, cannot
explain, they were in the only vehicle on the falling section of
bridge.
   Stephan, 33, of San Francisco, was treated for minor bruises and
released. Freiburger, 41, of Larkspur, was hospitalized with a
cracked sternum, a cracked collar bone and a crack in her spine.
Doctors predict that she will be released early next week.
   ``When I look at it, I can't imagine that neither of us were
(more seriously) hurt,'' Freiburger said from her room at Pacific
Presbyterian Hospital. ``I have injuries, but I'm just fine.''
   Stephan and Freiburger, co-workers at a San Francisco real
estate company, were returning from a project in the East Bay when
they were caught on the bridge.
   ``It all happened in just split seconds,'' Freiburger recalled.
``First there was a moment of utter silence and then boom, an
explosion-type of noise. It all opened up. We went traveling down
like a roller coaster ride, just that fast.''
   ``I closed my eyes real tight and made my mind blank,'' said
Stephan. ``You know how you're supposed to have all those
flashbacks and your whole life flashes before your eyes? That
didn't happen. ... I told Janice, `We're going to die,' and she
said, `No, we're not. Hold on.'''
   After the car stopped, Stephan clambered out the window and onto
the hood of the car before hoisting himself up onto the surface of
the bridge's lower deck. He said he didn't look down as he and a
stranger helped pull Freiburger from the hood to the roadway.
   The pair walked more than a mile to Treasure Island, where they
were examined at a clinic before being taken by ambulance to San
Francisco General Hospital.
   Stephan said he is trying to come to grips with his good fortune.
   ``It seems like it should be more profound. It was kind of a
brush with death, but I don't feel that much different,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
