<FIRST>r a AM-MineBombings     10-19 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mine Bombings,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine Miners Arrested in Bombing of Coal Mine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILBURN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine United Mine Workers members were
arrested Thursday in connection with a series of bombings at a coal
mine that has been the target of a union strike for five years.
   U.S. Attorney Michael Carey said the arrests culminated an
investigation by a federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
task force looking into mine bombings.
   Arrested for conspiracy to use explosives at Milburn Colliery
were Russell Lee Delung of Dothan; Jesse Harvey, Raymon Thomas and
Julian Wriston of Scarbro; Alan Ray Sharp and Michael Woodson of
Oak Hill; Darrell Ray Sharp of Minden; and Billie Lafferty of Mount
Hope.
   Each faces five years in prison and $250,000 in fines if
convicted, U.S. Attorney Michael Carey said Thursday.
   Larry Massey of Burnwell was charged with destroying property
involved in interstate commerce, Carey said. He faces 10 years in
prison and $250,000 in fines, Carey said.
   All nine were arraigned before U.S. Magistrate Charles
Cunningham in Bluefield and are free on bond.
   The mine, which has been operated by Mountain Minerals Inc.
since last May, has been the target of a strike by about 45 miners
from UMW Local 5948 since Oct. 8, 1984. The walkout is not
connected to the union's larger strike against Pittston Coal Group,
which began last April.
   Last June, a bomb was set off at a bridge entrance to the mine,
and a July fire resulted in about $400,000 damage, Carey said.
   Last month, a bomb caused about $35,000 damage to a mine
ventilation system. Also last month, authorities disarmed a
57-pound time bomb set to explode, Carey said.
   Neither the arrested miners nor local union leaders could be
reached for comment Thursday night.
   UMW national spokesman Joe Corcoran said the union was unaware
of any evidence implicating the nine.
   ``In any strike situation, there are many allegations and
accusations that turn out not to be true,'' he said.
</TEXT>
