<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay-Crash     10-19 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay-Crash,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>7 Dead, 10 Injured in Crash; President's Guards Believed Among Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A single-engine plane crashed into a
building while trying to land Thursday at an airport in eastern
Paraguay, killing seven people and injuring 10 others, government
radio said.
   Believed to be among the dead in the crash outside City of the
East, formerly Stroessner City, were some members of the security
group guarding President Gen. Andres Rodriguez, according to
government radio.
   The security group was in City of the East, 235 miles east of
the capital Asuncion, in advance of a visit planned Friday by
Rodriguez, who came to power in February in a coup that deposed
former dictator Alfredo Stroessner.
   The government said late Thursday that the visit by Rodriguez
had been suspended because of the accident.
   The pilot and co-pilot, members of the Paraguayan Air Force,
died in the crash of the Brazilian-made Tucano, the station
reported, as did three policemen and two airport personnel. No
cause of the crash was given.
   It was not clear whether the other fatalities were aboard the
plane, or were in the airport building. The injured were
transported to nearby hospitals, the report said, but their
conditions and identities were not immediately available.
   The airport belongs to the government agency constructing Itaipu
Dam on the Parana River, one of the largest hydroelectric projects
in the world.
   City of the East is the closest Paraguayan municipality to the
dam.
</TEXT>
