<HEAD>Man Pleads Innocent in Deaths of Six Firefighters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 18-year-old man pleaded innocent to
second-degree murder charges Thursday in the fiery deaths of six
Kansas City firefighters last year.
   Jackson County Circuit Court Judge Lee E. Wells refused to lower
a $1.5 million bond set for Bryan E. Sheppard, but he agreed to
hold a bond hearing soon to discuss the amount.
   Sheppard was charged Sept. 25 with six counts of second-degree
murder and one count of knowingly burning. Prosecutors contend he
set fire to construction trailers filled with explosives before
dawn the morning of Nov. 29. Six firefighters died as they fought
the blaze.
   His lawyer, John P. O'Connor, said the defense would revolve
around Sheppard's contention that he was home that morning.
   Sheppard is the only person charged in the crime, but
authorities have said they expect to make more arrests.
