<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru a0715 10-19 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0715,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Personal Pilot of Medellin Cartel Chief Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with other arrests, judges' strike
to end. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said they arrested the personal
pilot of Colombia's alleged cocaine godfather Thursday and will
hold him for extradition to the United States.
   The pilot, Jorge de la Cuesta Marquez, is wanted in Florida on
charges of conspiracy to distribute cocaine, national police Col.
Oscar Pelaez Carmona said in a news release. He identified De la
Cuesta as the pilot of Pablo Escobar, leader of the Medellin
cocaine cartel.
   Pelaez would say only that De la Cuesta was arrested in an
apartment in northern Bogota.
   With De la Cuesta's arrest, five Colombians await extradition to
the United States. Colombia earlier extradited four others.
   None is on the U.S. Justice Department's list of the 12 most
wanted drug suspects in Colombia.
   An army official said Thursday the army detained Dairo Chica, a
well-known Colombian bullfighter, as a low-level drug trafficker in
a raid on a farm outside of Medellin.
   The official, speaking to The Associated Press on condition of
anonymity, said Chica was among four people captured.
   Press reports said Chica was wanted for extradition to the
United States on drug-trafficking charges, but the official could
not confirm this.
   In Mexico City, authorities said they captured the nephews of
two Colombian drug kingpins and broke up a ring that flew cocaine
into Mexico via the Yucatan Peninsula and shipped it by boat to
Florida.
   Federal police commander Fausto Valverde, head of Mexico's
narcotics interdiction forces, said the two _ identified as Luis
Alfredo Aguilar Castro, a nephew of Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha, and
Ricardo Isunza Ochoa, a nephew of Fabio Ochoa _ were seized with
eight other men Sunday at a clandestine airstrip in the Yucatan.
   President Virgilio Barco resumed extraditions on Aug. 18
following the slayings of a leading presidential candidate, a
federal judge, and a police colonel by drug barons.
   Another federal judge was killed by a gunman in Medellin on
Tuesday, three days after three Colombians were extradited.
   A group calling itself the Extraditables said in a telephone
call to a Medellin radio station the murder was in revenge for the
extraditions carried out so far.
   Barco says he will not back down in his war on drug traffickers.
The traffickers replied they prefer a grave in Colombia to a jail
cell in the United States. They killed a governor, bombed two
newspapers, killed eight news media employees and set off 164
explosions in an effort to force the government to call off
extraditions.
   The explosions at banks, shopping areas, hotels, schools and
government offices have killed 16 people.
   The latest occurred Wednesday in Bogota's main plaza when a hand
grenade exploded, apparently accidentally, and killed the man
carrying it.
   The man was only steps from the building of the national
congress.
   About 17,000 Colombian judges and judicial employees, meanwhile,
said they were ending a 72-hour strike Thursday night and will
return to work Friday despite the government's inability to address
their security concerns.
   Consuelo Herrera, a board member of the court workers' union,
said Justice Minister Roberto Salazar Manrique told the board
Tuesday the government did not have the resources to increase
protection for judges threatened by drug traffickers.
   ``He told us that the U.S. aid for us had not arrived and that
the government could do nothing for us without it,'' Ms. Herrera
told the AP by telephone.
   In September, the Bush administration pledged $19 million in
U.S. aid to protect Colombia's judges.
   The walkout has paralyzed most courts here since Tuesday.
   Ms. Herrera said judges and court workers were returning to work
with the certainty more of them will be murdered.
   ``We can't shut down the court system for very long because it
is just too important,'' she said. ``But the next time one of us is
assassinated _ and it is sure to happen _ we will go on strike
again.''
</TEXT>
