<FIRST>r a AM-BollesGrandJury     10-19 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bolles Grand Jury,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Reopens Probe Into Reporter's Death, Sources Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state grand jury has begun a new investigation
into the 1976 car-bomb slaying of investigative reporter Don
Bolles, sources said Thursday.
   The grand jury has already issued subpoenas for several
witnesses, including people in California or Colorado, said sources
familiar with the investigation who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Although the man who planted the remote-control bomb that killed
the Arizona Republic reporter was found guilty and imprisoned, no
mastermind has ever been convicted.
   Attorney General Bob Corbin, who has come under fire for his
handling of the Bolles case, declined to comment on any grand jury
matter, but confirmed that his office had been working on the
Bolles case for more than a year.
   Witnesses subpoenaed in California or Colorado may be entitled
to a court hearing before any Arizona subpoenas are honored,
sources said.
   The sources demanded anonymity because they feared prosecution
under an Arizona law making it a crime to dislose grand jury
matters.
   Bolles clung to life for 11 days after the bomb went off,
repeatedly saying the word ``Emprise,'' an apparent reference to a
company later called Delaware North that runs dog and horse racing
tracks.
   Racing dog owner John Adamson was convicted of murder for
planting the bomb that killed Bolles.
   Adamson, testifying at the trial of Max Dunlap of Phoenix and
James Robison of Chandler, said Dunlap had asked him to kill Bolles
because of the reporter's articles about a wealthy benefactor of
Dunlap unrelated to the company.
   Dunlap and Robison were convicted and sentenced to death, but
the verdicts were overturned on appeal. Attempts to try them again
were put on hold when Adamson refused to testify again unless he
got a better deal from prosecutors.
   Corbin's office then withdrew the deal under which Adamson had
been sentenced to 48 years in prison in exchange for his earlier
testimony, and prosecuted him again.
   He was convicted and sentenced to death, but a federal appeals
court in San Francisco threw out the sentence _ and Arizona's death
penalty in general _ as unconstitutional. That ruling has been
appealed to the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Corbin, a Republican who is up for re-election next year, has
come under increasing pressure over the Bolles case. His only
announced opponent for the GOP nomination, Tucson attorney David
Eisenstein, has made the case a centerpiece of his campaign.
   Eisenstein on Thursday questioned the timing of the grand jury
leak.
   ``I find it very interesting that there is a grand jury working
on it just a month after I pointed out that he hadn't done anything
about it for 11 years,'' Eisenstein said. ``I'm curious, but at the
same time I'm encouraged.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891019-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 2314EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Highway 2ndLd-Writethru a0859 10-19 0989</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Highway, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0859,1016</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spray Paint Points Way to Carnage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 7th graf pvs, `Gov. George ..., to UPDATE
with Oakland mayor confronted on television; pick up 8th graf, `Across
from ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The reek of gasoline dripping from
flattened cars and trucks mingled Thursday with the aroma from
eucalyptus trees splintered by tons of concrete crashing to the
streets below.
   On the railing of the flattened upper deck of Interstate 880,
markers of flourescent green, pink and orange spray paint point the
way to crushed cars and shattered bodies.
   The code is crisp and clear: The letters 1DOA signified a body,
2MT a pair of empty cars, a circle and arrow with the number 43
showed a car 43 feet away.
   Here and there, blood spatters the highway's underside.
   Two days ago, 3-foot-thick concrete supports turned to dust,
2-inch steel reinforcing bars bent like pipecleaners, and chunks of
freeway cascaded like runaway boulders when an earthquake collapsed
a mile-long section of I-880, the Nimitz Freeway.
   Early estimates put the number of dead at 250 people, but by
Thursday, officials said they expected the total would be lower _
possibly much lower.
   Gov. George Deukmejian said he would likely appoint a board to
look into the failure of the freeway, which was partially
reinforced in 1977 to make it less prone to damage from earthquakes.
   During a live broadcast of the CBS television show ``48 Hours''
on Thursday, an angry parent who believes his son may be buried in
the Cypress rubble confronted Oakland Mayor Lionel Wilson.
   ``Mayor, did you know that you are directly responsible for this
here mess, this disaster?'' asked Daniel Rubi of San Francisco.
Rubi said he had been turned away on Wednesday when he asked to
climb the freeway structure and search for his son, Juan.
   The mayor replied, ``I'm sorry, I can't answer that question.''
   Police took Rubi from the scene in a squad car. Oakland jail
officials reported he was not arrested.
   Across from the rubble, just outside the Pacific Pipe Co., a
salesman who would identify himself only as Dennis stood on the
sidewalk Thursday, still shaken by what he had seen.
   ``It just was one single POW!'' Dennis said. ``The concrete made
so much dust you couldn't see anything.
   ``After you got out here it was so quiet, all you could hear was
people screaming. Anybody who could move was getting out. We got
some ropes. The thought everyone had was that this was the way it
was everywhere. We didn't know how long it would be before help
came.''
   One who came to help was David Horn, a firefighter from
neighboring Berkeley.
   ``It was a mess,'' said Horn, who returned Thursday to see how
the scene appeared in daylight. ``It looks worse to me today. You
always look at the dangers, but they don't affect you so much in an
emergency.
   ``There was cars this tall,'' he said, holding his hand level
below his knee, ``and arms sticking out of them.
   ``At first, I though we should be a lot more frantic, but then I
realized there was no way life could be supported in there.
   ``But we never gave up hope,'' he added. ``It's been proven some
people could survive. Some places might not support an adult, but
would support a child.''
   Chainsaws roared and hammers pounded Thursday as carpenters and
ironworkers used 20-30-foot lengths of 12-inch timbers and 16-inch
pipe to shore up the bottom deck of the highway.
   Others on the top deck used heavy machines called concrete
nibblers to break holes to reach each crushed vehicle. The concrete
railing of the lower deck was being punched out by a huge backhoe
fitted with a steel ram to allow rescuers inside.
   Black soot marked where gasoline had caught fire and burned
within the wreckage, out of reach of help.
   On the sidewalk below, hundreds of expensive bottles of wine and
champagne lay unbroken where they had been thrown when a rental
truck was pitched from the overpass.
   Blankets were heaped on the sidewalk in front of a warehouse
where injured people had been comforted.
   Construction worker Brad Elfring, wearing an orange safety vest
and a hardhat, got up from a cot in a loading bay where he had
napped after working straight through from Tuesday, when he came in
from Sacramento.
   ``You sleep a few hours and go back to work,'' he said. ``You
try to ignore it (the carnage around him) and just do your job.''
   A burly carpenter who refused to give his name said he had seen
incredible bravery by his fellow carpenters and ironworkers.
   ``That whole damn structure was shaking when a cat (caterpillar
tractor) went by and guys were in there shoring up under there,''
he said. ``I saw people crawling in there in places where they
weren't sure a branch was holding them up, running torches in
places they weren't sure there was gas because they had to.
   ``Four carpenters worked 'til 2 this morning and went to their
regular jobs at 7 and they'll be back tonight,'' he said. ``We're
here just because we believe in it.''
   Oakland Police Sgt. Bob Crawford said he thought the death toll
would ultimately be far less than the 250 first estimated. The
earthquake hit while many people were already home in front of
televisions or across the bay at Candlestick Park for the third
game of the World Series between the Oakland A's and the San
Francisco Giants.
   ``Normally at 5 o'clock on a Tuesday afternoon the traffic in
this area would be bumper to bumper,'' Crawford said. ``We thought
at first it might be 200 or 300 (dead).
   ``But it was World Series day and the traffic was light. We
might get lucky on this one because of the World Series.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
