<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1316EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv20   10-19 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 20,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Friday, Oct. 20</HEAD>
<HEAD>Horatio Alger Was Right</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Those whose youthful ambitions were nourished by
Horatio Alger might not find much new in this story, but a few
adult cynics might very well be surprised.
   It really is true that long hours, hard work and good service
are keys to entrepreneurial success. You are assured of this by a
detailed, three-year study of nearly 3,000 business owners and
companies.
   The study takes its place in a long list of similar works, all
aimed at understanding American entrepreneurs, considered a
curious, even mysterious breed by scholars, and just common-sense
folks by themselves.
   In earlier analyses, the entrepreneur was found, among other
things, to have who moved to _ rather than being born in _ the area
of success, to have delivered newspapers, been a so-so student and
to have experienced need.
   Whether such findings are sound or have significance is another
matter, but the latest, by the National Federation of Independent
Business and American Express, has the ring of truth.
   It did turn up at least one finding not revealed by the many
earlier studies, that long hours on the job do indeed make a
positive difference, but that extreme hours apparently erode
entrepreneurial effectiveness.
   ``Long, but not excessive hours, make a difference,'' according
to the Federation, which claims membership of more than 570,000
small and independent business in all 50 states.
   ``Small Business'' is a poorly defined category, sometimes used
to include all companies not among the top 1,000 in gross income,
but the Federation's membership ranges all the way down to sole
proprietorships.
   Its research arm found that 80 percent of those who worked
between 60 hours and 69 hours a week remained in business after the
first three years, a period in which many startup companies fail.
   However, the survival rate of those who worked more than 69
hours a week actually dropped to 75 percent, while those who worked
fewer hours fell to 76 percent.
   While the federation didn't say so, fatigue could be a critical
factor in the effectiveness decline, because more than 69 hours is
double that of many wage-earners and translates into 10 hours a day
seven days a week.
   Of the companies studied, more than three-quarters succeeded.
The owner's average age was 35 years, with a working spouse and no
more than five previous jobs. Of these successes, 90 percent said
they would do it again.
   Based on their experiences, it was determined that quality
service is more important than low price, that success is enhanced
by positive attitudes, and that it is important to have had prior
experience with the product involved.
   The importance of service over price was pronounced. Those whose
companies emphasized better service showed an 82 percent success
rate, compared with those who adopted a low-price strategy.
   As expected, the quality of financing played a big role in the
success or failure of the companies involved. Too little capital
shows up in almost every survey of small-business failure, and this
one was no exception.
   What motivated the entrepreneurs? More than three-quarters
agreed that it was to have greater control over their lives,
closely followed by ``using my skills and abilities,'' and
``building something for my family.''
   Less than half agreed with the statement ``earning lots of
money.'' That kind of reward, Mr. Alger might have suggested, is
simply the just recognition of ambitious, hard-working people who
seek to serve.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday, Oct. 20.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891019-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1217EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-APonTV-Crystal Adv20   10-19 0804</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Crystal, Adv 20,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday PMs, Oct. 20, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Billy Crystal Takes New Act to Old Country</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last April, Billy Crystal tries a few jokes on a
small audience. Bomb City.
   Uh-oh, he thinks, I need to see what works, ``but where am I
going to break in? At Catch a Rising Czar? At the Impravda?'' He
thinks this way because he is in the Soviet Union at the time. A
rough place for an American comic to break in a new act.
   But anyone who survives ``Saturday Night Live,'' ``Soap'' and
publicity tours for ``When Harry Met Sally ...'' is clearly of
sturdy stuff. Crystal returns to Mother Russia in August. It
results in a 90-minute show.
   Called ``Billy Crystal _ Midnight Train to Moscow,'' it's
getting five Home Box Office cable showings that start Saturday.
It's a mix of comic fantasy, a bit of jazz and a tracing of roots.
   In addition to teaching one Moscow audience how to do The Wave,
he does a short, but memorable skit as Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev and maverick Soviet politician Boris Yeltsin in a fierce
argument.
   Instead of mimicking their voices himself, he does it with
big-band jazz riffs on old Maynard Ferguson recording, ``Got the
Spirit.''
   ``They went nuts with that because it was so timely,'' said
Crystal, who also in the show plays a jazzman, Lester Hawkins, a
combination of several famous musicians he actually knew as a kid.
   His knowledge of jazz and decision to attempt a comedy show in
the Soviet Union, despite initial worries, may stem from several
factors.
   One of his grandmothers came from the Soviet Union. He also is
the nephew of a man who founded Commodore Records, a label devoted
to Dixieland. His father used to produce jazz concerts.
   As a kid in New York, he learned the rudiments of clarinet from
a jazz great, Pee Wee Russell. He met Billie Holliday when he was
5, grew up around jazz folk, all friends of his father and uncle.
   ``Those musicians made me want to be a performer,'' said
Crystal, now 41. ``The house was always full of them, always
smelled of bourbon and brisket.''
   He achieved his boyhood goal. But when it came time to visit the
land of his relatives, to perform there, he wanted first to case
the place, try a few things there. His first trip left him
discouraged. The reason?
   ``Well, there's no sense of humor there that makes any sense to
me. To my kind of comedy. What I like to do. I'm talking about live
on the stage. How would that work?''
   He kicked ideas back and forth with Paul Flaherty, who
eventually directed his show. Finally, Crystal said, he hit on a
comedy-fantasy concept ``and started really tracing my roots back,
found how deep they went.
   ``And then the show became more than a comedy show.''
   Early in the program, he does a stand-up routine on a Moscow
stage, in front of an audience, many of whom obviously appear to
understand English. But he opens by speaking fluent-sounding
Russian.
   Although he has the ear of a good mimic, he doesn't know the
language, he said.
   ``I had a good coach,'' he explained. But he admitted he found
Russian ``a tough language. There's a lot of coughing and spitting
...''
   Still, he said, ``I wanted to come out speaking Russian, and not
slow and loud the way people do with foreigners. I wanted the
people to know my roots are there.''
   Although his two Soviet trips were for the purpose of a show
that hopes to make people laugh, Crystal found what he saw of the
Soviet Union a little sad, a little unsettling, despite many
reports of change for the better there.
   ``There's a joke in the show that the place is so gray that Ted
Turner should buy it and colorize it,'' he said. ``You feel that
there. There are some beautiful things to see.
   ``But there's an eeriness ... that there's a sadness among the
people. You just feel it, this fog that is around everybody.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television...
   RIVERA AND HEROES _ Geraldo Rivera, the talk show host, has
taken his syndicated show to San Francisco to find heroes of
Tuesday's killer earthquake there. He will interview them Monday on
a show taped for broadcast next Wednesday, a spokeman for the show
says.
   LETTERMAN TOURS OLD HOUSE _ Tonight's ``Late Night With David
Letterman'' on NBC has its sardonic host in Washington where,
guided by Rep. Jack Buechner, R-Mo., he takes a behind-the-scenes
tour of the U.S. Capitol. The tour, taped on Monday, includes a
look at the Congressional Supply Store.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday PMs, Oct. 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891019-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1401EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Arhoolie Adv25   10-19 0991</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Arhoolie, Adv 25,1019</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday AMs, Oct. 25, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Roaming America for Regional Sounds</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELISABETH DUNHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL CERRITO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blues singer Big Joe Williams was
fresh out of jail when he cut his first album for Arhoolie Records
one October day in 1960.
   It was one of the most emotional blues sessions Chris Strachwitz
has ever recorded.
   ``He was just fierce,'' the Arhoolie owner recalled. ``He had
jail on his mind, and everything was going bad. I mean that's the
blues. That's pure blues.''
   For more than three decades, the German-born Strachwitz has
wandered the United States holding scores of impromptu recording
sessions, capturing some of the greatest blues, Cajun and
Mexican-American musicians _ as well as many obscure artists _ for
his Arhoolie Records label.
   ``I don't think these people today with 10 million tracks could
have done a ... thing more than what I did with a (Capps) condenser
microphone,'' Strachwitz said. ``But of course, these were all
acoustic instruments.''
   Record collectors know his Down Home Music store, which shares a
building in El Cerrito, about 20 miles east of San Francisco, with
Arhoolie.
   The place is a record mecca for fans of folk, blues, country and
world music. But unlike the big retailers, tapes and compact discs
still represent the minority of sales. Down Home ships albums
nationwide through detailed mail-order catalogs that feature
reviews _ some good, some bad _ for the records it carries.
   Strachwitz also has produced and co-directed films about music
with director Les Blanc, whose studio is adjacent to Arhoolie, and
he is working on a book about Lydia Mendoza, the famous
Mexican-American singer.
   But Strachwitz doesn't spend much time in the record store. He
bought the building more than 20 years ago with proceeds from rock
band Country Joe and the Fish's hit ``I'm Fixin' to Die Rag,'' to
which he held the publishing rights.
   The one-time high school German teacher and avid record
collector _ he has at least 22,000 records stashed in something
called ``the vault'' _ now faces the task of putting more than a
hundred recordings made over 30 years, plus scores of others he's
released, onto compact disc.
   All for a business he says has never been very profitable.
   ``I never went at it as a business. That's where I'm somewhat
different than most,'' Strachwitz said in an interview. ``I never
thought about merchandising or that this stuff was a product. I
began to realize this country was constituted of all kinds of
people from all kinds of backgrounds.''
   In the late 1950s, he saved money he made teaching and headed
east one summer to Louisiana, Mississippi and Texas. He recorded a
handful of performers, then returned to California and formed a
record label.
   ``I learned to splice 12 songs together, two sides of a record,
roughly 20 minutes a side,'' he said. ``Then I sent that to a guy
who cut an acetate master. From that the plates were made. And then
they started pressing the plates. Then you made the jacket.''
   He found musicians on street corners, bars and fields.
   Artists such as Mississippi Fred McDowell, Big Mama Thornton,
Earl Hooker, Clifton Chenier and Michael Ducet owe at least part of
their status to Strachwitz.
   He found Arhoolie's first artist, Mance Lipscomb, while driving
near Houston. Another, Black Ace, he found by asking locals whether
they knew of any good guitar pickers.
   ``I'd stop on street corners. There'd be guys playing dice and
I'd walk up and ask them, `You guys ever heard of a guy named
Little Brother?' They'd usually just stare at you and say, `What
you want with him?' They figure you're a bill collector or
something.
   ``So this one guy said, `Yeah, he's hangin' around with Black
Ace.' That name was on my list that Paul Oliver, a blues fanatic
friend, had sent me. They said he comes to this tavern right around
the corner every afternoon about 5 o'clock.
   ``That's how I met Black Ace. That was another record.''
   Strachwitz traces his love of blues to his boyhood in Los
Angeles, where he first idolized bluesman Lightning Hopkins after
hearing his single ``Hello Central'' on radio station KFVD.
   In 1959, he visited Hopkins for the first time in Houston, and a
year later he returned, hoping to record Hopkins' music.
   ``At that time I decided I wanted to make a record label because
I wanted to document Lightning Hopkins in the beer joints, the way
he sounded. I was never able to do that. I didn't have the
technical equipment. I didn't have the money.''
   He got his chance later in his career when he took Hopkins into
a recording studio.
   By the time Strachwitz made his first recording, he had teamed
with fellow blues fanatic Mack McCormick, a ``playwrite-cab
driver'' from Houston. After asking around, the two found bluesman
Lipscomb at his home in Navasota, Texas.
   ``We just turned the machine on and he played one song after the
other. They usually give you their best,'' Strachwitz said. ``It
was just a little shotgun house, with his wife and a number of
grandchildren.''
   In 1963, Hopkins introduced Strachwitz to Clifton Chenier, who
was playing little bars in Houston's French section.
   ``I always tried to get him to play his French music, but he
always wanted to play rock 'n' roll.''
   Chenier, one of Arhoolie's best-selling artists, died in 1987.
   Over the years, Strachwitz has improved his equipment, but he
still prefers taping acoustic instruments with simple recording
devices. More and more, he is forced to take bands into the studio
to cut albums.
   His current best seller is the Cajun band Beausoleil, featuring
fiddler Michael Ducet. Strachwitz said Ducet has much of the
spontaneity and character of the singers he found in remote areas
during the 1960s.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wednesday AMs, Oct. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891019-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1406EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:IrishAnthology Adv26   10-19 0818</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Irish Anthology, Adv 26,0832</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday AMs, Oct. 26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Anthologist Hopes for a Weapon Too Big To Throw</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Books as well as rocks and guns have long been
weapons in the feuds that have riven Ireland.
   Seamus Deane, nearing the end of his work on one of the biggest
books of all, an anthology of 14 centuries of Irish writing, hopes
it will be simply too large and too inclusive to hurl at an enemy.
   Deane, a professor of English and American literature at
University College Dublin, is general editor of ``The Field Day
Anthology of Irish Writing, 550-1990,'' to be published in April by
Faber &amp; Faber.
   In two volumes and 3,000 pages, the anthology will include
examples of writing in early, medieval and modern Irish, Norman
French, Latin and English.
   Deane stresses ``writing'' in the title because he has included
magazine and newspaper articles, oral histories, attempts at
literature that could hardly be called great and commentaries about
Ireland by English notables including Oliver Cromwell, who led a
bloody military expedition through Ireland.
   ``This immense and distressing work,'' as Deane calls it, is
inevitably a political document, an argument against anyone _
republican, loyalist, Protestant, Catholic, Celt, Gael,
Scots-Irish, Anglo-Irish _ who would stake an exclusive claim to
being Irish.
   ``We are not trying to say, in fact we are refusing to say, that
there is some metaphysical essence called `Irishness' that is as
visible in a 9th century poem as it is in a play by Sean O'Casey.
We're not interested in that, because we don't believe in the
existence of it,'' said Deane, a native of Londonderry in the
British province of Northern Ireland, during a recent visit to
London.
   ``The anthology is a serious attempt to try to introduce to
people the idea of a culture that was so rich and diverse that it
cannot be appropriated by any one group.''
   The anthology was sponsored by Field Day, founded in Londonderry
in 1980 by playwright Brian Friel and actor Stephen Rea as a
traveling theater company. It expanded into publishing in 1983 with
a series of political pamphlets, and is widely regarded as the
finest cultural response Northern Ireland has produced against the
violence that has torn the province.
   Deane described the anthology as a definition of Irish writing;
of repossession of Irish-born authors such George Bernard Shaw,
Oscar Wilde, Jonathan Swift, Edmund Burke and Laurence Sterne who
are prominent in English letters; and of decolonization.
   ``It is important that this should be an exemplary act of
showing how you can retain cultural intimacy and links with the
colonizing power while at the same time not learning to think of
yourself as having an ancillary, marginal or junior role to that
power,'' Deane said.
   However, he also detects in Ireland a tendency to fall into a
trap of colonial self-image: ``They don't know where they are or
where they came from, and they invent fake origins that exclude
many people whom they have to live with.''
   Ultimately, he argued, this process of inventing origins and
excluding late-comers makes the ``others'' less human, and thus
suitable targets for murder.
   The anthology is intended, Deane said, to ``provide material
that will show the stupidity and the brokenhearted terminus to
which sectarianism leads, and how sectarianism can only be
justified by a certain kind of deliberate, fostered, nurtured
ignorance of what in fact has happened, what contributions have
been made by various groups over the centuries to the culture.''
   One section will be devoted to Protestant political oratory in
the north in the 19th and 20th centuries. It will also take note of
an Ulster Protestant literary tradition _ ``a literature, alas,
that is not known to many Protestants.''
   One important figure in that tradition is Sir Samuel Ferguson of
Belfast, ``one of the first to try to combine in his writings a
plea for Irish cultural unity which at the same time would allow
maintenance of the political union with Britain.''
   Deane believes the anthology will demonstrate that the Republic
of Ireland does not have a culture distinct from that of Northern
Ireland, and he sees that as a rebuke to southern provincialism.
   ``There is a section called `Provincialism and Censorship,'
centering in the 1930s and 1940s, and is about those writers such
as (Samuel) Beckett, Sean O'Faolain, Frank O'Connor, Flann O'Brien,
Denis Devlin, who in a sense find that the atmosphere in the south
was suffocating,'' he said.
   ``They shut the doors on the minds in the south, they exported
the young people and by the 1950s it had become a kind of
semi-geriatric society with most of its young energy drained away
and the Catholic church ruling the roost, and the intellectual life
in a dreadful state of disrepair.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday AMs, Oct. 26</NOTE>
