<FIRST>a a AM-LandfillActivists Adv26   10-19 1201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Landfill Activists, Adv 26,1231</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday AMs, Oct. 26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Landfill Stirs Emotions, Fears on Both Sides</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN KUSMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CENTER POINT, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A great blue heron, its craned neck
and long bill poking through the morning mist, feeds along the
wooded shore of a strip-mine lake.
   Not far away are watchers armed with binoculars, cameras and
video cameras. But it's not the heron they're watching _ it's
dozens of out-of-state trash trucks rumbling up to the Center Point
Landfill, feeding the earth-movers whose drone shatters the idyll a
half-mile from the lake.
   The ``dump patrol'' _ including teachers, miners, teen-agers and
retirees _ was organized by Terri Moore, whose dream of a quiet,
rural life also has been shattered, by fears of a mountain of
garbage imported from the East Coast.
   ``Until the out-of-state waste stops, we're going to be out
here,'' said Moore, 33, whose troops have logged nearly 1,200 rigs
from 140 companies in the 11 weeks since they started keeping track.
   The landfill operators have called it harassment. ``I have a
substantial investment in the landfill. I'm not going to be doing
anything to jeopardize that,'' said John R. Hoffman, a New
Jersey-based businessman who is a partner in the Center Point
landfill and others near Peru and Wabash.
   But Moore said that if a cleanup is ever needed, officials will
have names they need by tracing license plates and companies logged
by the dump patrol.
   John and Terri Moore and their family moved into their home on
25 acres outside this western Indiana town 2{ years ago. The
lifelong area residents wanted their children to grow up here, too,
near the five-acre lake on their land that attracts the herons,
geese and other wildlife.
   ``It was our dream house. We knew in life we couldn't ask for
anything more. It was like having a vacation every night,'' Terri
said.
   Then last year, John came home from work one day and said
developers proposed a landfill on the property adjacent to theirs,
a few hundred feet from their lake, across the road from Center
Point Landfill.
   Moore feared toxins would leak through abandoned mine shafts to
their lake and property. Last October, she formed HOPE, Hoosiers
Opposing Pollution of the Environment, and tried to reach all of
approximately 750 people who live within two miles of the dump. She
figures 60 percent of the families now are members.
   ``I got people upset. I got people concerned and worried.'' She
also got them to have local land-zoning changes approved that
stopped that landfill.
   It proved to be an empty victory.
   Last November, Center Point Landfill got a state permit to
accept asbestos, which causes cancer and is being removed from
buildings across the country. It also began accepting limited
shipments of trash from out of state. East Coast landfill space is
dwindling and communities must ship refuse elsewhere.
   The landfill's neighbors objected.
   Robert Bedwell Jr., whose family owned the site, said some
people called state officials to report suspected but unfounded
infractions. He began talks with a group headed by Hoffman, and a
sale was completed in July.
   Since then, trucks carrying out-of-state trash have rolled into
Center Point. Some days, as many as 30 trucks queue up at the dump,
motoring to the top of a hill and unloading refuse that bulldozers
cover with dirt.
   ``We knew the landfill was sold, and then one morning we saw 30
or 40 trucks were going by. That kind of made all of our nightmares
come true,'' said Terri Moore.
   ``I don't see how our state officials can have this go on,''
said patrol member Forest Reece, a 78-year-old retired custodian
and factory worker. ``My God, I think it's horrible myself.''
   Indiana apparently can do little. Federal laws forbid one state
from refusing to accept trash from another state. The Solid Waste
Management Board has given preliminary approval to a plan to track
the amount and origin of the trash, but it faces public hearings
and other steps before it goes into effect.
   Bedwell, 37, began taking out-of-state garbage a year ago out of
fear that if a new landfill opened across the road it would steal
his business. He began taking asbestos because it was an
opportunity for the family business to grow.
   ``I didn't take anything hazardous,'' he said, adding that his
asbestos operation met the highest state and federal requirements.
Bedwell said he tried to talk to members of HOPE and show them how
the landfill operated, but, ``They didn't want to see. They wanted
to stand by the road and imagine it.
   ``I went to school with these people. Now they won't even talk
to me. These people used to be my friends. It hurts. It hurts real
bad.''
   Neither Bedwell nor Hoffman would say how much was paid for the
landfill, but legal papers show Hoffman's group came up with an
initial $2.7 million.
   Hoffman, a 13-year veteran of landfill operations, said that
without the out-of-state business, his landfills would be barely
getting by. He said half the refuse accepted at Center Point comes
from out of state.
   ``This is a privately owned business. We have space to sell,''
he said. ``To run a good operation, you need income.''
   The landfill employs 12 people with an annual payroll of
$350,000. It will pump about $1 million into the local economy over
the next 12 months, he said. ``I think that's a very good
neighbor.''
   Hoffman also said the landfill was safe and, like his operations
near Wabash and Peru, refuses waste it is not permitted to accept.
``That particular landfill is probably the best geologically sited
in the state of Indiana.''
   HOPE's fears about the asbestos are unfounded, he said. While it
is dangerous in the air, he said, it ``has zero chance of getting
into the groundwater. It is not mobile in soil.''
   Hoffman acknowledged that HOPE's presence will probably help him
run the landfill better. He has tried to work with the group and
called Moore shortly after he took over, but she wasn't interested
in seeing the operation.
   Now, Hoffman said, he has no more time for Moore or HOPE. ``You
cannot deal with these people rationally. I can't be distracted by
them. They're interested in closing the landfill, true and simple.''
   Meanwhile, U.S. Rep. Christopher H. Smith, R-N.J., says he will
use the photographs taken by Moore and her patrol to convince
Congress that it needs to ban the practice of transporting trash
and food in the same trucks.
   Smith plans to introduce legislation to bar refrigerated trucks
from hauling landfill waste, ban waste transporters from hauling
food, and require landfill operators to have truck-cleaning
procedures. Moore sent him pictures of refrigerated trucks
unloading garbage at the landfill during the summer.
   ``Four different truckers told us they hauled beef on hanging
meat racks from Chicago to the East Coast after making trash
runs,'' she said. ``One thing that really upset us was when
truckers showed us live maggots in the back of non-refrigerated
trucks that had gone through the landfill's washing procedure.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday AMs, Oct. 26</NOTE>
