<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-MelHarris Adv03-05   10-19 0859</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Mel Harris, Adv 03-05,0877</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 3-5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mel Harris Stars as Victim of Klan Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The handsome, charismatic grand dragon of the
Ku Klux Klan was destined for political control of Indiana until a
young schoolteacher looked beneath his sheet.
   It had, in a sense, fatal consequences for both. It led to her
kidnaping and rape; in her humiliation she took her own life. It
sent him to prison amidst revelations of corruption and criminal
activities behind the facade of a benevolent KKK that brought his
empire crashing down.
   NBC retells the story in the miniseries ``Cross of Fire.''
   Mel Harris stars as Madge Oberholtzer, a teacher working for the
Department of Education, and John Heard is David Stephenson, the
Klansman, in this drama based upon a true story of events in
Indiana in the 1920s. At that time, the KKK was a major political
force in a number of states.
   ``Cross of Fire,'' which NBC will telecast in two parts on
Sunday and Monday, also stars Lloyd Bridges as the defense attorney
and David Morse as the prosecutor. Paul Wendkos directed on
location in Kansas from a screenplay by Robert Crais.
   ``They meet at a party for state bigwigs,'' said Harris, who
played the role during time off from ABC's ``thirtysomething.''
   ``She sees it as an opportunity to promote her book program. She
meets David and he tells her the Klan does good work and charity.
He says the bad reports are merely being spread by outside
factions. He's very charismatic and she goes for him.''
   Her feelings cause some emotional conflict, yet it's the first
love of her life. She tries to set aside her reservations about the
Klan.
   ``He has his own private party with her,'' Harris said. ``She
goes to his house to talk about her book project. When she resists
his aggression, he kidnaps her, beats her and rapes her.
   ``She wasn't naive. She was very intelligent. She had been taken
in by his charm. There's always the element that love is blind. She
wanted to believe that he was good. She tries to kill herself when
she realizes the situation she's in.''
   Although she died as a result of taking poison, the jury was so
enraged at his conduct that they sent him to prison for life for
murder. Some of his political cronies also went to jail. No
governor dared release him from prison until 1956, after he served
31 years.
   Harris plays Hope Steadman in the Emmy-winning
``thirtysomething.'' She recently co-starred with Jim Belushi in
the feature film ``K-9'' and co-stars with John Ritter in the
upcoming ABC movie ``My Brother's Wife.'' The latter is based on
the play ``The Middle Ages.''
   During an interview, she was in costume for a 1940s fantasy
sequence for ``thirtysomething'': pants, shirt and tie, a bowler on
her head. The studio streets and commissary were filled with extras
in period clothing.
   ``I don't know what's ahead for Hope,'' she said. ``We talked
about her having a second baby. Hope will continue to work and have
a career outside of the house. She's very loving and caring and
friendly, but sometimes she can be a little too much of those
things.
   ``She would make a wonderful best friend. I don't want to be
her, but I would certainly take her as a friend.''
   In the show she's married to Michael, played by Ken Olin.
Michael is Jewish and the interfaith marriage occasionally causes a
few problems. Such as which faith to raise their son in and the
celebration of Christmas.
   ```My Brother's Wife' is a romantic comedy and a nice change of
pace,'' she said. ``I did it after I completed `Cross of Fire.'
It's about a girl who meets two brothers. One's a straight
Republican growing up in his father's mold. The other pushes the
limits, played by John Ritter, of course. David Byron plays the
other brother.
   ``I marry the stuffy brother. Then it's about how I and the
other brother keep crossing paths. I guess they have this love for
each other. She stays faithful to her husband. It's about how
people's lives change over the years.''
   Her first movie was the 1985 TV movie ``Harry's Hong Kong.'' It
was a series pilot in which David Soul was a businessman and she
was a reporter. She moved to Los Angeles with her husband and
newborn son just before the 1984 Summer Olympics. She had been
doing modeling and commercials and studying acting in New York.
   Harris is married to Cotter Smith, who stars in the upcoming ABC
midseason series ``Equal Justice.'' He plays a bureau chief in the
district attorney's office.
   She grew up in New Brunswick, N.J., where her father was
defensive football coach at Princeton University. She was accepted
at Barnard College, but opted to go into acting instead.
   She was born Mary Ellen but a younger sister couldn't pronounce
it and called her ``Melon,'' which was later shortened to Mel.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 3-5</NOTE>
