<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1811EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WalterMears Adv22   10-19 0864</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv 22,0881</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 22, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Trip Gives Rich Meaning to Word `Honorarium'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Ronald Reagan is beginning a
week in Japan that gives rich, new meaning to the word
``honorarium.'' Make that very rich.
   Reagan is said to be picking up a fee of $2 million, prompting
complaints in Congress and an inquiry into the government costs for
Secret Service protection during the trip.
   The trip, and the flap, came as Congress completed action on a
bill providing $1.8 million to pay the pensions, office and staff
expenses of the four living former presidents. That does not
include the cost of the Secret Service protection provided to
former presidents and their wives.
   The total cost of that protection is expected to come to $12.5
million this year, for three of the former presidents. Richard M.
Nixon decided in 1985 to give up his Secret Service bodyguards and
pay for his own protection. A spokesman said he now spends about
$150,000 a year on it.
   Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., wants a review of the benefits
bestowed on the men who have served in the White House. He called
it federal largesse intended to avoid commercialization of the
office.
   ``Perhaps there is an equitable middle ground between the Reagan
and Nixon situations regarding public funding of protective
services for former presidents when they are traveling on
profitmaking ventures,'' Pryor said.
   He has arranged to meet with Secret Service officials next week
to talk about the cost of guarding former presidents on trips like
Reagan's.
   Pryor suggested Reagan voluntarily reimburse the Treasury for
Secret Service costs on his trip to Japan. ``I doubt he will do
so,'' Pryor told the Senate. ``If some administrative accommodation
cannot be reached on this matter, I will introduce legislation to
make sure the taxpayer does not get stuck with the bill when our
former presidents are off actually increasing their personal
fortunes.''
   In the House, Rep. Paul Kanjorski, D-Pa., said it is
embarrassing to have a former president picking up big fees from a
foreign corporation, then, warming to his topic, called it an
``unmitigated atrocity'' for the government to pay security costs
on such a trip.
   ``I do think it is reasonable to ask what it is costing American
taxpayers to send a former president of the United States to Japan
so that he may engage in conversations with Japanese corporations
and gain $2 million in personal income for doing that,'' Kanjorski
said Tuesday when the House passed the bill including the
appropriation for former presidents, who receive annual pensions of
$99,500. The Senate completed action on Wednesday, without debate.
   Reagan and his wife were spending the weekend in an elegantly
refurbished Japanese guest house after flying to Tokyo on Friday on
a TWA 747 chartered by Fujisankei Communications Group. The company
is financing the trip at an estimated cost of $7 million, including
the reported $2 million fee to Reagan. Neither the company's
spokesmen nor Reagan's have confirmed the size of his payment.
``I'm not familiar with those details,'' said Reagan aide Mark
Weinberg. Reagan is to meet with Japanese officials and to appear
at a series of company-sponsored events, including two speeches
followed by question-answer sessions.
   The Japanese government is co-host for a visit first discussed
in 1983, and again in 1988, before Reagan left office. Charles Z.
Wick, former director of the U.S. Information Agency and a close
friend of the Reagans, helped arrange the visit and was traveling
with them.
   About 200 dependents of American military personnel stationed in
Japan flew there for visits on the chartered jet. They are to
return to Los Angeles with the Reagans on Oct. 28.
   The staff, office and expense appropriations provided to former
presidents date back 21 years. Costs have been increasing, and
there have been proposals to limit that spending during the past
five years. The Reagan controversy may give that movement a push.
   ``We owe our former presidents protection and respect, but do we
owe them a guarantee to underwrite whatever future business
ventures they may undertake for personal gain?'' Pryor asked.
   Sen. Charles E. Grassley, R-Iowa, has proposed a bill to limit
staff and expense payments to former presidents, and also to
provide for annual reviews of their security needs beginning five
years after they leave office. ``While they should be rewarded for
their service to this country, it is not appropriate to treat them
as royalty at taxpayer expense,'' Grassley said when he introduced
it last summer.
   The appropriation Congress has just passed provides $559,500 for
Reagan, $387,800 for Jimmy Carter, $426,800 for Gerald R. Ford and
$426,700 for Nixon.
   Nixon's assistant said none of the money he gets has been used
on his books ``or any other profit-making work.'' John H. Taylor
said Nixon does not accept speech fees despite offers that total
$720,000 a year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national
politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
