<DOCNO> AP891019-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1358EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--OnShow Adv00   10-19 1006</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--On Show, Adv 00,1150</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>On Show: Museum and Gallery Exhibits and Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THE ASSOCIATED PRESS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A new museum will be created in Pittsburgh to house the works of
pop artist Andy Warhol. More than 700 Warhol paintings, prints,
drawings, sculptures, films and videotapes will form the collection
in the Andy Warhol Museum. It is scheduled to open in 1992.
   The first major exhibit in two decades of works by Frederic
Edwin Church has opened at the National Gallery of Art in
Washington. The Hudson River artist's majestic idealization of
nature and landscapes can be seen in such paintings as ``Twilight
in the Wilderness'' and ``New England Scenery.''
   Church is one of the leading artists of the Hudson River school.
Last spring, his ``Home by the Lakes'' was auctioned for $8.25
million.
   Here is a list of other current shows this season at some
museums and galleries in the United States:
   
   WASHINGTON
   
   National Gallery of Art:
   Works of Frederic Edwin Church. Through Jan. 28.
   
   NEW YORK
   
   Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum:
   First major American exhibition of works by Italian artist Mario
Merz, who integrates natural materials into his work. Through Nov.
26.
   
   Washburn Gallery:
   ``Anne Ryan: A Centennial.'' Paintings, collages of artist-poet
Anne Ryan (1889-1954). Through Nov. 4.
   
   Nerlino Gallery:
   Mantle sculptures, lithographs and multiple exposure sepia
photos by Mary Clare Galvin. Through Nov. 1.
   
   Metropolitan Museum of Art:
   Compositions by Diego Rodriquez de Silva y Velazquez, including
his ``An Old Woman Cooking Eggs'' (1618) with its haunting reality,
and ``The Forge of Vulcan'' and ``Joseph's Coat,'' two large works
painted during a trip to Italy in 1629-31. Through Jan. 7.
   ``Masterworks of Ming and Qing Painting From the Forbidden
City.'' Chinese paintings dating from the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing
(1644-1911) dynasties. Through Oct. 29.
   Flemish drawings and prints from 16th and 17th centuries.
Through Nov. 12.
   
   Museum of Modern Art:
   ``Picasso and Braque: Pioneering Cubism.'' Through Jan. 16.
   
   Phillippe Staib Gallery:
   Bronze sculpture by Louis Derbre. Through Nov. 18.
   
   Pace-McGill Gallery:
   Vintage photographs by Alexander Rodchenko. Through Nov. 25.
