<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     10-19 0820</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0861</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction, buffeted by rising
mortgage rates, fell for a second straight month in September,
declining to the weakest pace in seven years, the government
reported.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that construction of new
homes and apartments dropped 5.2 percent following a 6.2 percent
August decline.
   The back-to-back drops pushed construction starts down to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.26 million units, the slowest
pace since October 1982.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street sized up the California earthquake
and bid up the stocks of builders, lumber companies and computer
disaster-recovery services, all of which do big business after a
catastrophe.
   In somewhat of a surprise, some insurance stocks also rose
Wednesday, apparently on speculation that the quake would provide
an opportunity for insurers to raise rates.
   Despite an early drop in a nervous reaction to the quake, the
overall stock market had its calmest day since Friday's 190-point
plunge in the Dow Jones 30-stock industrial average.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Inspectors examined Northern California gasoline pipelines in
the aftermath of a devastating earthquake and major oil companies
made contingency plans to avoid supply disruptions, but energy
prices were little affected.
   On the oil futures market Wednesday, crude oil contracts rose at
first because of concerns about possible damage to major oil
refineries, but they closed near the day's lows following reports
that the quake was unlikely to seriously disrupt production or
distribution.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee voted to give the
Transportation Department authority to block major airline
takeovers, after backers of the bill said travelers want assurances
a purchaser's heavy debt would not jeopardize safety.
   Under the legislation, approved by the panel Wednesday, the
Transportation Department would be obligated to block the purchase
of 15 percent of an airline's voting stock if the deal would
jeopardize safety, lead to a breakup of the company, hinder its
ability to compete, or leave the carrier in the hands of a foreign
interest.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration will quit buying
Mexican oil for the U.S. emergency stockpile early next year,
ending an eight-year supply link aimed in part at aiding the
debt-ridden Mexican economy, sources said.
   The administration and the Mexican state oil company, Pemex,
agreed that an existing supply contract expiring Nov. 30 will not
be renewed, an Energy Department source said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bankers said they were trying to lure Japanese
investors into the endangered takeover deal for airline giant UAL
Corp., and oilman Marvin Davis suggested he might resurrect his bid
for United Airlines' parent at a lower price.
   UAL Corp. stock appeared to stabilize Wednesday after a
three-day slide triggered by word that the $6.75 billion,
$300-a-share offer for the company from a management-labor group
had fizzled because it couldn't get financing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AMR Corp. called Donald Trump's aborted $7.5
billion takeover attempt ``ill-considered and reckless'' and said
the parent company of American Airlines ``has not been, and is not,
for sale.''
   AMR also reported Wednesday that its third-quarter profit
dropped as expected from a year earlier, falling nearly 8.9
percent, and forecast continued pressure on earnings from rising
fuel prices and lower passenger yields.
   In its first statement since Trump's $120-per-share offer was
made Oct. 4, the AMR board said, ``We are pleased that Mr. Donald
Trump has withdrawn his uninvited proposal to negotiate a cash
merger agreement with AMR.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal racketeering laws, with their
potentially stiff fines and forfeiture provisions, are a useful
tool to prosecute defendants in the savings and loan scandals, a
former top federal prosecutor says.
   At a conference Wednesday debating the uses of the Racketeer
Influenced Corrupt Organizations (RICO) Act, Joseph diGenova,
former U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia, said the law was
``perfect for what went on in the savings and loan industry.''
   The government recently enacted a $50 billion plan to bail out
the nation's thrifts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiations aimed at ending a strike by Boeing
Co. production workers have resumed, but union leaders expressed
doubt that a quick settlement was likely.
   Justin Ostro, aerospace industry bargaining coordinator and vice
president of the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers, refused to say Wednesday what might happen,
``just that we're here and hopeful _ always.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks posted modest price gains Wednesday as the market
regained its composure after several jumpy sessions. Contrary to
initial fears, the Northern California earthquake didn't do much
damage to the market. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
finished with a gain of 4.92 at 2,643.65.
   The dollar ended weaker against key foreign currencies.
   Bond prices finished little changed in subdued dealings.
   Copper futures prices slipped to their lowest point this month;
precious metals advanced; grains and soybeans were mixed; livestock
and meat futures were mixed; and stock-index futures rose.
</TEXT>
