<FIRST>r f PM-IBMBuyback     10-19 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IBM Buyback,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Directors Authorize $1 Billion Stock Buyback</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. said its
board of directors had authorized the repurchase of up to $1
billion worth of IBM stock.
   IBM already has bought back more than $5 billion of its own
shares since early 1986, making the company its own most loyal
investor. Outside investors aren't so happy with the computer
giant, whose stock is down about 40 percent from its high of $175
before the 1987 stock market crash.
   The announcement Wednesday was made after the close of trading.
IBM's stock fell 50 cents a share to $101.75 in consolidated New
York Stock Exchange trading.
   The latest repurchase would amount to about 3.4 percent of the
company's roughly 579 million outstanding shares at current stock
prices.
   ``We view it as a good long-term investment,'' IBM spokesman
John Boudreaux said. For shareholders, he said, ``it has a positive
effect on the earnings per share and the return on equity.''
</TEXT>
