<DOCNO> AP891019-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0047EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-US-MexicoOil     10-19 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Mexico Oil,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>US to Halt Purchases of Mexican Oil for Emergency Reserve</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration will quit buying
Mexican oil for the U.S. emergency stockpile early next year,
ending an eight-year supply link aimed in part at aiding the
debt-ridden Mexican economy, sources said.
   The administration and the Mexican state oil company, Pemex,
agreed that an existing supply contract expiring Nov. 30 will not
be renewed, said an Energy Department source who spoke on condition
he not be identified.
   Additional Mexican oil will be purchased for three months beyond
the contract's expiration in order to satisfy a minimum volume
requirement, the source said Wednesday.
   The arrangement is to be announced next month, according to an
internal Energy Department memorandum made available to The
Associated Press.
   Starting in December, the Energy Department will meet its
stockpile needs by soliciting bids for short-term supply deals with
domestic and foreign suppliers _ the usual practice before the
Mexican contracts started in 1981.
   In August 1982, at the height of Mexico's foreign debt crisis,
the Reagan administration agreed to pay Mexico $1 billion in
advance for oil to be put in the Strategic Petroleum Reserve.
   The decision to end contract purchases from Mexico is due in
part to a growing constraint on Mexico's capability to produce
enough high-quality Isthmus crude to meet both export and domestic
demand, the source said.
   The reserve was started in 1975 after the Arab oil embargo and
is designed to give the United States enough emergency supplies to
weather any future disruption of oil imports. The oil, about 575
million barrels, is stored in underground salt domes in Texas and
Louisiana. Nearly half has come from Mexico and only 6 percent from
U.S. wells.
   On Tuesday the department gave Congress an interim report that
suggested ways to cut costs of filling the reserve, including
leasing oil from foreign producers and selling U.S. government
bonds to finance the reserve.
   An Energy Department delegation is to fly to the Middle East
early next month to discuss the leasing idea and other topics with
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates, a department
source said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891019-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0121EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Quake-Economics Bjt   10-19 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Economics, Bjt,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Long-Term Economic Problems Seen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early indications were that California's
strong economy would shake off the effects of the devastating
earthquake in the San Francisco Bay area.
   San Francisco Mayor Art Agnos said damage in his city and county
alone might reach $2 billion.
   But in a sign of investor confidence in the state, California
municipal bond issues were down only slightly Wednesday and in line
with the overall decline in the market, said Mark Haslinger, a
senior vice president with the investment house Clayton Brown &amp;
Associates in New York.
   Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., which evaluates the safety of bond
issues and other financial instruments, said it expected the credit
impact to be localized. And it said it did not expect to adjust its
ratings of the financial obligations of major West Coast financial
institutions.
   John Sullivan, the undersecretary of the state Department of
Business, Transportation and Housing, said Wednesday he stayed up
all night assessing the situation, but that it was still too early
to set a damage figure.
   However, he said, ``Overall the impact will be one the state
will recover from very quickly.
   ``We have a large, strong economy, and while the personal
tragedy for many families is great, the overall economic picture
for the Bay Area and the rest of the state is unclouded by this,''
he said.
   Sullivan said he was optimistic about the insurance business.
   ``We don't have huge areas of just massive devastation, block
after block, fortunately,'' Sullivan said.
   While damage appeared extremely heavy in such cities as Santa
Cruz and Watsonville, Farmers Insurance Group Inc. spokesman
Jeffrey Beyer said he tended to agree with Sullivan that most
insurers would have no major problems.
   Meanwhile Wednesday, San Francisco-area businesses began to
return to normal.
   Most shuttered companies planned to reopen in the next day or
two. Many of them continued operations from offices outside the
Silicon Valley.
   ``As long as you can manufacture, as long as you can ship and as
long as sales people around the world are selling, we're OK,'' said
Kevin Sullivan, senior vice president for Apple Computer Inc.,
which closed its Cupertino complex Wednesday.
   The complex of about 20 buildings was still without power nearly
24 hours after the quake, but company officials were optimistic
they could reopen today or Friday.
   International Business Machines Corp. closed one plant with
8,500 employees just south of San Jose, but kept open another plant
in the city itself, said Dave Berman, communications manager.
   At Amdahl Corp., a Silicon Valley manufacturer of mainframe
computers, the computer system crashed, then was brought back up _
albeit at one-third the usual speed _ in a backup mode late Tuesday
night.
   Advanced Micro Devices Inc., another big Sunnyvale-based
high-tech company, said it called off the overnight shift Tuesday
but normal operations resumed with the start of the day shift
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891019-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0114EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Quake-Insurance Bjt   10-19 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Insurance, Bjt,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Homeowners Not Insured; Analysts Say Disaster May Benefit Insurers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Those who follow the insurance industry
see opportunities for investors in the wake of the San Francisco
earthquake.
   Analysts predicted insurers will be able to reverse three years
of declining rates in California by increasing pressure on state
regulators to boost premiums as a result of the earthquake and the
estimated $4 billion in damage from Hurricane Hugo in South
Carolina.
   An increase in insurance rates could translate into greater
profitability in the long term, which in turn would boost the value
of stocks, the analysts said Wednesday.
   ``There's a perception that this could turn the cycle .... that
this could be enough to firm pricing,'' said Gloria L. Vogel, an
analyst with Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. Inc. in New York.
   Insurance companies struggled Wednesday to assess the amount of
claims they're likely to pay as a result of the quake. In addition
to home damage, the insurance companies are likely to face claims
for automobile damage, broken glass, theft and burglary, business
interruption due to electrical outages, water damage and, possibly,
workers compensation.
   Some estimated that damages will reach $1 billion or more. But
industry observers said they don't expect any company to be
seriously hurt by claims arising from the quake.
   ``We don't think any company is going to have problems paying
claims,'' said Elisa Siegal, public affairs manager for the
American Insurance Association, a Washington-based trade group.
   Easing the burden on insurers is the fact that most homeowners
in the San Francisco area don't have earthquake insurance on their
houses.
   The Association of California Insurance Cos. in Sacramento said
that in the San Francisco area, 25 to 30 percent of the homes have
earthquake insurance. The organization estimated residential damage
at $500 million in the Bay area, with $100 million to $150 million
of that insured.
   Statewide in California, only 15 to 20 percent of all homeowners
have earthquake insurance, which typically requires a 10 percent
deductible and costs $200 to $400 a year for a $100,000 home,
according to industry spokesmen.
   Insured homeowners without earthquake protection will have to
pay for repairs to their houses themselves, unless their homes are
ravaged by fire. Fire damage is covered under basic homeowner
insurance polices, said Hugh Strawn, director of catastrophe
services at the Property Loss Research Bureau in Schaumburg, Ill.
   ``If there was fire damage, the fire is covered. That's quite
specific,'' Strawn said.
   Earthquake insurance is an emotional and politically-charged
issue in California, where many of the nation's most damaging
earthquakes have occurred.
   Under a 1985 California law, insurers are required to offer
earthquake insurance to homebuyers, but homebuyers are not required
to buy the coverage.
   Insurers aren't required to offer earthquake insurance to
commercial property owners, but the percentage of business property
with the coverage is higher than that of homeowners, industry
spokesmen said. They estimated that at least 25 percent, and
probably many more, business properties are insured.
   Because of its high costs, earthquake insurance has become a
target of the controversial Proposition 103 approved by California
voters last year. The proposition calls for a 20 percent rollback
in insurance rates. Insurers and state regulators are battling over
the rates and how they're set.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891019-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0105EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TalkingAd Bjt   10-19 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Talking Ad, Bjt,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Instruments Unveils First Magazine Ad That Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There've been pop-up ads, scented ads, even a
magazine spread that played Christmas music. But this week Texas
Instruments Inc. has taken it a step further with a magazine ad
that ``talks'' to readers.
   ``I am the talking chip, one of many Texas Instruments MegaChip
Technologies that are changing the way the world lives, works and
plays,'' says the voice generated by a miniscule computer chip that
costs less than $2 to produce.
   ``This ad demonstrates a new tool for creative people to deliver
powerful messages in an arresting way,'' said Bill Edwards, who
supervised the project for the Dallas office of the McCann-Erickson
advertising agency.
   ``Who can ignore a printed page in Business Week that talks to
you?'' he said. ``The effect is truly startling.''
   The ad will run in 140,000 copies of Business Week's Oct. 20
industrial-technology edition and 76,000 copies of its Nov. 20
international editions.
   The ad also features a tear-away section, allowing a look at the
credit-card-sized, eighth-inch thick gadget that contains three
batteries with enough juice for 650 repetitions; a microprocessor
that performs 61 chores and generates the voice; and a one-inch
speaker.
   The chip represents the latest advance in speech synthesis
semiconductors, said TI's Ken Melvin, product manager for
semiconductor speech.
   ``For years, high-quality speech has been a luxury that
manufactures added only to consumer products with price points of
$50, $75, $100 or more,'' Melvin said. ``Our goal has been to
reduce the cost of speech technology to make it practical in more
applications.''
   TI hopes the advertisement will demonstrate not only marketing
possibilities, but spark ideas for other uses of the silicon wafer.
   Reducing the chip cost to under $2 allows products using the
technology to sell at retail for about $10, Melvin said.
   One possible use for the chip is the creation of talking
products for the visually handicapped, which would contain verbal
warnings or statements about their use.
   Magazine advertisers in recent years gone to extraordinary
lengths to make their messages stand out.
   TransAmerica, for instance, devised an ad that ran in Time
magazine in 1986 that featured a pop-up of a facsimile of its
distinctive San Francisco tower. Dodge trucks had a similar pop-up
ad for its midsize pickup truck in a 1987 issue of Sports
Illustrated.
   Also in 1987, the importers of Absolut vodka introduced sound to
mass-market magazine advertising by including a battery-powered
microchip that played Christmas music when its ad in The New Yorker
magazine was opened. Absolut's most recent ad features a punch-out
paper bottle of its vodka that produces a 3-D image when the reader
looks through two eye holes in it.
   TI began using speech technology in 1974 and in 1978 introduced
its popular Speak and Spell line of educational toys. In the
meantime, all sorts of products have begun to talk: books, cars,
alarm clocks, toys, learning aids and appliances.
   TI also uses its speech know-how in many of its military
projects.
   Texas Instruments' ad was developed with Intervisual
Communications and McCann-Erickson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
