<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0153EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-S&amp;L-Racketeering Bjt   10-19 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;L-Racketeering, Bjt,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Prosecutor: Use Racketeering Laws on S&amp;L Mess</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former top federal prosecutor says the
crippling fines and forfeiture provisions of the federal
racketeering law should be turned on those accused of fraud in the
savings and loan scandals.
   And the man who helped craft the controversial Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act agrees.
   At a conference discussing the future of RICO, Joseph diGenova,
former U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia, said the law was
``perfect for what went on in the savings and loan industry.''
   Congress has enacted a $50 billion bailout plan for the nation's
faltering savings and loans, many of which failed because of fraud,
mismanagement and the economic downturn in the Southwest.
   In April, the government seized a large California thrift,
Lincoln Savings and Loan Association of Irvine, and filed a $1.1
billion civil lawsuit against its operators, charging fraud and
racketeering.
   James Barth, chief economist at the Office of Thrift
Supervision, attributed approximately one in 10 failures to fraud.
   ``It seems to me that knowing what we know about RICO, and
knowing what we know about the S&amp;L crisis, that Congress could not
have enacted a better statute to deal with what went on in the
savings and loan industry over the last few years,'' said diGenova,
now in private practice.
   That notion was seconded by G. Robert Blakey, a University of
Notre Dame professor who was one of the architects of the RICO
statute nearly 20 years ago.
   ``It's not a single instance of fraud but it would be a pattern
of frauds: multiple bad loans of one kind and another, insiders
dealing with outsiders. That falls within the core meaning of RICO,
mail fraud and wire fraud.''
   Their remarks came at a conference, ``RICO, Rights and the
Constitution,'' sponsored by the Cato Institute, a Washington-based
think tank.
   Passed by Congress in 1970 as part of the Organized Crime
Control Act, RICO was designed to make it easier for prosecutors to
go after mobsters by giving them a tool to attack seemingly
legitimate businesses associated with organized crime.
   Prosecutors can take seemingly unrelated crimes or alleged
crimes committed by several people over a 10-year-period, and if
they can convince a jury that those charged were linked through a
``criminal enterprise,'' they can win a racketeering conviction.
   Those convicted are subject to maximum penalties of 20 years in
prison, hundreds of thousands of dollars in fines and forfeiture of
illegal profits into the millions, if the government can collect.
   In civil RICO cases, brought either by the government or private
parties, defendants are liable to pay triple damages if found to
have engaged in a ``racketeering enterprise.''
   Though tremendously successful in the Justice Department's
attack on the Mafia, RICO has become increasingly controversial as
prosecutors used it on crooked politicians and businessmen in cases
that critics say might not have been brought under other laws.
   But in reply to that argument, diGenova countered: ``No one
seems to have a problem with applying RICO to the Colombo
(organized crime) family or the Genovese (organized crime) family
or anyone of a number of families whose names end in vowels. The do
have a problem, apparently, applying RICO to people whose names
don't end in vowels and run what are called legitimate businesses
but who happen to engage in massive fraud.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891019-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Quake-OilPrices     10-19 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Oil Prices,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Little Affected By Earthquake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A devastating earthquake in California failed to move the U.S.
oil futures market despite reports of major pipeline shutdowns.
   Late Wednesday, inspectors examined gasoline pipelines in
Northern California for possible leaks or ruptures while major oil
companies made contingency plans to avoid supply disruptions.
   Officials said the pipelines were closed as a precaution
following Tuesday's earthquake.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, fell 19 cents to
finish at $20.56 cents a barrel after a brief earthquake-related
rally at the opening.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for November delivery closed at
54.58 cents a gallon, down 1.26 cents from Tuesday, and November
heating oil dipped 0.45 cent to settle at 60.60 cents a gallon.
   Energy brokers said weekly inventory statistics that showed a
5.7-million-barrel rise in crude oil last week helped weaken the
market once earthquake news was absorbed.
   Pipeline owners in Northern California, including Chevron Corp.,
Santa Fe Pacific Pipeline Partners and Shell Co., said hundreds of
miles of underground gasoline pipes were closed Tuesday when the
quake hit.
   No damage was detected as of late Wednesday and the pipelines
were expected to resume normal operations, they said.
   ``We know of no line ruptures or seam leaks,'' said John Abboud,
senior vice president for Santa Fe Pacific, which has 800 miles of
pipeline stretching from San Francisco to Reno, Nev. ``We will do
some low-pressure testing and once we're satisfied that the lines
are in good shape, we will start the system back up.''
   The pipelines deliver gasoline, diesel and jet fuel from
Richmond, Calif., refineries to big terminals. Products are then
trucked to service stations.
   Chevron Corp. and Exxon Corp. both reported minor damage to
refineries.
   Chevron spokesman Hal Holt said the quake jolted Chevron's
315,000 barrel-a-day Richmond facility but the plant resumed normal
operations early in the day. Exxon said it slowed operations
slightly at its 135,000-barrel-a-day Benicia, Calif., refinery.
Spokesman Henry Beathard said the company did not know when normal
refinery operations would resume.
   Several companies said they were making contingency plans to
ensure delivery of products by truck in case pipelines remained
closed.
   ``Theoretically, we could bring product up from Los Angeles or
Bakersfield if necessary,'' said Albert Greenstein, spokesman for
Atlantic Richfield Co.
   Companies also said they were inspecting underground storage
tanks at service stations and establishing alternate delivery
routes to avoid damaged roadways.
   Texaco Inc. said its Richmond terminal sustained minor damage
but would not disrupt deliveries.
   Unocal Corp. said between 12,000 and 15,000 barrels of gasoline
leaked from three storage tanks at its Richmond terminal but the
spill was contained.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
