<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     10-19 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Ahead of U.S. Consumer Figures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in early European trading in
anticipation of the U.S. Consumer Price Index for September to be
released later today, which dealers expect to set a trend for the
currency.
   Gold was slightly higher.
   Dealers said the dollar was still under pressure following a
larger-than-expected U.S. trade deficit in August and relaxed
monetary policy by the U.S. Federal Reserve following Friday's
stock market slide.
   The price index was expected to rise 0.4 percent after being
unchanged in August, dealers said.
   ``We're seeing a very quiet, technical market this morning,''
said one trader in Milan. ``Nonetheless, there is still evidence of
volatility. We don't have a determined trend.''
   A dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt said: ``The dollar has been
strongly offered in recent days, so we are actually surprised that
it isn't even lower. ... The market is waiting for another piece of
bad news, and then it will go down quickly.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.55 yen to a closing 141.55 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted lower, at 141.25 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
prices, included: 1.84495 West German marks, down from 1.8525;
1.6193 Swiss francs, down from 1.6255; 6.26725 French francs, down
from 6.2990; 2.08425 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0818; 1,359.50
Italian lire, down from 1,366.00; 1.17325 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1737.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.60075 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.5880 late
Wednesday.
   Bullion dealers said trading was quiet as gold showed a subdued
reaction to the weaker dollar.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $368.40 a troy ounce, up
from late Wednesday's $368.25. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $368.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $368.75, up from late Wednesday's
$368.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 51 cents to close at a bid
$368.89.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.12 a troy
ounce, up from late Wednesday's $5.11.
</TEXT>
