<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down In Tokyo, Stocks Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose for the third consecutive session
today, continuing their comeback from Monday's plunge.
   Meanwhile, the dollar declined against the Japanese yen. The
U.S. currency closed at 141.55 yen, down 0.55 yen from Wednesday's
142.10 yen-close. It opened at 140.97 yen and moved between 140.80
yen and 141.70 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues gained 266.66 points, or 0.76 percent, closing at
35,374.22. It had gained 111.48 points Wednesday and 527.39 on
Tuesday.
   ``The Tokyo market has completely recovered from its large drop
Monday,'' said Shunichi Ishimura, a senior dealer at Nomura
Securities.
   The index fell 647.33 points on Monday, this year's largest
one-day loss, following the big tumble in prices in New York on
Friday, when the Dow Jones industrial average fell 190 points.
   The Nikkei index has shot up a total of 905.53 points since
Monday.
   Share prices rose steadily despite uncertainties about prospects
for the U.S. economy, Ishimura said.
   ``Investors' major concern was whether the United States is
going to ease its monetary policy and cut the discount rate,'' he
said.
   Trading was fairly active, with first section volume estimated
at 800 million shares, the same as Wednesday.
   Steel, construction and railway issues were among the gainers.
   In currency dealings, the dollar opened sharply lower following
selling on overseas markets, said Yuji Nakao, a trader with
Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   After that, he said, market participants could not decide the
dollar's direction.
   ``The dollar has become less attractive to investors,'' he said,
citing U.S. economic developments including a wider trade deficit,
Friday's stock price plunge and lower interest rates.
</TEXT>
