<FIRST>u f PM-UAL     10-19 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Stabilizes, Machinists Get Part of Blame for Deal's Failure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp.'s stock price appears to have
stabilized, but dealmakers trying to salvage a proposed buyout of
the parent of United Airlines may have trouble courting one
prospective investor, British Airways PLC.
   Derek Stevens, British Airways' chief financial officer, said
his company was ``in no way committed to a deal going through at
all.''
   Stevens, in an interview with Dow Jones News Service, also said
his company might reduce its planned equity investment of $750
million if a new UAL buyout deal is put together.
   A buyout offer of $230 a share would be ``certainly not too
low,'' Stevens said.
   Meanwhile, UAL's stock closed at $191.75 Wednesday on the New
York Stock Exchange, down a comparatively small $6.25 following a
two-day drop of $81.62 at the beginning of the week.
   ``The worst of the sell-off appears to be over at this point,''
said Stephen Dexter, an airline industry analyst with Kemper
Financial Services Inc., who predicted speculators would watch the
market until concrete terms of a new bid are announced.
   Citibank and Chase Manhattan Bank said Wednesday they were
continuing to court Japanese lenders, who balked at the original
deal, with a sweeter offer. A Citicorp spokesman in Tokyo has said
the new offer was worth $250 a share, or $5.62 billion
   The group trying acquire the nation's second-largest air carrier
said Friday it could not get banks to finance its $6.75 billion,
$300-a-share offer.
   That announcement from the group _ made up of United pilots, UAL
management and British Airways PLC _ helped spark a stock market
plunge and the biggest one-day decline in the Dow Jones industrial
average since the crash of 1987. The widely-followed index tumbled
190 points Friday.
   A British Airways spokesman in New York, John Lampl, said he
could not comment on how long it would take to reconstruct a
revised formal proposal. Spokesmen for the pilots union could not
be reached Wednesday.
   Billionaire investor Marvin Davis said he remained interested in
acquiring UAL, but not at the $300-a-share level he previously
offered. Davis started the buyout fight for UAL when he submitted a
bid in August.
   The International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers, which represents nearly 25,000 of United's 70,000 workers,
vehemently opposed the pilot-management group's original bid.
   It contended the plan would put the airline into too much debt,
and that the 10 percent steady revenue-growth projections on which
the deal was based were unrealistic.
   On Tuesday, the Machinists called for the resignation of UAL
Chairman Stephen M. Wolf and asked for a federal investigation into
possible violations of securities laws by UAL and Davis.
   ``It's very, very important, especially from the Japanese
viewpoint, that there is some semblance of labor harmony,'' Dexter
said of the Machinist actions.
   But even with the Machinists' continued opposition, Japanese
backers could agree to finance a less risky bid of under $250 a
share, he said.
   Machinists spokesman Jim Conley said the union was not looking
for credit for quashing the original proposal, but was happy to
accept it.
   ``Had we gone along with it I think it probably would have
flown, but that would have been irresponsible on our part,'' Conley
said.
   ``It was really an issue of job security,'' he said. ``When the
deal starts going sour, they don't go back to the banks to
renegotiate the financing. The first thing they do is lop heads.''
</TEXT>
