<FIRST>u f PM-Britain-BAT 1stLd-Writethru   10-19 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-BAT, 1st Ld-Writethru,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>BAT Shareholders Approve Restructuring Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, beginning `BAT's shares ...' to CORRECT stock
price.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BAT Industries PLC's shareholders, as expected,
today approved a major, defensive restructuring planned by the
British conglomerate, including the sale of all its U.S. retailing
operations.
   BAT's plan is aimed at increasing shareholder value in an
attempt to thwart a hostile, all-paper $21 billion bid from an
investor group led by Sir James Goldsmith.
   The purchase would be the world's second largest takeover behind
the $25 billion acquisition of RJR Nabisco Inc. completed earlier
this year.
   BAT is the world's biggest tobacco company and has substantial
operations in retailing _ such as the Saks Fifth Avenue and
Marshall Field chains in the United States _ paper and financial
services.
   BAT's shareholders cast their vote at a special shareholders
meeting held in London. BAT Chairman Patrick Sheehy said more than
99 percent of the votes favored the plan.
   Goldsmith previously said his bidding group Hoylake Investments
Ltd. would vote in favor of the BAT plan, calling it ``a first
step'' in the ``unbundling'' of the conglomerate which he has
proposed.
   Goldsmith, who wants to sell off all of BAT's non-tobacco
interests, has said he intends to pursue a takeover of BAT.
   Hoylake's offer of $13.96 worth of securities for each BAT share
has been suspended while the bidders seek approval from U.S. state
insurance commissioners to change the ownership of BAT's Farmers
Insurance Group Inc. of Los Angeles. That could take months.
   Hoylake held between 2 percent and 3 percent of BAT's shares at
the last announced count.
   BAT's shares were up the equivalent of 52 cents at $12.55 on
London's Stock Exchange after the voting results were announced.
The stock has been seesawing during the recent stock market turmoil
and on concerns about what effect Wednesday's disastrous Northern
California earthquake might have on Farmers.
   Company spokesman Michael Prideaux said Wednesday that the stock
market's recent gyrations would not change BAT's restructuring
plans, which he characterized as long-term.
   BAT intends to sell off its U.S. retailing interests and divest
its paper companies and British retailing interests to existing BAT
shareholders. It plans to retain its tobacco and financial services
businesses.
   BAT also intends to buy back 10 percent of its stock and boost
its dividend by 50 percent.
   These moves are intended to enhance BAT's share value. The
company's critics have complained that BAT's share price has been
depressed by the relative slow growth of its tobacco interests.
</TEXT>
