<FIRST>u f PM-Quake-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   10-19 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nation's Stock Markets Shrug Off California Quake</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with today's trading; picks up
6th graf pvs, Most companies ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's stock markets have shrugged off the
deadly California earthquake and traders even found it created
buying opportunities in certain stocks.
   Construction contractors and computer disaster-recovery services
were among the companies that saw their stock prices jacked up
Wednesday by investors in search of quake-related profits.
   Even some insurance stocks rose after analysts said the quake
could stimulate insurers to raise rates and improve the industry's
profitability.
   By today the California quake was mostly forgotten on Wall
Street as stocks rallied in response to a fresh piece of news: an
unexpected slowdown of inflation. The Labor Department said today
that consumer prices rose a modest 0.2 percent in September.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was up 23.56
points at 2,667.21 at 11 a.m. EDT as advancing issues outnumbered
declining ones by a 3-to-1 margin on the New York Stock Exchange.
   On Wednesday, the first session after the California quake, the
Dow Jones average ended the day up 4.92 to 2,643.65 in the calmest
trading since last Friday's 190-point plunge. The only
quake-related jitters came in the opening moments.
   Most companies with headquarters in San Francisco and the nearby
Silicon Valley were unscathed by the market. Even the phone and
utility companies suffered only small declines on Wall Street, as
analysts concluded damage to them was less than feared. The Diablo
Canyon nuclear power plants of Pacific Gas &amp; Electric Co. were
reported to be unharmed.
   One big gainer from the quake was Kasler Corp., a road and
bridge builder based in San Bernardino, Calif., whose stock rose
almost 30 percent.
   ``Obviously one has to assume that the amount of construction
work that's going to be necessary out there is enormous. Kasler is
one of those that should see a good increase in business,'' said
Richard Rossi, an analyst for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   He added, ``I hate to use the word `good' in such a tragedy.''
   The earthquake cut power to the San Francisco floor of the
Pacific Stock Exchange, where some traders continued to work by
candlelight, but trading in stock options had to be suspended. The
Securities and Exchange Commission late Wednesday approved a plan
to shift trading in those options temporarily to exchanges in New
York, Philadelphia and Chicago.
   The biggest declines from the quake actually came overseas on
the Australian and New Zealand markets, which close before New York
opens for business. Traders there sold partly out of fear that the
quake might sink the U.S. stock markets.
   The bigger foreign markets reacted more calmly. Key indexes
gained about 0.3 percent in Tokyo and 1.6 percent in London, where
trading overlaps with the U.S. trading day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
