<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Whitbread     10-19 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Whitbread,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whitbread Plans to Sell off Spirits Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whitbread and Co. said Wednesday it would sell its
distilled spirits division and concentrate on brewing and marketing
beer and running hotels and restaurants.
   Whitbread, one of Britain's biggest brewers, said Wednesday it
plans to sell its James Burrough Distillers unit, whose brands
include Laphroaig malt whiskey and Beefeater gin.
   It also intends to dispose of its Atlas Peak vineyards in
California and its U.S. distribution arm, Buckingham Wile, which
sells Cutty Sark Scotch whisky, officials said.
   The company said it hoped to complete the sales by February.
   Whitbread declined to estimate how much it hoped to earn from
the sales, but industry analysts predicted Whitbread would pick up
as much as 500 million pounds, or $800 million.
   Whitbread last month agreed to buy the brewing interests of
Boddington Group PLC. It also has been investing heavily in
restaurant chains, including Pizza Hut and Beefeater Steak houses
in Europe.
</TEXT>
