<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   10-19 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn and Soybeans Surge On Snow and Soviet Rumors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices surged in early
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid talk of a large
corn purchase by the Soviet Union and forecasts for
harvest-stopping snow in the Midwest.
   Wheat futures were mostly higher, supported by the Agriculture
Department's confirmation that Egypt had bought 55,000 metric tons
of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   Traders said there were strong indications the Soviets had
bought as much as 2 million metric tons of U.S. corn overnight.
   Snow accumulations of up to six inches were forecast for today
and tonight in the central Corn Belt, which could temporarily bring
harvesting activity to a standstill.
   The corn and soybean harvest has been largely unhampered by
inclement conditions so far. Fair weather is expected to return
this weekend.
   In early trading, wheat futures were unchanged to 1\ cents
higher with the contract for delivery in December at $4.06\ a
bushel; corn was 2 cents to 6} cents higher with December at $2.45
a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 2\ cents higher with December at
$1.46{ a bushel; soybeans were 7{ cent to 10\ cents higher with
November at $5.69 a bushel.
   Livestock futures were mostly lower while pork bellies were
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .20 cent higher with October
at 74.55 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .20 cent
lower with October at 82.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .07 cent
to .42 cent lower with October at 48.30 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .18 cent to .60 cent higher with February at 51.95
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
