<FIRST>r f BC-Harley-Glazer     10-19 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Harley-Glazer,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harley Files Suit Against Glazer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harley-Davidson Inc. says a stock-purchase
offer from a Rochester, N.Y.-based group should be halted, saying
it may be just an attempt to drive the stock price higher so the
investors can sell out at a profit.
   Harley, the only major U.S. manufacturer of motorcycles, filed
suit Wednesday in U.S. District Court against Malcolm L. Glazer,
whose investment firm also owns 6 percent of the Milwaukee
company's stock.
   Glazer, three of his companies and his six children violated
rules of the Securities Exchange Act, the suit said.
   Glazero heads an investor group based in Rochester, N.Y. He has
announced Oct. 2 that the group had acquired 6.24 percent of Harley
stock and was thinking of expanding the share to 15 percent.
   Harley requested a Federal Trade Commission investigation,
arguing Glazer did not give it the required written notice of the
filing and did not get the required advance clearance for spending
more than $15 million to acquire Harley stock.
   The suit asks that Judge Terence T. Evans enjoin Glazer from
acquiring more Harley stock or voting on any of the company's
securities, and force Glazer to divest of Harley stock.
</TEXT>
