<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1349EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Caterpillar     10-19 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Caterpillar,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caterpillar Earnings Plunge 43 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caterpillar Inc.'s third-quarter earnings
tumbled 43 percent because of a sales slump that has forced the
company to place about 325 employees on indefinite layoff, the firm
said Thursday.
   Plants in East Peoria, Mossville and Mapleton, Ill. would be
affected, but Caterpillar, a major manufacturer of earth-moving
equipment, did not announce how many workers at each plant would be
idled.
   Caterpillar also said a plant in York, Pa. would shut down
operations involving about 175 workers for a total of four weeks in
November and December.
   The layoffs are necessary ``to keep production in line with
demand,'' the company said in a statement.
   The York plant employs 2,200 people, while in the area of
Illinois affected by layoffs, there are 10,500 production workers,
said company spokesman R.E. Stober.
   Caterpillar blamed its sales decline in part on higher interest
rates, which led to reduced construction activity and discouraged
purchases of replacement equipment, particularly in the housing
sector.
   Caterpillar said it earned $108 million, or $1.07 per share, for
the three months ended Sept. 30, compared to $190 million, or $1.87
per share, for the same period a year ago.
   Revenue fell 5 percent to $2.64 billion from $2.79 billion as
equipment sales declined 6 percent to $2.58 billion from $2.74
billion.
   The company said its earnings also reflected an $11 million
provision for bad debts on Latin American receivables.
   For the first nine months, Caterpillar reported net income of
$390 million, or $3.85 per share, down 14 percent from $453
million, or $4.46 per share, a year ago.
   Revenue for the first three quarters rose 8 percent to $8.36
billion from $7.77 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
