<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0316</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose sharply today, extending their
recovery from the ``Friday the 13th massacre'' with encouragement
from better-than-expected inflation news.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 43.24 points to
2,686.89 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 1,155 up, 329 down
and 405 unchanged.
   After taking a 190.58-point tumble last Friday, the Dow Jones
industrials recovered 73.39 points over this week's first three
sessions.
   The average got an added lift today when the Labor Department
reported that the consumer price index rose just 0.2 percent in
September.
   The increase was about half of what had been expected, given a
marked upswing in the producer price index of finished goods
reported last week for September.
   Interest rates fell in the credit markets in response to the
news. Prices of long-term government bonds, which move in the
opposite direction from interest rates, rose about $5 for each
$1,000 in face value, putting their yields in the 7.98 percent-8.05
percent range.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph rose ~ to 43] in active trading.
The company reported third-quarter earnings of 65 cents a share, up
from 55 cents in the like period last year.
   International Business Machines, which authorized an additional
$1 billion in repurchases of its stock, gained 3[ to 104~.
   American Medical International was up 1~ at 23|. An investor
group said it obtained bank financing for a $26.50-a-share buyout
of AMI.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained 2.82 to 192.14. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up 4.19 at 382.26.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 137.28 million shares with two
hours to go.
</TEXT>
