<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1443EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-BAT     10-19 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BAT,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shareholders Vote For BAT Restructuring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BAT Industries PLC shareholders overwhelmingly
approved a major restructuring Thursday that includes the sale of
the conglomerate's U.S. retailing businesses and is aimed at
thwarting a $21 billion hostile takeover.
   Among shares voting for the restructuring, in which BAT hopes to
bolster its stock value by concentrating on its tobacco and
financial interests, were those controlled by the takeover group
led by Anglo-French financier Sir James Goldsmith.
   BAT also plans to buy back up to 10 percent of its outstanding
stock, or 153 million shares. Shortly after the midday vote at a
special shareholders meeting announced it had bought 2.5 million
shares at the equivalent of $12.48 a share from the brokerage
Barclays de Zoete Wedd Securities Ltd.
   BAT's shares rose the equivalent of 43 cents to $12.52 a share
Thursday on London's Stock Exchange.
   The Goldsmith group, Hoylake Investments Ltd., and its
associates controlled between 2 percent and 3 percent of BAT's
shares at the last announced count.
   A spokesman for Goldsmith, who was not identified, said by
telephone, ``We voted for it, as we said we would.''
   The restructuring was favored by 99 percent of the shareholder
votes cast, said BAT Chairman Patrick Sheehy.
   BAT plans to retain its tobacco and financial services
businesses and sell its U.S. retailing interests, which include
Saks Fifth Avenue and Marshall Field stores. It also plans to spin
off its paper companies and British retailing interests to existing
BAT shareholders and to boost its dividend by 50 percent.
   BAT said it would keep acquiring shares under its buyback plan,
subject to price, availability and market conditions, up to the
close of business on Friday. After then, BAT may not buy more
shares until it has released its third-quarter results on Nov. 22.
   ``We will proceed as speedily as possible and in light of market
conditions,'' Sheehy told shareholders.
   There was concern that the recent stock market turmoil following
the Friday the 13th plunge on Wall Street and the large number of
U.S. retailing properties on the block might make it difficult for
BAT to sell pieces at a good price and might delay the
restructuring.
   ``We are determined to get a good price for them,'' Sheehy said.
``We are not in any hurry to sell them.''
   Sheehy said BAT already had intended to change its strategy of
diversifying slowly away from tobacco, and Goldsmith's bid prompted
a ``significant acceleration.''
   Hoylake wants to sell off all BAT's non-tobacco interests and
says it will continue pursuing its bid despite the restructuring.
   BAT's critics have complained the relative slow growth of the
tobacco businesses has depressed the market value of BAT's shares.
   But Sheehy said tobacco offers steady earnings and good cash
flow, while financial services offer faster growth. These
businesses represent 80 percent of BAT's forecast pre-tax profit
for 1989.
   There was no sign of Goldsmith at the shareholders meeting. The
Anglo-French financier previously said Hoylake would vote for the
restructuring, calling it a first step in his hoped-for
``unbundling'' of the conglomerate.
   Hoylake's bid of $13.96 worth of securities for each BAT share
has been suspended while it seeks approval from U.S. state
insurance commissioners to change the ownership of BAT's Farmers
Insurance Group Inc.
   Sheehy said he didn't expect Farmers' profit to be hurt by
Tuesday's disastrous Northern California earthquake.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
