<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1601EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Textron     10-19 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Textron,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Textron Blames Sagging Auto, Aerospace Markets for Lower Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textron Inc. reported Thursday that
higher costs in its aerospace and auto products businesses
contributed to a 5.5 percent drop in the conglomerate's
third-quarter earnings.
   Textron said it earned $59.5 million, or 66 cents per share, in
the quarter ended Sept. 30, compared with 1988 third-quarter
results of $62.8 million, or 72 cents per share.
   Revenue increased to $1.73 billion from $1.72 billion a year
earlier.
   Textron's aerospace business was especially hard hit by cost
increases in its fixed-price contracts to develop the V22 Osprey
tilt-rotor aircraft with Boeing Helicopter Co., said spokesman
Raymond W. Caine Jr.
   The Defense Department has canceled that program, but Textron is
attempting to persuade Congress to restore funding, he said.
   Overall aerospace segment revenue fell nearly 10 percent to $756
million, and earnings in that division were down almost 17 percent
to $65.6 million.
   Textron's commercial products segment, which includes its
automotive businesses, posted a $41 million increase in revenue to
$434 million but earnings decreased from $33 million to $27 million.
   Caine said he was unable to pinpoint one reason for the softer
margins in that segment. ``It's just a question of the costs were
higher than we thought they would be,'' he said.
   Textron's financial services sector saw earnings increase 25
percent to $69 million because of strength in consumer finance and
insurance businesses, Caine said.
   For the first nine months of the year, Textron said it earned
$182.1 million, or $2.17 a share, compared with $170.4 million, or
$2.27 a share, a year earlier. Textron had more shares outstanding
a year ago.
   Revenue for the first three quarters increased to $5.41 billion
from $5.3 billion.
</TEXT>
