<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1532EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Banks     10-19 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Banks,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>BankAmerica Enjoys Earnings Surge; Bank of Boston Takes Big Hit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   BankAmerica Corp. reported a 34 percent rise in third-quarter
earnings Thursday on the strength of its basic money-lending
business, while across the continent the Bank of Boston reported a
$125.1 million loss related to an increased reserve for bad loans.
   Analysts said BankAmerica's results reflected a remarkable
turnaround at the nation's second-biggest banking company behind
Citicorp. Only a few years ago BankAmerica was wallowing in heavy
losses.
   The Bank of Boston results underscored growing economic problems
in once-thriving New England, which has put pressure on many banks
that have lent money aggressively in that region.
   San Francisco-based BankAmerica said it earned $254 million or
$1.16 a share in the three months ended Sept. 30, vs. $190 million
or 97 cents a share in the year-earlier quarter. The bank had an
average of 201.49 million shares outstanding in the 1989
third-quarter vs. 178.91 million a year earlier.
   Combined net interest income and non-interest income totaled
$1.47 billion, a 19.5 percent increase over $1.23 billion a year
earlier.
   ``The quarter's results reflect continued strong performance in
the fundamental areas of our business, particularly growth in
consumer and residential mortgage loans,'' said BankAmerica
Chairman A.W. Clausen. ``Net credit losses were low during the
quarter, capital and reserve levels increased, and expenses
continued to be effectively controlled.''
   For the nine months, BankAmerica earned $833 million or $4.07 a
share, an 81 percent increase over the $461 million or $2.40 a
share earned a year earlier. The bank had an average of 194.56
million shares outstanding in the first three quarters of 1989 vs.
172.19 million a year earlier.
   Combined net interest income and non-interest income for the
nine months totaled $4.36 billion, an 18.2 percent increase over
$3.69 billion a year earlier.
   At the Bank of Boston, the nation's 14th-largest banking
concern, the third-quarter loss totaled $125.1 million or a
per-share loss of $1.82, compared with earnings of $79.2 million or
$1.14 a share a year earlier. The bank's average shares outstanding
in the quarter totaled 78.68 million vs. 66.34 million.
   Combined net interest income and non-interest income for the
third quarter totaled $430.6 million, a 5.4 percent decrease over
the $455.3 million a year earlier.
   Ira Stepanian, chairman and chief executive officer, said the
results reflected the bank's previously announced $370 million
addition to its reserve for possibly bad loans, due largely to a
weakening real estate market.
   For the nine months, the bank earned $61.8 million or 73 cents a
share, a 74 percent decline over the $239.6 million or $3.47 a
share earned a year earlier. Average shares outstanding totaled
70.21 million vs. 65.92 million.
   Combined net interest income and non-interest income for the
nine months totaled $1.39 billion vs. $1.35 billion, a 2.9 percent
gain.
</TEXT>
