<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   10-19 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn Futures Rise Sharply On Signs Of Soviet Purchase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Signs of a large Soviet purchase of U.S. corn
pulled corn futures prices up sharply Thursday on the Chicago Board
of Trade, and the other grain markets rallied in kind.
   ``It looks like Russia bought another 2 million (metric tons) of
corn overnight and I believe it's true,'' said Gerald Zusel,
manager of Balfour Maclaine Corp.'s floor operations at the
exchange.
   He cited heavy buying of futures by grain exporters, which
frequently signals a large foreign purchase.
   Rumors of Soviet buying of U.S. soybeans and soybean meal gave
those markets an additional boost and wheat futures gained on a
spillover of the bullish enthusiasm.
   Snow accumulations of up to six inches were expected overnight
in the eastern Corn Belt, which would bring harvesting activity to
a halt. But Zusel said forecasts for mild weekend temperatures and
drier-than-normal conditions in the Midwest next week minimized
chances of significant harvest delays.
   At the close, wheat futures were { cent to 1{ cents higher with
December at $4.07} a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 5} cents higher
with December at $2.44 a bushel; oats were { cent to 1} cents
higher with December at $1.46 a bushel; soybeans were 7 cents to 9
cents higher with November at $5.66} a bushel.
</TEXT>
