<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1955EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-AmericanBrands     10-19 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-American Brands,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Brands Announces Third-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLD GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Brands Inc. today reported
its earnings increased 13 percent in the third quarter despite a 2
percent drop in revenue.
   American Brands said it earned $166.4 million, or $1.71 per
share, in the quarter ended Sept. 30, up from $146.8 million, or
$1.53 per share, in the third quarter of 1988.
   Revenue declined to $3.06 billion from $3.13 billion. The
company attributed the drop to the sale of its Southland Life
insurance operation in March and to the impact of a stronger U.S.
dollar, which makes the company's products more expensive abroad.
   American Brands Chairman William J. Alley said the company's
core businesses, tobacco, distilled spirits and life insurance, all
performed well during the quarter, with improvements in operating
income.
   The company said operating income was higher from its office
products, hardware and home improvement operations, although
revenue and operating income were lower for specialty business,
including golf products and housewares.
   For the first nine months of the year, American Brands said it
earned $458.8 million, or $4.76 per share, up from $452 million, or
$4.50 per share, in the same period a year ago.
   Revenue for the three quarters rose to $9.03 billion from $8.98
billion a year earlier.
   American Brands' businesses include the American Tobacco Co.;
liquor distilling, with brands including Jim Beam and Gilbey's;
office products, with brands including Swingline; and sporting
goods, including Titleist products. It also owns Franklin life
insurance companies.
</TEXT>
