<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 2034EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SFQuake-Costs     10-19 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Costs,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Quake Among Most Costly Disasters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt. A version moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With damage in the Northern California
earthquake being estimated as high at $1 billion or more, insurance
officials say only five other natural disasters have had higher
dollar price tags.
   Because of inflation, the dollar cost of natural disasters from
earlier times can't be directly compared to the dollar cost of the
Bay Quake.
   The Independent Insurance Agents of America said Thursday that
while the final cost of the San Francisco region quake will not be
known for some time, it will likely top $1 billion.
   Only five other disasters in the United States have had price
tags in excess of that amount, the association reported.
   Those are Hurricane Hugo, with the cleanup still under way but
costs expected to reach $3.98 billion; Hurricane Agnes, 1972, $3
billion; Hurricane Camille, 1969, $1.42 billion; Hurricane Betsy,
1965, $1.4 billion, and the eruption of Mount St. Helens, 1980,
$1.1 billion.
   The next most costly earthquake, the insurance agents reported,
was the 1971 San Fernando quake, where losses were estimated at
$553 million.
   The great San Francisco quake of 1906 caused an estimated $524
million in damage, according to the agents group. In today's
dollars that would be $5 billion to $5.8 billion, the group said.
That is a huge sum considering that San Francisco was a far smaller
city in 1906.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
