<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-MartinMarietta     10-19 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Martin Marietta,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Martin Marietta Posts Adjusted 3rd Quarter Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Marietta Corp. reported its third
quarter earnings declined 57 percent from a year earlier, when it
had a one-time gain from the sale of one of its divisions.
   The aerospace, defense and electronics company said it earned
$87.3 million, or $1.65 per share, in the quarter ended Sept. 30,
compared to earnings of $202.7 million, or $3.82 per share, in the
same period of 1988.
   In the year-earlier period, Martin Marietta had a one-time
after-tax gain of $135.7 million, from the sale of Hoskyns Group
PLC, a British computer services company.
   Without that gain, its earnings would have risen 30 percent in
the latest quarter.
   Third-quarter revenue slipped to $1.42 billion from $1.45
billion a year ago.
   Martin Marietta Chairman Norman R. Augustine said the latest
period was highlighted by ``improved margins in our two largest
segments, astronautics and electronics and missiles.''
   For the first nine months of 1989, Martin Marietta's profit
totaled $233.4 million, or $4.41 per share, compared to unadjusted
figures of $335.1 million, or $6.30 per share, for the same period
last year.
   Revenue totaled $4.17 billion in the nine months, down from
$4.19 a year earlier.
