<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 2013EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-USX-Kobe     10-19 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USX-Kobe,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steelmakers Plan Second Joint Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. and Kobe Steel Ltd. of Japan said
Thursday they plan a joint venture in sheet steel galvanizing for
auto and appliance makers.
   The two companies, as USS-Kobe Steel Co., already share another
joint venture, operating the former USX plant at Lorain, Ohio.
   The new venture is an effort to answer growing demand for
high-quality, coated sheet steel, primarily for domestic and
Japanese automakers in the United States, and other sheet steel
consumers, such as makers of appliances and office furniture.
   The companies hope to reach a definitive agreement by year's end
on a 50-50 equity partnership.
   USX and Kobe plan to jointly design and build a state-of-the-art
plant somewhere in the Midwest to produce 600,000 tons per year.
Construction could begin next spring and production could begin two
years later.
   The steel will be coated by dipping it in molten zinc, a process
once limited to culverts, water pails, garbage cans and other
low-grade uses. Hot-dip galvanizing has become increasingly
sophisticated and now can compete with sheets coated by
electrolysis, or electrogalvanizing, said USX spokesman Tom Farrell.
   Master coils would come from USX plants at Pittsburgh, Gary,
Ind., and Birmingham, Ala. The new plant is not expected to hurt
other USX hot-dipped galvanizing lines.
   The companies said they could not project the number of jobs
that would be created or the cost of the plant.
   USX is the nation's largest steelmaker. Kobe is Japan's
fifth-largest steelmaker.
</TEXT>
