<FIRST>u f AM-AutoDefects     10-19 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Defects,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Intensifies Probe of Faulty Cruise Controls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal engineers have stepped up an
investigation of four Ford Motor Co. models following complaints of
malfunctioning cruise controls, the government said Thursday.
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said its
investigation of speed controls in the 1986 and 1987 Ford Tempo and
Mustang and the Mercury Topaz and Capri was being upgraded from a
preliminary evaluation to an engineering analysis.
   The change means engineers will study the potentially defective
parts as opposed to just paperwork analysis.
   The investigations help the agency decide whether to seek
recalls.
   Fifty-five customers have complained that the cruise controls do
not disengage properly, forcing drivers to hit the brakes to slow
the cars, agency spokesman Tim Hurd said. The problem has been
blamed for two accidents and three injuries.
   In Detroit, Ford spokeswoman Joyce Stinson said the company was
investigating the purported defect but had reached no conclusions.
   ``It's always our policy to cooperate fully with NHTSA in their
investigations, and we will do so in this case,'' she said.
   An estimated 562,000 of the 1986-87 Tempos, Mustangs, Topazes
and Capris are on the road, Hurd said.
   The agency also said it was launching several new investigations
and calling off some probes for lack of evidence the public was
endangered.
   NHTSA also upgraded to an engineering analysis its probe of 1985
Toyota vans and cargo vans, of which 104,100 are on the road. There
have been five complaints alleging eight accidents caused by
steering gear failure and resulting loss of control over the
vehicles.
   An engineering analysis of hydraulic fuel leaks in the 1985
Volkswagen Audi 500 was halted despite 663 complaints of hydraulic
fuel leaks causing loss of power steering and brakes.
   Engineers determined the problem is not a safety hazard because
the cars can be controlled with manual brakes and steering, Hurd
said. An estimated 90,000 are on the road.
   The agency opened preliminary evaluations of:
   _Reports that on hard turns, the front wheels of 1987, 1988 and
1989 Chrysler LeBarons rub on something under the car, causing tire
wear. An estimated 600,000 are on the road.
   _Four complaints of locking wheels and steering systems in
180,000 Chevrolet Berettas from 1988, causing two accidents and one
injury.
   _Fractured rear axle shafts in 1.2 million Chevrolet Camaros and
Pontiac Firebirds from the 1982 through 1988 model years. Six
accidents and three injuries have been reported.
   _Alleged transmission oil leaks in the 1988-89 Ford Probe and
Mazda MX6, which are built in the same facilities and have similar
designs. Two Probe fires have been reported.
   _Fires under dashboards of Chrysler Voyager Caravans from
1984-1989. Ten fires have been reported; 1.5 million vehicles are
on the road.
   _Brake failure in the 1986-88 Pontiac Bonneville, Buick LeSabre
and Oldsmobile 88. There have been 35 complaints alleging six
accidents and three injuries. An estimated 1.2 million of the cars
are in use.
   Preliminary evaluations also were begun on two child-restraint
seat models. There have been complaints of children pulling off and
putting in their mouths metallic labels of the Fisher Price model
9100 made in 1988 and foam rubber from Century Products models
4365DT and 4366BH made in 1989.
   The agency closed the books on three preliminary evaluations,
finding no defect trends.
   Those included investigations of axle seal failures in 643,800
General Motors Safari and Astro minivans from 1985-88; breaking
stabilizer bars in 567,000 Toyota Tercels from 1982-88; and wearing
parking brake cable sheaths on the Chevrolet Monte Carlo,
Oldsmobile 88 and Pontiac Grand Prix from 1985-88.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
