<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     10-19 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Finish Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices ended mostly higher Thursday,
boosted in part by strength in the heating oil market.
   Energy prices were unaffected for the second day by the
devastating San Francisco Bay earthquake. Most gasoline pipelines
closed after the quake hit on Tuesday were reopened by late
Wednesday and refineries were reported operating at or near normal.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
domestic heating oil rose 0.29 cent to finish at 60.89 cents a
gallon, after dipping 0.45 cent in the previous session.
   ``I like the way heating oil came back today,'' said James
Steel, analyst with Refco Inc. ``It could be partly because there
is a bigger shortage in Europe than we realize.''
   Colder weather in many parts of the country also helped prices,
traders said.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for November delivery closed 0.07
cent higher at 54.65 cents a gallon after a 1.26 cent decline on
Wednesday.
   Prices of West Texas Intermediate crude were mostly higher with
the exception of the November contract, which closed down 14 cents
at $20.42 a barrel. The contract for December delivery settled 17
cents higher at $20.42 and January finished at $20.18, up 22 cents.
   Projections of higher fourth-quarter demand by the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries' technical committee had no
immediate impact on the market, traders said.
   The OPEC committee projected that worldwide demand for OPEC oil
would increase by 600,000 barrels a day to 23.1 million barrels in
the final quarter of 1989 from the estimated 22.5 million barrels
that the cartel is now producing.
</TEXT>
