<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Oil 1stLd-Writethru   10-19 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Oil, 1st Ld-Writethru,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amoco Down; Schlumberger Up; Ashland Expects Loss</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Amoco Earnings; picks up
6th graf pvs, `Schlumberger Chairman ...; note: The name `Euan' in 12th
graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Amoco Corp. posted a 39 percent drop in third-quarter profit due
partly to lower refining earnings and an $80 million charge for
environmental programs, the company said Thursday.
   Schlumberger Ltd., meanwhile, reported its third-quarter profit
rose nearly 2 percent as oilfield earnings offset a decrease in
interest income.
   And Ashland Oil Inc. said an after-tax charge of $78 million in
the fourth quarter will result in a net loss for the period and
significantly lower results for the year.
   Chicago-based Amoco said its third-quarter earnings tumbled to
$336 million, or 65 cents a share, from $552 million, or $1.07 a
share, in the year-earlier period. Revenue climbed 12 percent to
$6.6 billion, from $5.9 billion a year ago.
   Amoco's nine-month earnings declined 24 percent to $1.3 billion,
or $2.50 a share, from $1.7 billion, or $3.28 a share, in the same
1988 period. The oil company's revenue, meanwhile, climbed 12
percent to $19.9 billion from $17.7 billion in 1988.
   For the three-month period ended Sept. 30, New York-based
Schlumberger said its net income totaled $114.2 million, or 48
cents a share, compared with $112.2 million, or 42 cents a share,
in the same 1988 quarter.
   Revenue totaled $1.12 billion, down 6 percent from $1.18 billion
a year ago.
   Amoco Chairman Richard M. Morrow said an $80 million charge to
``increase provisions for future costs of refining and marketing
environmental programs'' helped reduce third-quarter results.
   Also contributing to the third-quarter decline were lower
production earnings overseas _ $12 million compared with $95
million in the 1988 third period _ and lower U.S. refining,
marketing and transportation income _ $134 million vs. $319 million
a year ago.
   In addition, higher interest income and operating costs offset
the favorable effects of higher crude oil prices and increased
natural gas and crude oil production, Amoco said.
   Schlumberger's income in the first nine months fell 9.5 percent
to $323.4 million, or $1.36 a share, from $357.2 million, or $1.32
a share, in the comparable 1988 period. Revenue declined 5 percent
to $3.48 billion from $3.68 billion.
   Schlumberger Chairman Euan Baird said the company experienced
growth in its oilfield services unit in the third period despite a
9 percent decline in the average number of active rigs worldwide.
That helped offset a decrease in interest income stemming from a
$1.2 billion stock buyback in 1988.
   The nine-month figures include a gain of $13 million, or 5 cents
a share, from the sale of a defense systems unit and a $22 million
extraordinary gain from an award by the Iran-U.S. Claims Tribunal.
The award stemmed from a claim filed by Schlumberger over oilfield
equipment left in Iran a decade earlier when many U.S. companies
evacuated the country due to political turmoil and the rescinding
of oil exploration agreements.
   Ashland, based in Ashland, Ky., said its fourth-quarter charges
include $38 million from a previously announced $325 million
settlement with the National Iranian Oil Co., a $15 million charge
from the planned sale of Ashland's Technology Corp. subsidiary and
a $25 million charge stemming from costs to correct performance
problems at its Riley Consolidated subsidiary.
   The out-of-court settlement with Iran involved claims for oil
that had not been paid for a decade ago when Iran rescinded
exploration agreements with Ashland as well as other U.S. oil
companies.
   Ashland said it plans to announce its results next week. In last
year's fourth quarter, the company had net income of $66 million,
or $1.19 a share, on revenue of $2.2 billion. For the 1988 fiscal
year, it had net income of $224 million, or $4.01, a share, on
revenue of $8.2 billion.
</TEXT>
