<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 2048EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Economy     10-19 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Economy,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawson Stands Firm On Inflation Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Nigel Lawson reaffirmed on Thursday
that Britain's interest rates would stay high ``for some time to
come.''
   Lawson ruled out any alternative to his strategy of raising
interest rates to curb inflation, and said there would be no major
policy changes.
   He also criticized European proposals for a single European
currency, warning any attempt to create a single central bank for
Europe could ``end in tears.''
   Lawson made his comments at the annual banquet of the Lord Mayor
of London. Called the ``Mansion House speech,'' it is a traditional
platform from which the government announces changes in economic
policies.
   The government has pushed up interest rates to 15 percent, their
highest level in eight years, to support the recently weak pound
and slow down inflation, which is running at an annual rate of 7.6
percent.
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit of $26.8 billion in the
first eight months of this year eventually will narrow and
inflation will abate, Lawson predicted.
</TEXT>
