<DOCNO> AP891019-0330 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1720EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-19 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Both Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mixed against major foreign
currencies Thursday at the end of an uneventful session.
   Gold prices eased in the United States after posting scattered
gains and losses overseas.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
settled at $367.10 a troy ounce, down $1.60 from Wednesday.
Republic National Bank quoted a troy ounce of gold at $366.50 at 4
p.m. EDT, $2.20 lower than Wednesday's late bid.
   Currency dealers in financial centers around the world
temporarily sold dollars when news broke that the U.S. Consumer
Price Index went up a modest 0.2 percent in September.
   But the unexpectedly small inflation rate, released at the start
of the U.S. business day, had little lasting impact on currency
trading.
   Speculation about the chances for lower interest rates
circulated in the markets and tended to temper any urge to buy
dollars, dealers said. The low inflation reading could give the
Federal Reserve Board greater leeway to ease monetary tightness,
leading to lower interest rates.
   ``There was no real direction in the market,'' said Siobhan
Lackey, an assistant on the foreign exchange desk of Bank Julius
Baer &amp; Co. ``There wasn't that wild of a reaction to the inflation
news.''
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell to 141.55 yen from 142.10 yen at
Wednesday's close. Later, in London, it fell further to 141.25 yen.
But at the end of New York's day the dollar was quoted at 142 yen,
stronger than Wednesday's late level of 141.40 yen.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5940 from $1.5880 late
Wednesday. In New York, a pound fetched $1.5975 vs. $1.5922 on
Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with Wednesday's
quotes included: 1.8500 West German marks, up from 1.8485; 1.6205
Swiss francs, down from 1.6243; 6.27895 French francs, down from
6.2810; 1.17405 Canadian dollars, up from 1.17335; and 1,360.95
Italian lire, down from 1,362.00.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with late rates on
Wednesday, included: 1.8525 West German marks, unchanged; 1.6225
Swiss francs, down from 1.6255; 6.2875 French francs, down from
6.2990; 2.0820 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0818; 1,358.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,366.00; and 1.1741 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1737.
   In precious metals trading, gold prices posted mixed results
while silver moved lower.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $367.75 a troy ounce,
down from $368.25 bid late Wednesday. In Zurich, gold fell to a
closing $368.20 bid from $368.50 bid late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 51 cents to close at a bid
$368.89.
   On New York's Comex silver bullion for current delivery closed
at $5.08 a troy ounce, down from Wednesday's settlement of $5.105.
Silver bullion fell in London to a late bid price of $5.09 a troy
ounce, down from $5.11 bid late Wednesday.
