<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Purchase Boosts Corn Futures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Signs of a large Soviet purchase of U.S. corn pulled corn
futures prices up sharply Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade
and it wasn't just idle speculation.
   The Agriculture Department confirmed after the close that the
Soviet Union had bought 1.2 million metric tons of corn.
   On other commodity markets, copper futures rallied while
precious metals retreated; stock-index futures soared; energy
futures advanced and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Corn settled 2 cents to 5} cents higher with the contract for
December delivery at $2.44 a bushel.
   Wheat futures finished { cent to 1{ cents higher with December
at $4.07} a bushel; oats were { cent to 1} cents higher with
December at $1.46 a bushel; soybeans were 7 cents to 9 cents higher
with November at $5.66} a bushel.
   Heavy buying of corn futures by grain exporters, freqently a
signal of a large foreign purchase, fueled speculation that the
Soviets had been in the market overnight. The purchase had been
rumored to be as large as 2 million metric tons.
   Persistent rumors of Soviet interest in U.S. soybean meal and
soybean oil continued on Thursday, giving the soybean complex a
boost, and wheat futures gained as the enthusiasm spread from the
corn and soybean pits to the wheat arena.
   Export sales of corn and soybeans typically increase in
mid-autumn, when newly harvested crops increase the supply and
bring prices down.
   ``A general rule of thumb in these markets is that after the
harvest is past the halfway point you'll see a rally, and we're
past the halfway point now,'' said Walter Spilka, a grain-market
analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York.
   The harvest has suffered a setback this week due to cold, stormy
weather in the Midwest, and a storm was expected to drop up to six
inches of snow in the eastern Corn Belt overnight.
   But forecasts for mild weekend temperatures and
drier-than-normal conditions next week minimized chances of
significant harvest delays.
   ``If anyone bought today on weather, they bought for the wrong
reason,'' said Gerald Zusel, manager of Balfour Maclaine Corp.'s
floor operations at the Board of Trade.
   Copper futures rallied modestly on New York's Commodity Exchange
after slipping on Thursday below $1.27 a pound in a move that some
analysts had interpreted as a signal the market was weakening
significantly.
   Precious metals prices declined following the government's
report of a lower-than-expected 0.2 percent rise in consumer prices
last month.
   Copper settled 1.3 cents to 2.3 cents higher with December at
$1.2795 a pound; gold finished $1.80 lower across the board with
December at $370.60 a troy ounce; silver was 2.5 cents to 2.8 cents
lower with December at $5.133 a troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures advanced strongly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange as jitters linked to last Friday's collapse continued to
fade. The contract for December delivery of stocks tracked by the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled 4.95 points higher at 349.60.
The contract is valued at $500 a point.
   Most energy futures prices rallied on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, boosted by strength in the heating oil market.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 14 cents lower to 22
cents higher with November at $20.42 a barrel; heating oil was .01
cent lower to .36 cent higher with November at 60.89 cents a
gallon; unleaded gasoline was .05 cent to .10 cent higher with
November at 54.65 cents a gallon.
   Livestock and meat trading was cautious on the Chicago Merc
ahead of Friday's quarterly USDA cattle-on-feed report and Monday's
monthly USDA cold-storage report.
   Live cattle were .22 cent lower to .05 cent higher with October
at 74.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .25 cent
lower with October at 83 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent
lower to .03 cent higher with October at 48.75 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .13 cent to .55 cent higher with February
at 51.97 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
