<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-ConsumerProducts     10-19 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Consumer Products,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colgate-Palmolive Profit Climbs 28 Percent In Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colgate-Palmolive Co. said Thursday its
third-quarter profit rose 27.5 percent, aided by more efficient
manufacturing operations and strong sales growth.
   For the three-month period ended Sept. 30, the consumer products
company reported net income of $76.7 million, or $1.06 a share, up
from $60.2 million, or 88 cents a share, in the same 1988 quarter.
   Revenue increased 6 percent to $1.26 billion from $1.19 billion.
   Colgate-Palmolive, headquartered in New York, markets its
products under such brand names as Ajax, Fab and Irish Spring, in
addition to Colgate and Palmolive.
   Net income in the first nine months rose 14 percent to $217.5
million, or $3.09 a share, from $191.1 million, or $2.79 a share,
in the comparable period last year. Sales grew by 7 percent to
$3.75 billion from $3.52 billion.
   Colgate-Palmolive Chairman Reuben Mark said the company
``generated the highest return on sales in almost half a century,
well in excess of our 5 percent target level'' in the latest
quarter.
   Mark said that in addition to strong domestic sales, all major
geographic regions showed strong profit growth, particularly Europe
and South America despite the adverse effects of the stronger
dollar.
   Net earnings also benefited from reduced net interest expense
after the divestment of one of its units and the expansion of its
employee stock ownership program.
   Volume increases, manufacturing efficiencies, and strategic
price increases also helped boost pre-tax earnings by 32 percent,
the company said.
</TEXT>
