<HEAD>Jump Higher On Second Anniversary Of Black Monday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 new grafs to INCLUDE reference to crash anniversary,
editing to conform. Picks up 5th graf, The market...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose broadly Thursday, marking the
second anniversary of the Black Monday crash with a rally sparked
by better-than-expected inflation news and extending the recovery
from the market's latest slide.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which plunged 190.58
points last Friday, finished up 39.55 points at 2,683.20. The rise
gave the widely followed market indicator a gain of 112.94 points
during this week's first four sessions.
   Broader market indicators also rose, with seven issues advancing
for every two that dropped on the New York Stock Exchange.
   The upsurge came on the second anniversary of the Oct. 19, 1987
Black Monday crash that saw the Dow industrials nosedive 508 points
to 1,738.74.
   The market got a lift when the Labor Department reported the
consumer price index rose just 0.2 percent in September.
   The increase was about half of what had been expected, given a
sharp rise in the producer price index of finished goods reported
last week for September.
   Interest rates fell in the credit markets in response to the
news, which raised speculation that the Federal Reserve might have
more leeway to push rates lower, making mortgages and other loans
more affordable.
   Prices of long-term government bonds, which move in the opposite
direction from interest rates, rose about $7.50 for each $1,000 in
face value, with the yield on the bellwether 30-year Treasury bond
falling to about 7.95 percent from 8.03 percent late Wednesday.
