<FIRST>r f AM-TimeWarnerRuling     10-19 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time Warner Ruling,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delaware Supreme Court Backs Time Warner on Chris-Craft Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Delaware Supreme Court has sided with Time
Warner Inc., affirming a lower court decision that swept away what
is probably the last obstacle to the acquisition of Warner
Communications Inc.
   Time Inc. earlier this year began a two-stage $14 billion buyout
of Warner in which it initially purchased a controlling interest in
Warner for $70 a share in cash. Time then became Time Warner Inc.
   But Chris-Craft Industries Inc., which had been Warner's biggest
shareholder before Time completed the first phase of the buyout,
contended that it had the right to veto the structure of the second
part of the deal.
   It argued that as the only holder of Warner's Series B preferred
stock, it had the right to vote as a class on the merger agreement.
   But a Delaware Chancery Court judge ruled against Chris-Craft
last month and a three-judge panel of the Delaware Supreme Court
meeting in Dover, Del., affirmed that ruling late Wednesday.
   Time Warner currently owns about 69 percent of Warner's shares
and has offered a package of preferred stock plus Warner's stake in
a Chris-Craft subsidiary for the remainder.
   A Warner spokeswoman said the deal is expected to be completed
by the end of the year.
</TEXT>
