<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 2ndLd-Writethru   10-19 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Extend Comeback With Broad Gain; Mark Crash Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 new grafs to INCLUDE reference to crash anniversary.
Picks up 5th graf, The market...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Better-than-expected inflation news helped send
stock prices broadly higher Thursday, extending the market's
recovery from last week's ``Friday the 13th massacre'' and marking
the second anniversary of its 1987 crash in style.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials gained 39.55 points to
2,683.20.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 2 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
1,235 up, 355 down and 379 unchanged.
   After taking a 190.58-point tumble last Friday for its
second-largest point loss on record, the Dow Jones industrial
average has rebounded 113.94 points over this week's first four
sessions.
   Thursday's jump came exactly two years after the Dow industrials
plummeted 508 points in the infamous Black Monday crash that rocked
markets worldwide.
   The market got an extra lift Thursday morning when the Labor
Department reported that the consumer price index rose just 0.2
percent in September.
   The increase was about half of what had been expected, given the
upswing in the producer price index of finished goods reported last
week for September.
   Analysts said it seemed to improve the odds, as traders saw
them, that the Federal Reserve might soon take new steps to relax
its credit policy.
   Interest rates fell in the credit markets in response to the
news. Prices of long-term government bonds, which move in the
opposite direction from interest rates, rose more than $5 for each
$1,000 in face value, putting their yields in the 7.96 percent-8.04
percent range.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph rose ~ to 43] in active trading.
The company reported third-quarter earnings of 65 cents a share, up
from 55 cents in the like period last year.
   International Business Machines, which authorized an additional
$1 billion in repurchases of its stock, added 2] to 104[.
   Other gainers among the blue chips included Philip Morris, up 1[
at 44{; Procter &amp; Gamble, up } at 128; General Motors, up | at 45{;
Coca-Cola, up 2] at 70], and DuPont, up 1{ at 115~.
   American Medical International was up 1~ at 23|. An investor
group said it obtained bank financing for a $26.50-a-share buyout
of the company.
   Brokers said the AMI news was taken as a plus for stocks in
general, at a time when recent snags in other proposed deals have
unsettled both the stock and high-yield, or ``junk,'' bond markets.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 198.12 million
shares, up from 166.90 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 224.95 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $50.28 billion, or
1.50 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained 2.85 to 192.17.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 6.35 to 396.57, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was up 5.37 at 347.13.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
jumped 7.52 to 470.80. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 382.81, up 4.74.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
