<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 1915EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Seidman-Thrifts     10-19 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seidman-Thrifts,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDIC To Offer $428 Million Package Of Real Estate From Insolvent
Thrifts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In one of the federal government's largest real
estate deals, regulators said Thursday they will sell a $428
million portfolio of property acquired through the bailout of
insolvent thrifts in five states.
   L. William Seidman, chairman of the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp., announced the plan during a speech to Dallas real estate and
financial executives.
   Of the 150 properties, 82 are in Texas and the rest are in
California, Colorado, Arizona and Florida. He said regulators hoped
to sell the real estate in one package but would sell it in pieces
if necessary.
   The properties, which include residential, commercial,
industrial, retail and vacant land, are part of the $2.7 billion in
assets being managed by the Federal Asset Disposition Association,
which is being dissolved under legislation rescuing the savings and
loan industry.
   In addition, Seidman said the FDIC had received considerable
interest in the FADA organization, which is being sold separately
through sealed bids due Oct. 31.
   Seidman said the Resolution Trust Corp., the agency created to
supervise the thrift bailout, will take over an additional 300
insolvent S&amp;Ls this year, giving it control of more than 600
institutions and more than $350 billion in deposits.
   Separately, Seidman said the $50 billion Congress provided to
rescue the thrift industry may be enough if losses continue to
decline at the current rapid rate. In the past, Seidman has
indicated Congress may have to appropriate more money.
   Overall, Seidman said the RTC eventually will have to return $65
billion to $70 billion of repossessed real estate into private
hands.
   ``I don't think it will be sold in the five years that the RTC
is mandated to sell it. It's going to be a factor in the market
over the next decade,'' Seidman told reporters after his speech.
   He said it would be at least a year before regulators begin
selling most of the properties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
