<DOCNO> AP891019-0345 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 2141EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Holiday     10-19 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Holiday,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holiday Corp. Third-Quarter Earnings Leap 89 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holiday Corp. on Thursday reported its
earnings increased 89 percent in the third quarter on the strength
of record income from its gaming operations and the sale of
property.
   Holiday Corp. said it earned $39.7 million, or $1.53 per share,
in the quarter ended Sept. 29, up from $21 million, or 84 cents per
share, in the third quarter of 1988.
   Revenue rose to $433.5 million from last year's $422.1 million.
The company said the results included $19.2 million in pre-tax
gains from property transactions, including the sale of one Embassy
Suites hotel, and $3.5 million in non-recurring costs associated
with the sale of the Holiday Inn hotel chain to Bass PLC.
   Gaming operating income for the third quarter increased to a
record $61.4 million on the strength of record results at the
company's Las Vegas and Atlantic City casinos, the company said.
Hotel operating income for the quarter was even with last year.
   ``During the quarter we negotiated the largest and most
significant transaction in our 37-year history,'' Michael D. Rose,
chairman, president and chief executive officer, said of the $2.23
billion deal with Bass. The sale is expected to close in January.
   For the first nine months of the year, Holiday earned $99.1
million, or $3.86 a share, compared with $102.1 million, or $4.10 a
share, in the first nine months of 1988. Revenue for the first nine
months totaled $1.21 billion, compared with $1.23 billion in the
year-ago period.
   Holiday also announced it planned to make a tender offer and
solicit consents for the repurchase of $1.4 billion of its publicly
traded debt. The repurchase is part of the sale of the Holiday Inn
chain to Bass.
</TEXT>
