<DOCNO> AP891019-0346 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 2329EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Y&amp;R-Jamaica     10-19 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Y&amp;R-Jamaica,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young &amp; Rubicam Says It Resigned Jamaica Account That Led to Indictment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young &amp; Rubicam Inc. said Thursday it would end
its contract with the Jamaica Tourist Board, an account that led to
charges that the advertising agency paid nearly $1 million in
bribes to Jamaican officials.
   ``Y&amp;R and the Jamaica Tourist Board have reviewed our contract
and under the present circumstances have agreed that it is prudent
to discontinue that contract,'' Alex Kroll, the ad agency's
chairman and chief executive officer, said in a statement.
   He said Y&amp;R would represent the tourist board until it finds a
new ad agency.
   The tourist board issued its own statement later Thursday in
which it expressed ``shock'' at the timing and content of Y&amp;R's
announcement.
   The tourist board said the ad agency had not notified the board
that it would make such a statement. The board also said it had
notified Y&amp;R on Oct. 10 of its intent to cancel the agency's
account.
   ``The board wishes to emphasize that the decision to terminate
Y&amp;R is a result of the development of an unsatisfactory commerical
relationship between Y&amp;R and the board and is not to be interpreted
as a comment on the accuracy of the allegations reflected in the
indictment,'' the tourist board said.
   The indictment, handed up earlier this month by a federal grand
jury in Connecticut, charges the New York-based agency, two of its
executives and a former executive with racketeering and conspiracy
to violate the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act.
   Jamaica's former minister of tourism and another Jamaican were
charged with accepting the bribes.
   The ad agency and its executives and former executive pleaded
innocent. The Jamaican officials have not appeared in court on the
charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
